report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 25 year old right handed woman with epilepsy since age 16, admitted with recurrent tonic-clonic seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Lamictal
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is described as very drowsy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The drowsy state includes generous beta and low-voltage theta.  Vertex waves appear, as do spindles.  Brief stimulation of the patient produces a brief alerting with theta but sustained wakefulness was not identified.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is drifting in and out of sleep and did not activate the record.
HR:    90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Excessive theta in a drowsy patient.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were seen.  The excessive drowsiness may be due to this patient's medications or sleep deprivation.  She has eye movements into sleep which is not a pathological finding and can be seen in normal as well as well as those with sleep disturbances and depression. Prior EEGs demonstrated parietal spikes.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 49-year-old man with past medical history of traumatic brain injury in 1987 and subsequent seizures, has been seizure-free since 2008.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, lisinopril, hydrocortisone cream.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The alpha rhythm is 7 Hz and the background EEG is slow and low voltage.  There is shifting slowing in bilateral temporal region.  No epileptiform discharges are seen.  Photic stimulation causes some muscle artifact, but no driving.  Hyperventilation causes generalized slowing.
Heart rate is 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Mildly abnormal EEG due to mild background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are no epileptiform discharges identified in this EEG and the mild background slowing can be seen in traumatic brain injury.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 34-year-old woman with a history of seizures as well as kidney disease with  last one 2 months.
MEDICATIONS:  Lipitor, Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness with activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and stage 1 sleep.  Activating procedures including  hyperventilation and photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
HEART RATE:  60.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 23 year old left handed woman with history of seizures and postictal confusion.  Last seizure on January 16, 2012.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Lamictal.
REASON FOR STUDY:  History of seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures, including hyperventilation and photic stimulation, were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some multiple electrode muscle and impedance artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontal central beta seen.  The patient achieves sleep stages 1 and 2. Activating procedures, including photic stimulation and hyperventilation produces no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:      None.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  A normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. Repeat recording with deeper stages of sleep may aid in confirming diagnosis.

HISTORY: 43 year old right handed woman with tonoclonic seizures since age 12 and recurrent seizures, last seizure occurred on 09/26/2010. Also a history of staring spells, absence seizures. The primary seizure type at present is absence epilepsy with nearly daily absence seizure .
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Keppra, Buspar.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This Is an awake through stage 2 sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD The patient appears to be drowsy throughout much of the record. There are some sections in apparent wakefulness where there is a pattern with 7.3 Hz activity in the background and some faster 15Hz activity. There is at times a 10Hz alpha rhythm. As the patient transitions into stage 2 steep with vertex waves, K-complexes and spindles., frontally predominant spike and wave and polyspike and wave activity is Identified at 3 to 5 Hz.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Excess background 7.5 Hz activity and wakefulness.
2. Frontally predominant spike and wave and polyspike and wave activity, identified quite prominently In sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The excess 7.5 Hz activity was not previously described in other records and may be part of this patient's underlying neurologic process or due to underlying sleep deprivation. It does correlate with a faster frequency harmonic also noted in the background. The generalized, polyspike and spike and wave activity has been previously described. No absence seizures were recorded; however, the patient does seem to be quite drowsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 33 year old male with refractory epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Lamictal, ZONISAMIDE, Buspar, Folate Acid, Seroquel, Diazepam,
Clorazepate, Valium
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed In lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a markedly abnormal pattern lacking in the Typical wave forms of an awake adult. It is relatively low voltage and featureless with frequent high amplitude slow spike and wave activity of approximately 2-3 Hz. In addition, there is predominant polyspike activity, focal epileptiform activity in the right hemisphere, frontal central, and some isolated discharges from the left. There is likely 1 seizure in this EEG during photic stimulation, but after the 7 Hz stimulation concludes when the Patient has a burst of alpha frequency activity on the right with head turning to the left.
HR: 96bpm
IMPRESSION: markedly ABNORMAL EEG due to:
1. Absence of normal wave forms for an adult of this age.
2. High amplitude spike and wave activity and polyspike and wave activity.
3. Focal activity more prominent on the right, but seen independently from the left.
4. Seizure in right
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are seen In Lennox-Gastaut type syndrome and are quite typical. Is focal activity and in this EEG, at least, it is a bit more prominent on the right.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  52 year old right handed gentleman with diabetes and hypertension, syncopal event March 3, after taking tramadol, felt lightheaded.  Past history of a prior event which was similar.  In this most recent event, he was unconscious for 5 minutes and was confused afterwards.
MEDICATIONS:  No seizure medications.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz 30 mV posterior dominant rhythm.  In the transition to drowsiness, there is occasional, isolated right or left temporal mixed theta-delta. Hyperventilation produces an increase in rhythmic theta.
Vertex waves and POSTs are identified in sleep which is not sustained.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  The occasional right or left temporal slowing in drowsiness is a nonspecific finding, but can be seen in
those with atherosclerotic disease risk factors.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow-up study with more prolonged sleep can be obtained.

TYPE OF STUDY:  Outpatient EEG.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 37-year-old woman with epilepsy since birth.  Birth and developmental history unknown, but strong family history of epilepsy on her father's side.  Patient also has severe migraines.  She describes her last seizure as screaming, crying, and epistaxis.  Typically, seizures not so severe.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, phenobarbital, Zoloft, Prilosec, Risperdal, Spiriva, albuterol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with 9.5 Hz, 40 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm.  The alpha rhythm reaches 10 Hz, 70 microvolts with occasional posterior slow waves of youth.  Features of drowsiness include attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Hyperventilation does not significantly activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.  Heart rate 72 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  In this individual with lifelong, refractory epilepsy, a follow-up study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 52 year old right handed woman with epilepsy, now with increasing difficulty with word finding.

MEDICATIONS: Metformin, Carbamazepine, Abilify, Cymbalta, Singulair

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm. There is prominent, excessive theta noted in the background. Occasional, medium amplitude left anterior temporal sharp waves are observed. Hyperventilation is performed early on in record. There are some artifacts noted in hyperventilation but no definitive exacerbation of sharps or spikes. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.

HR: 72 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Excess theta.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: Previous EEGs have demonstrated excess theta as well as the left temporal sharp waves. It is difficult to determine if quantitatively there is more theta than noted in prior studies. There are no specific hallmarks of an encephalopathy, and this patient's medications may also contribute to the theta described above.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 29 year old right handed male with refractory epilepsy, Lennox-Gastaut
syndrome, rare, early morning seizures none serious at this time.

MEDICATIONS: Carbatrol, Zonisamide.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. The patient is cooperative.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a dynamic pattern. There are brief sections of the record where the EEG is medium amplitude, reasonably well organized with a 6 hertz background. This is disrupted by bursts of rhythmic, frontally predominant delta. In addition, there is arrhythmic delta activity sometimes identified in the occipital scalp region. There are shifting asymmetries but some of the arrhythmic delta activity is higher amplitude on the left compared to the right. Within the bursts of delta, there are subtle, slow, frontal spike and slow wave complexes. The epileptiform activity is not as prominent as the frontal delta. Hyperventilation produces prominent bursts of delta. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Markedly abnormal background.
2. Frontal spike and slow wave activity.
3. Occipital delta.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are similar to previous studies. No clinical seizures  were identified.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   46 year old woman with history of seizure disorder.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep, stage I.  Activating procedures, including hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient has a normal amount of frontal central beta.  Activating procedures produce no abnormal discharges.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness and stage I sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen intermittently at F7/T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 mV.  At times this slowing is slightly arrhythmic and periodic.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right anterior temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right anterior temporal region, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizure or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 64 year old right handed gentleman with a history of right
subdural hematoma followed by complex partial seizures, also history of intractable
pain.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra, gabapentin, Nifedipine, Levetiracetam, HCTZ

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is noted to have a
previous craniotomy site.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness there is a 9 Hz posterior
dominant rhythm. Superimposed upon this there is an area of focal delta with
arrhythmic mixed theta delta seen in the right to mid to posterior temporal region and
right central parietal region. On rare occasions right temporal sharp waves are noted.
Photic stimulation elicits little in the way of a driving response. Drowsiness is
characterized by an accentuation of the focal slowing, as well as more of a distribution
of the focal slowing in the right posterior quadrant. Hyperventilation seems to
accentuate the focal slowing more in a central temporal or central parietal distribution.

HR: 72bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Right temporal and central temporal focal slowing.
2. Rare right temporal sharp waves.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The focal slowing is much less prominent than it was
years ago. The sharp waves are in the region of his previous craniotomy. Overall, this
study is unchanged compared to prior.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 26 year old right handed female with past medical history of epilepsy, has been seizure free for the past 7 years. This is a follow-up EEG.

MEDICATIONS: Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed In lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized with a 9-Hz posterior dominant rhythm. Hyperventilation produced supraharmonic driving. When the patient closed her eyes, she had some alpha squeaks. There was a single burst of 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity, mostly located frontally predominantly. Patient also demonstrated POSTS in stage 2 sleep.

HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is an abnormal EEG which supports an underlying generalized mechanism of epilepsy.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  21 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 25-year-old man with a history of cognitive impairment and seizures.  He had an episode of shaking and falling that occurred several days ago.
CURRENT MEDICATIONS:  Zonegran, Depakote, and triamterene/hydrochlorothiazide.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of polymorphic poorly formed 8.5 to 9 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  The anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient is present, but fragmented at times.  Additional diffuse polymorphic theta is captured.  During drowsiness diffuse bursts of slow theta and increase in the amount of central beta is observed.  Hyperventilation is performed with poor effort and results in no significant change in the background.  Stepped photic stimulation does not result in additional abnormalities.
FINDINGS:
Mild diffuse slowing and disorganization.
No stage 2 sleep.
No clear epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is a mildly abnormal awake and drowsy 21 minute EEG due to mild diffuse slowing and disorganization.  This finding indicates etiologic nonspecific mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  No epileptiform discharges were captured, however, stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If a clinical indication for seizures persist, a repeat study with stage 2 sleep may be of benefit.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  51 year old right handed woman with syncope and headaches, past history of closed head injury in June 2011.
MEDICATIONS:  HCTZ, Lymphedema, Aspirin, Omeprazole.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz symmetric reactive alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  Central mu activity is noted, but testing is not performed to confirm this. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background and a small amount of slowing. Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements, attenuation of the alpha, and POSTS.
Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving.
HR:    72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features were observed.  Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 27 year old male a history of gunshot wound to the left side of
the skull and chronic daily headaches.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Percocet, Tylenol, Phenytoin, Gabapentin

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The right hemisphere demonstrates a reasonably well-organized background with a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. The left hemisphere demonstrates continuous theta. Hyperventilation accentuates the theta rhythmic data from the left hemisphere. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.

HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Continuous slowing from the hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a structural or functional abnormality on the left involving gray and white matter congruent with the history.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 36-year-old man with a history of seizures since childhood, with no seizures in the last several years.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamotrigine, Topamax, Fosamax, vitamin D, calcium and others.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of well-formed and modulated 9 Hz moderate amplitude alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During drowsiness the posterior dominant rhythm attenuates and symmetrical vertex waves are observed.  Hyperventilation was performed and the results have no significant change in the background.  Stepped photic stimulation results in occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.  A single EKG lead demonstrates a normal cardiac rhythm.
FINDINGS:
No stages of sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy 22 minutes EEG.  When compared to the EEG from 04/25/2008, epileptiform discharges seen over the right posterior temporal region are not captured on this study.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not preclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  If clinical indication for seizures persist, a repeat study with stage 2 sleep may be of benefit.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 49 year old left handed woman with refractory epilepsy, schizophrenia, hypothyroidism.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax, Depakote, Valproic Acid
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is awake.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is poorly organized with excess background theta. There is focal slowing noted in the background, particularly in the right hemisphere, but there is some shifting and slowing from either hemisphere. Discrete T2 sharp waves can be observed which can be differentiated from EKG artifact. Features of drowsiness include an increase in rhythmicity. In drowsiness, there are a handful of sharp waves observed from the left. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response which demonstrates some shifting asymmetries but is a bit better preserved on the left than the right.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Shifting and slowing with focal features from either hemisphere.
3. Right temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison to previous studies, this pattern with primarily right temporal seizures has been seen in her 7 prior EEGs.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 44-year-old with a 1-minute staring spell 2 weeks ago.
Of note, this patient has had many previous EEGs in 2003, 2008 with long-term monitoring, and then followup in 2009.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  Drowsiness is characterized by a small amount of hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing as well as anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.  Rhythmic mid-temporal state of drowsiness was noted.
Hyperventilation produces rhythmic slowing.  Otic stimulation elicits scant driving.
Heart rate:  60 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  A handful of normal variants were noted in this EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 39 year old right-handed woman with a history of epilepsy with myoclonic, tonic clonic, and absence seizures. Recent recurrence of nocturnal seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Cymbalta, Clorazepate
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well
organized with a 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm and a modest amount of 13 Hz beta activity. Posterior slow waves of youth are observed as a Mu rhythm, although testing is not performed to confirm this. Drowsiness is characterized by anterior of the alpha rhythm. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude in the background. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed today. A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  79 year old right handed woman with recent TIA, intermittent delirium.
MEDICATIONS:  Unknown by patient
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is low-voltage.  There is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is intermittent low-voltage theta and delta in what is otherwise a quite low-voltage record.  There are sections of the record where the background is well organized with lambda.  Prominent eye artifact is observed. Photic stimulation functions as an alerting response with symmetric driving.
HR:    60 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Intermittent excess theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The intermittent excess theta is a nonspecific finding and can be seen in the context of a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function such as underlying ischemic cerebrovascular disease or dementia.  No epileptiform features
have been seen in any of her EEGs.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a followup study is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   58 year old right handed gentleman with a long history of epilepsy, currently seizures down to 1 every 3 months.  Previous left central focus during EEG monitoring.  Cerebellar atrophy.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  Both drowsiness and hyperventilation produced an increase in theta.  Vertex waves are noted in stage 1 sleep.  There are minor asymmetries as well as artifact noted in the T3 electrode.  These are apparent in sleep. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is relatively drowsy and/or transitioning in and out of stage 1 and stage 2 sleep.  There is no significant driving response.
HR:    72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are no epileptiform features noted in this record.  Comparison with this patient's previous EEGs prior to 2002 as well as the 2009 and
2003 EEG can be considered, but the records in the Temple database appear to have been normal studies.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 63-year-old woman with previous meningioma, recent increase in seizures in 2012, seizures now occurring with falling and shaking.  Last seizure October 2012.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  The patient was noted to have multiple craniotomy scars.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 8.3 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Minimal drowsiness is characterized anterior in spite of the alpha rhythm.  Photic stimulation elicited subtle driving.  Hyperventilation produced increase in amplitude of the background.  Heart rate 72 BMP.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and limited drowsiness.
Clinical correlation:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy and if seizures are an important consideration, a follow up tracing may be of value.  In comparison to previous studies, the most recent EEG in June 2012, demonstrated right frontal focal slowing.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation only.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin.
HISTORY:  This 60-year-old woman presented with history of seizures, admitted on 7/19/2013 due to two seizures described as tonic-clonic with postictal confusion and tongue biting.  There may be a possibility of alcohol withdrawal and her seizures started five years ago.  The patient states that she is compliant with medication.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a diffuse and excessive amount of frontocentral beta seen throughout diffusely, but mainly frontocentrally.  The patient is recording during wakefulness, stage 1 and stage 2.  Activating procedures include photic stimulation.  There were no abnormal discharges, but photic stimulation did produce some nice photic driving.
Abnormal discharges:  None.
Heart rate:  72.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and asleep EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  Please note that the excessive beta may be due, at least in part, to medication effect, such as the use of benzodiazepines or barbiturates.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 48 year old left handed female with a history of childhood epilepsy with complex partial and generalized seizures typically 2 to 3 seizures a month but last seizures was on the 14th with multiple seizures, previously treated with Dilantin and Topamax.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat slow with excess theta and a poorly defined 9Hz alpha rhythm. Hyperventilation is performed early-on in the record, clearly accentuating rhythmic mixed theta delta from the right temporal region as well as left temporal sharp waves. Following hyperventilation, the sharp waves and the rhythmic slowing gradually abate and the patient becomes somewhat drowsy. Photic stimulation does not significantly activate the record.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Rhythmic theta and delta primarily from the right temporal region.
3. Right temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings were seen in previous EEGs. Of note, only 2 of this patient's previous 11 EEGs were available for review today but the findings are similar in this individual with known, refractory temporal lobe epilepsy and previous, unilateral or bitemporal findings.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 29 year old right handed woman with epilepsy, rare early
morning or nocturnal tonic clonic seizures typically in the context of sleep deprivation.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG
demonstrates a well developed symmetric reactive 9 hertz alpha rhythm reaching 80
microvolts. Occasional, frontally predominant bursts of high amplitude, 3-5 hertz spike
and slow wave activity are identified in wakefulness. They are accentuated in early
drowsiness and by hyperventilation. Bursts are typically frontally predominant and
symmetrical although there are a handful that demonstrate shifting symmetry and rare
bursts that are occipitally predominant. Photic stimulation elicits driving, but does not
seem to accentuate the spike in wave activity.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Frontally predominant 3-5 hertz spike in wave activity.
2. Occasional spike in wave discharge which may be a little bit more asymmetric or
posteriorly predominant
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings have been identified in this patient's
previous EEGs. They are most supportive of a primary generalized mechanism for
epilepsy, but could be seen in a secondary generalized mechanism.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 36 year old right handed male with epilepsy, seizure-free since 1993, but has episodes of trembling in the hands and legs.

MEDICATIONS: Depakote
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm with a modest amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Central mu rhythm is identified but testing is not performed to confirm this. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing an increase in background slowing with a small degree of shifting slowing. Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In contrast to a previous study in 2005, no left central or temporal sharp waves were identified.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 30-year-old woman, with epilepsy, 27 weeks pregnant.  The patient was admitted with a change in mental status.  She had a seizure on the 9th lasting 45 seconds and then another event today, question encephalopathy, question postictal, question behavior.
MEDICATIONS:  Metoprolol, heparin, Keppra, Ativan.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient had been sedated, had a recent seizure and was quite somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The initial sections of the EEG demonstrate a low voltage slow pattern with slow delta.  With stimulation, a scant 8 Hz alpha rhythm was noted.  The technologist was able to awaken the patient for hyperventilation which seems to produce some rhythmic, sharply contoured slowing in the right hemisphere, particularly in the right mid to anterior temporal region.  As the patient becomes drowsy bursts of high amplitude frontal delta were noted.
Photic stimulation did not activate the record.  Heart rate 78 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Abnormal background with a low voltage slow pattern.
Excess theta.
Rhythmic right delta particularly in the right mid temporal region notable with hyperventilation.
FIRDA.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG demonstrates a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function which may be due to a postictal state or medications.  In addition, there are focal features with rhythmic, sharply contoured slowing in the right temporal region.  Based on these findings, EEG monitoring was requested.

EEG REPORT
CLINICAL HISTORY: 41 year old right handed woman with episodes lasting 10-15 minutes with eyes rolling back in head, head turning to the left, confusion, seizure versus nonepileptic seizure.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Phenytoin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Photic stimulation is completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, the background EEG is somewhat abnormal. There is excess theta. There are bursts of slowing. Right frontal temporal sharp waves are noted. There is also some shifting slowing. As the patient becomes drowsy, the asymmetry is a bit more remarkable with focal slowing in the right anterior temporal region and higher amplitude right anterior temporal spike and slow wave complexes. Bursts of sharp waves are noted as the patient transitions into sleep, which are seen first on the right and then on the left. The patient starts to transition into stage sleep. Sharp waves at that point are seen with an unusual field of spread, F8, T4, and then frontal left or right, or with an asymmetry, but with some bilateral representation. Photic stimulation elicits a vigorous driving response.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Abundant epileptiform activity with more than 1 localization.
2. Right anterior temporal sharp waves.
3. Sharply contoured delta from the left mid temporal region.
4. Some bifrontal sharp activity.
CLINICAL This EEG supports a focal mechanism for epilepsy. The
background slowing and the focal slowing may be correlated with imaging.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  54 year old right handed female with history of seizures since childhood that was recently described as left side of the body burning lasting for a second.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with an additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness.  Activating procedures, including hyperventilation and photic stimulation, were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9 Hz only seen over the left hemisphere.  Over the right hemisphere there is attenuation of all frequencies, including beta frequency, which can only be seen over the left hemisphere.  The patient is only recorded during wakefulness.
Activating procedures produce no abnormal discharges.  However, during hyperventilation the patient does start complaining of left arm numbness and pain.  During this time and intermittently there appears to be a change in the EKG lead to what appears to be bigeminy for seconds intermittently.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal attenuation of the entire right hemisphere and disruption of the posterior dominant rhythm seen throughout the recording.
Mild excessive theta in wakefulness, along with bursts of FIRDA in wakefulness.
SEIZURES:  During the recording the patient complained of her left arm hurting, which is consistent with her typical events, but there is no EEG correlate during this event.  The patient did not loose consciousness.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right hemisphere attenuation and disruption of the posterior dominant rhythm in that hemisphere.
Mild generalized slowing.
FIRDA.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cortical dysfunction in the right hemisphere, which is consistent with a known hemiatrophy seen on the right hemisphere for this patient.  In addition, there is evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  The episodes of left arm burning did not have any EEG correlate.  However, please note that up to 75% of simple partial seizures may not be captured during scalp EEG.  Lastly, the patient did have some EKG abnormalities seen throughout the recording.  Due to this the patient was recommended to be seen in the emergency room right after the EEG.  She was taken there for this.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity which seems to be accentuated by drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are similar to previous studies. No sustained spike and wave bursts were noted.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 23 year old right handed male with primary generalized epilepsy.

MEDICATIONS: Topamax

IMPRESSION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are
performed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness the background EEG includes an 11.5 Hz
posterior dominant rhythm with posterior slow waves of youth. In relaxed wakefulness there are brief bursts of frontally predominant 3 to 5 Hz spike in wave activity with bursts typically 1.8 seconds in duration. Most are under 2 seconds and none exceed 3 seconds in duration. Hyperventilation seems to accentuate these bursts. An attempt to test for responsiveness during stimulation is attempted but the bursts are so brief that it is not possible to complete the test before the burst is over. There are no deficits in recall identified during the bursts. On rare occasions as the patient becomes drowsy, some of the bursts are a bit more maximum in the right frontal region. Other features of drowsiness include an increase in beta. Photic stimulation elicits a small amount of bilateral driving, but the spike in wave activity is not accentuated by this.

HR: 66bpm.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Frontally predominant 3 to 5 Hz spike in wave activity.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are more compatible with primary generalized
epilepsy. The presence of a single isolated burst in the right frontal region does not exclude this diagnosis. This individual does not appear to have outgrown his epilepsy at this time.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the record opens, there is a symmetric 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm that is of medium amplitude and is reactive to eye opening.  There was a small amount of frontocentral beta activity that is symmetrically distributed over the frontocentral regions bilaterally.  Throughout the recording, there is intermittent focal slowing noted over the left hemisphere.  This is maximal in the frontotemporal and frontocentral regions.  This is characterized by brief epochs of 5 to 6 Hz theta activity and rare very brief epochs of 2 to 3 Hz low amplitude delta activity.  When this is seen, it does disrupt the integrity of the posterior dominant rhythm on the left.  In addition to the focal slowing, there are sharp transient waves identified over the left frontal region.  These are not frankly epileptiform but are suggestive potentially of actual sharp waves.  There are no electrographic seizures detected and there were no clinical events denoted by the patient.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and did not induce a significant photic driving response.  The heart rate was between 60 and 90 beats during the recording.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG capturing wakefulness through drowsiness due to the presence of focal slowing over the left frontotemporal and frontocentral regions.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The presence of focal slowing may suggest a structural brain lesion in the left hemisphere.  Sharp transient waves are not frankly epileptiform but may be suggestive of an epileptiform discharge over the left hemisphere.  Clinical correlation is suggested.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  23 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 55-year-old man with a history of aneurysmal surgery, left frontal stroke, hemiparesis, and seizures.  EEG is being performed to assess the patient's baseline.
MEDICATIONS:  Current medications include phenobarbital, Dilantin, Prozac, and others.
CONDITION OF RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10/20 system, with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is continuous right to left interhemispheric asymmetry with faster waveforms over the left hemisphere.  Of note, the patient is asleep throughout most of the recording.  During brief wakefulness, the posterior dominant rhythm over the left consists of moderate amplitude 9-10 Hz alpha activity. PGR No comment can be made about reactivity.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient over the left hemisphere.  Additionally, continuous excess beta activity is captured over the left hemisphere.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the right hemisphere is not clearly visualized.  The background during maximal wakefulness over the right consists of a mixture of polymorphic alpha and theta activity.  Additional polymorphic delta activity with paucity of faster frequencies is observed during drowsiness and sleep over the right hemisphere, primarily over the right frontotemporal region.  Intermittent moderate to high amplitude sharp waves with aftergoing slow waves are captured over the right anterior temporal region.  Phase reversal occurs over F8/T4 electrodes.  Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation results in no additional abnormalities.
FINDINGS:
Continuous moderate right hemispheric slowing, most pronounced over the right frontotemporal region.
Excess beta activity observed over the left hemisphere.
Suspected breach artifact over the left hemisphere.
Intermittent sharp waves with aftergoing slow waves over the right anterior temporal region, with phase reversal over F8/T4 electrodes.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal, mostly asleep, very briefly awake EEG due to continuous focal right hemispheric slowing, that is most pronounced over the right frontotemporal region, and intermittent epileptiform discharges over the right anterior temporal region.  These findings indicate likely underlying focal cerebral dysfunction that carries increased epileptogenic potential.  Excess beta observed over the left hemisphere could be secondary to the medication effect such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates. Breach effect could be secondary to a skull defect. Breach effect over that region.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consisted of a well formed and modulated moderate amplitude 9.5 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During drowsiness, the posterior dominant rhythm attenuates but stage II sleep is not achieved.  Intermittent bursts of theta and delta activity are captured over the bitemporal regions.  Activity within these bursts is often sharply contoured; however, no clear sharp waves are observed within these bursts of slowing.  Additionally, there is significant EMG artifact during some parts of the recording and epileptic activity could have been missed as a result of this.
FINDINGS:
No sleep.
Intermittent moderate bitemporal slowing, often sharply contoured.
No clear epileptiform discharges; however, portions of the recording contain significant EMG artifact and epileptiform discharges could have been missed.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and drowsy EEG due to moderate bitemporal slowing that is often sharply contoured.  This finding indicates underlying cerebral dysfunction, possibly structural in etiology.  No clear epileptiform discharges were captured; however, portions of the recording contain significant EMG artifact and epileptiform discharges could have been missed.  If clinical indication for seizures persists, a repeat study with stage II sleep and less artifact could be of benefit.

Focal slow waves seen at T3 intermittently at a frequency of 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 mV.  Two of these patterns had a slightly sharply contoured appearance, but did not appear to be clearly pathologic or epileptiform.
SEIZURES:    None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right hemisphere focal slow waves maximal in the parietal region with additional decreased amplitude in the faster frequencies.
Focal slow waves intermittently seen in the left midtemporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right hemisphere, maximal in the parietal region which is consistent with the known injury and lesion in that region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left midtemporal region, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed In lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates an unusual
pattern. In apparent wakefulness, the activity is a bit slow with a 9 Hz alpha rhythm and
some excess theta appearance. There are paroxysmal bursts of frontally predominant,
sharply contoured irregular delta. Some of the bursts are notched. In fact, there seems
to be a subtle sharp and slow wave complex in the right frontal region in this activity. As the recording continues and the patient is a bit more relaxed, the activity is seen In more prolonged bursts. In addition, there is some sharply contoured discharges from the left frontal region. Photic stimulation does not elicit a driving response and does not clearly alter this frontally predominant paroxysmal activity.
HR: 72bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowing and disorganization.
2. Suspicious, frontal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral
function. The paroxysmal bursts can be seen in a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy,
but they could also be in a frontal lobe process, hydrocephalus or other disturbance.
Suspicious sharp waves are noted.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is poorly responsive but this study does include wakefulness and sleep.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is markedly abnormal and lacks all of the developmental milestones for an adult of this age. The overall background is one of theta with lower voltage slow frequency activity. Superimposed upon this there are occasional high amplitude sharp waves picked up with a generous field of spread which are primarily in the left central regions but are picked up bilaterally. When the patient drifts off to sleep, there is an increase in beta. Posteriorly predominant slow activity is noted.

HR: 96 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Replacement of the normal background with more of a beta frequency pattern with slower delta.
2. High amplitude left central spike and sharp wave activity with a generous field of spread. Sometimes this has a polyspike component
3. Occasional posteriorly predominant slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function, but the epileptiform activity came from the left.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 34-year-old female, who presents with a history of generalized tonic-clonic seizures for many years.  This is a followup EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 7-8 Hz in frequency seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is presence of low-amplitude diffuse beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  There is 6-7 Hz excess theta activity during wakefulness.  Stage 1 sleep is characterized by disappearance of the posterior dominant rhythm, slowing of the background and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and posts. Stage 2 sleep is characterized by presence of k- complexes and sleep spindles. There are occasional bursts of right temporal and central slowing, most pronounced in mid temporal region at T3 during wakefulness and sleep mixed with sharply contoured delta waves lasting for 1-3 seconds with no evolution.  During wakefulness and sleep, there are occasional bursts of generalized spike and wave discharges seen appearing with a frequency of 2.5-3 Hz, which were frontally predominant.  These occurred in bursts lasting from 1-3 seconds.  There was no clinical seizure correlate during these bursts.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response without any photoparoxysmal response.  Hyperventilation was performed and resulted in diffuse slowing of the background activity.  Heart rate was 72 beats per minutes.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through stage 2 sleep, due to:
Generalized spike and slow wave discharges seen during wakefulness and sleep with a frequency of 2.5-3 Hz with no evolution.
Disorganized background
Excess theta activity during wakefulness and slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm.
Right central and mid temporal slowing mixed with sharply contoured wave discharges.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm and excess theta activity are consistent with encephalopathy, which could be due to toxic, metabolic, infectious, medication induced, degenerative, postictal, or bilateral cerebral dysfunction. Occasional bursts of frontally predominant generalized spike and slow wave discharges and right central and temporal slowing and sharply contoured delta waves are consistent with underlying epileptogenicity with multiple foci. The generalized beta activity could be due to medication effect including benzodiazepine, barbiturate, or could be due to anxiety or hyperthyroidism. Clinical correlation and repeat EEG or prolonged EEG monitoring for further evolution is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 71-year-old woman with a history of cryptococcal meningitis who remains in unexplained coma.  An EEG is performed to rule out status epilepticus.
MEDICATIONS:  Lopressor, prednisone, Lovenox, metoprolol, and Protonix. The patient is not getting Versed.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to standard 10/20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single-EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The background consists of approximately 3 second bursts of variable amplitude polymorphic delta activity.  Bursts of activity are generally poorly formed over the right.  Inter-burst interval last approximately 4-7 seconds on average, thus making burst suppression ratio approximately 1:1 to 1:3.  No normal sleep architecture is captured.  Independent bursts of polymorphic sharply contoured fast activity are captured over the left posterior temporal/posterior quadrant.  Four electrographic seizures are captured.  These seizures all differ electrographically.  The seizures occurred at approximately 11:48 a.m., 11:51 a.m., 12:03 p.m., and 12:38, and last approximately 1 minute 39 seconds, 1 minute 23 seconds, 1 minute 15 seconds, and approximately 3 minutes and 16 seconds, respectively.  First electrographic seizure starts with moderate amplitude sharply contoured fast activity emanating from the left posterior temporal region.  This activity rapidly evolves into approximately 2.5 Hz rhythmic delta that increases in amplitude and decreases in frequency and spreads to the bilateral occipital region.
Seizure number 2 starts over the left lateral leads either over the left posterior temporal region or left anterior temple region.  Seizure starts with a low amplitude discrete spikes with after-going slow waves that rapidly increase in frequency into the alpha range (approximately 11 Hz activity) and spread throughout the left temporal region and bilateral occipital regions.  This activity gradually decreases in frequency and increases in amplitude, and spreads throughout the left hemisphere.  By the end of the seizure, the seizure is characterized by approximately 1 Hz 0.3 second bursts of moderate amplitude, rhythmic, alpha activity.
Seizure number 3 is similar in appearance and evolution to seizure number 2, however, it starts over the right temporal region.
Seizure number 4 appears to start over the right anterior temporal/mid temporal region.  It starts with a 5 Hz small amplitude sharp waves with after-going slow waves that rapidly decrease in frequency.  As the seizure progresses it appears to stop over the right temporal region and start over the left posterior temporal region.  As the seizure progresses it is similar in appearance to seizure number 1.
There is no clear clinical correlation with any of the patient's seizures.  There is no clear reactivity to either noxious, tactile, or verbal stimuli.  An irregular heart rate is noted in the single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:
Burst suppression, with burst suppression ratio of approximately 1:1 up to 1:3.
Near lack of clear bursts over the right temporal region.
Four discrete electrographic seizures that differ in appearance and emanate from either left posterior temporal region, left anterior temporal region, and right anterior temporal region.
No clear evidence of reactivity.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal nearly 24-minute coma EEG due to  1:1 to 1:3 burst suppression, poorly formed bursts over the right temporal region, and 4 discrete electrographic seizures that differ electrographically and that arise from at least 3 distinct cerebral regions.  These findings indicate significant cerebral dysfunction  and if the patient is not sedative medications indicate a poor prognosis of a full neurological recovery.  These findings were conveyed to the Neurology consultant team at that time of the review.  The patient will be converted to the long term monitoring.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  Approximately 22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 56-year-old man with a past medical history of a left craniotomy for aneurysms and stroke, who now presents with episodes of left arm numbness followed by twitching that lasts approximately 5 minutes with onset about 2 to 3 months ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Gabapentin.
INTRODUCTION:  Activation procedure of hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  EEG was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and single EKG leads.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated 9-10 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  During drowsiness increase in the amount of theta and vertex waves are evident.  Sleep architecture is more prominent over the left hemisphere.  Occasional bursts of delta and theta activity are captured over the left hemisphere.  Additional faster frequencies over the left central occipital region captured consistent with breach artifact.  Hyperventilation increases the amount of slowing observed over the left hemisphere.  Photic stimulation results in appropriate occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.  No epileptiform discharges are captured.  Heart rate less than 60 beats a minute is occasionally observed in a single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:
Occasional mild left hemispheric slowing.
Breach primarily over the left central occipital region.
Asymmetry of sleep architecture with sleep architecture better formed over the left hemisphere.
No stage II sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal 22 minute EEG due to intermittent mild left hemispheric focal slowing.  This finding indicates underlying cerebral dysfunction that in this case is consistent with the patient's history of aneurysm and a left craniotomy. Breach effect is observed with an underlying skull defect.  No epileptiform discharges are captured.  Stage II sleep is not recorded.  If a clinical suspicion of epilepsy still persists a repeat study with sleep may be of benefit.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

Brief arousals produce eye opening and scant alpha activity and then the patient  transitions back to a drowsy state with theta and generous beta.
Heart rate 78 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG primarily in drowsiness.

No previous EEGs are available at this time for comparison.  A previous study on June 14, 2006, may be utilized for comparison.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 38 year old woman with a history of a left temporal ganglioglioma status post resection in 2009, with seizures in the past 7 months described as having eye twitching.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode. TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  The patient easily and rapidly goes into stage 2 sleep in less than 10 seconds and activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen continuously T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-70 microvolts in addition a breach rhythm seen in that region.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing and breach rhythm in the left midtemporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left midtemporal region, which is consistent with a known surgery and tumor resection.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  Please note that the patient did appear to easily go to sleep during the recording and clinical consideration for a sleep study is warranted.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 57 year old right handed male with status epilepticus earlier this morning status post 10 mg of Ativan, Dilantin, and Keppra. History of cervical myelopathy. Intubated and paralyzed prior to the EEG.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Keppra, Ativan, Etomidate, Fentanyl, Versed, ROCURONIUM
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is starting to emerge from paralysis and demonstrates stiffening and movements.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, the patient is a bit quieter. Activity demonstrates a slow pattern with some rhythmic mixed theta and delta on the left with a lower voltage, slower, a bit more suppressed pattern on the right, particularly in the temporal regions.
Stimulation of the patient clearly produces an alerting with an increase in muscle as well as alpha and theta frequency activity. During the EEG, the patient starts to wake up, move around, and cough. After this, there is a more alert pattern with more theta frequency and alpha frequency activity from the left, but the right remains quite slow. By the end of the record in this very sharply contoured record, there was a suggestion of underlying sharp activity versus part of the fast activity at F3. In addition, more sharply contoured slowing is seen at T4-T6.
HR: 84 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Nearly continuous focal slowing on the right hemisphere.
2. Occasional T4-T6 sharps and question F3 sharps as well.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe, bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function as would be expected following the use of sedative, hypnotic medications. The focal slowing and rare sharp waves on the right are compatible with past right temporal hemorrhage. Additional evaluation of this patient's cerebral function may be needed. Ongoing EEG monitoring was undertaken to make sure no additional seizures occurred.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 69-year-old man with a history of recurrent pituitary tumor.  He had one seizure in 2004, subsequently pituitary tumor removal.  He now presents with a second seizure.  The seizure is  characterized by headache, body shaking with several second loss of consciousness.  The patient is aware of his seizure.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated 10 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During sleep, symmetrical POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep), vertex waves and sleep spindles are captured.  Hyperventilation is performed with variable effort and does not result in a significant change in the background.  Step photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.  A single EKG lead demonstrates a heart rate of fewer than 60 beats a minute with occasional premature QRS complexes.
FINDINGS:
Stage 2 sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
Bradycardia and occasional premature QRS complexes.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep 27-minute EEG.  Lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine EEG does not preclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes. TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some CZ electrode artifact.

The patient is recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures were performed. ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  During the recording, there are various bursts of generalized slowing at 2 to 4 Hz; however, intermixed with this slowing there are discrete bursts of well-formed generalized spikes and waves at a frequency of 4.5 to 5 Hz with a very high amplitude of about 80 to 100 microvolts. Bursts of generalized spike and wave.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  58 year old left handed man with intractable epilepsy status post VNS stimulators presents for seizure classification.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Topamax, Lacosamide
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous digital video 24 hours monitoring EEG was performed at bedside for 20 hours using the standard 10-20 electrode placement syndrome with additional arterial, temporal, and EKG electrodes.  Continuous seizure detection software as well as bi-detection software was utilized and supplemented by a patient-activated alarm, nursing observation, and testing.  The video/EEG files were reviewed on a daily basis.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-formed posterior dominant rhythm at 9 to 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening with a normal frontocentral beta.  All sleep stages are captured.  For the first 20 minutes, photic stimulation and hyperventilation were performed with no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Bursts of generalized spikes and waves seen at 4 to 4.5 Hz with anterior predominance and bursts of 1 to 3 seconds.  At times, the bursts seem to have a right frontal leading and at times a left frontal leading, but mainly they are symmetric.  No other focal spikes were seen.
SEIZURES:  [captured or patient event captured]:  No seizure events or patient events were captured during this first day of recording.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Bursts of generalized spikes and waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The findings in this recording are consistent with a diagnosis of idiopathic generalized epilepsy.  Although some of the bursts are asymmetric, no clear focality can be seen to suggest a primary focal lesion with secondary bilateral asynchrony.  No seizures were captured so far in the recording.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 60 year old right handed woman with multiple problems including past history of aneurysmal clip craniotomy, subdural hematoma subarachnoid hemorrhage now with contusion and right hemiparesis. CT demonstrates chronic ischemic changes.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is relatively drowsy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the recording begins, despite a some hat drowsy state, there is a 9.5 hertz alpha rhythm identified on the right. The left hemisphere IS remarkable for significant craniotomy defect with some double phase reversing artifact, but otherwise includes essentially continuous arrhythmic delta activity with occasional bursts of more rhythmic 2-5 hertz activity. Most of the delta is in category of 1-2 hertz. Stimulation of the patient is associated with arousal and an increase in beta frequency activity bilaterally. On occasion, there is a bit more rhythmic periodic 3-5 hertz activity on the left at T3 and T5. There is some sections with an increase in beta.
HR: 72bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Continuous focal slowing from the left hemisphere.
2. Rhythmic 3-5 hertz activity at T3-T5.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The continuous arrhythmic delta activity is compatible with structural disturbance. The rhythmic 3-5 hertz activity may represent an underlying epileptiform focus. If there are any additional concerns, a follow up study may be helpful to determine whether or not these focal features improve as the patient's mental status improves.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 62yo man with a history of Lung Cancer, S/P Resection, TIA, ITP, with recent TIA vs CPS
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, aspirin, hydroxyurea, Prilosec, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with an additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated moderate amplitude 10-10.5 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  This AP gradient is better formed over the right hemisphere.  During drowsiness, posterior dominant rhythm attenuates. There is continuous polymorphic, often sharply contoured, theta and delta activity captured over the left hemisphere.  This slowing is most pronounced over the left temporal region.  Additionally, the amplitude is higher over the left temporal region.  Also, faster frequencies are observed over the left temporal region.  Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.
FINDINGS:
Continuous mild-to-moderate left temporal slowing
A breach over the left temporal region.
No epileptiform discharges.
No stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and drowsy 21-minute EEG due to continuous mild-to-moderate left temporal slowing.  This finding indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, possibly structural in etiology.  Breach artifact is secondary to a skull defect.  No clear epileptiform discharges were captured, however, stage II sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indication for seizures persists, a repeat study with sleep may be of benefit.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 57-year-old man with a history of stroke, right temporal, and seizures, now with recurrent seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Atorvastatin, carbamazepine, omeprazole, lisinopril, and amlodipine.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some electrode artifact, mainly over the left hemisphere, seen continuously.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 to 10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
Abnormal discharges:
Focal sharp waves seen intermittently at F7/T3 during wakefulness and drowsiness, as well as F8/T4, also during wakefulness and drowsiness (slightly more on the left than the right).
Focal slow waves seen at F8/T4 at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts, almost continuously throughout the recording.  In addition, there is some intermittent F7/T3 focal slowing at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and amplitude of 20 to 50 microvolts.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to bilateral anterior temporal sharp waves as well as independent focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from either anterior temporal lobes.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction which is independently seen in both anterior temporal regions, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology.  No seizures were seen.

1. Left anterior temporal focal slowing with destruction of faster frequency activity and rhythmic theta.
2. Left anterior temporal sharp waves.

CLINICAL HISTORY: A 55-year-old woman with asthma, depression, and epilepsy as well as chronic pain, currently seizure free.

Photic stimulation elicited a driving response but spike and wave discharges occurred after, not during the photic stimulation period.
Heart rate 54 BPM.

bursts. Following hyperventilation there is an isolated, very subtle sharp and slow wave
complex again noted in the frontal regions. Features of drowsiness included an increase
in beta. Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 64-year-old male with a past medical history of ruptured aneurysms status post surgery, stroke, and subsequent seizures who has been seizure free for several years. This EEG is a part of an evaluation to stop Dilantin due to liver problems.
MEDICATIONS:  Patient has been on Dilantin, amlodipine, pravastatin, Lasix, metoprolol, and losartan.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital EEG was performed in lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was performed.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is slow with the posterior dominant rhythm of 7-8 Hz through a excess theta activity during wakefulness.  Drowsiness was characterized by more slowing of the background activity and loss of absence of eye blink artifact and muscle artifact.  There is right breach rhythm.  There is also almost continuous right temporal slowing with a frequency of 4.5-5 Hz.  There are occasional bursts of left temporal slowing.  There are intermittent spikes noted with maximum voltage at T4 with no evolutions.  Heart rate was 80 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing. Diffuse background slowing
Right breach rhythm.
Continuous right temporal slowing.
Occasional left temporal slowing.
Spikes T4(Right Temporal) occasionally with no evolution, or seizures.
CLINICAL CORRELATIONS:  Diffuse slowing is indicative of bihemispheric dysfunctions that could be due to infectious, degenerative, hypoxic ischemic, postictal, and toxic metabolic etiologies. Clinical correlation is recommended.  Right breach rhythm could be due to the history of craniotomy in the past. Continuous right temporal slowing could be due to structural lesions in the right temporal region.  The presence of spike in right temporal region is indicative of hyperexcitability of cortex in this area that places this patient at higher risk for partial seizures. Clinical correlation is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 53 year old right handed woman admitted with status epilepticus on August 26, 2010, previous status epilepticus. MRI shows right MTS.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an interhemispheric asymmetry with a 9 Hz alpha rhythm sometimes disrupted on the right in addition, there is some focal slowing from the right hemisphere. In wakefulness there are high amplitude right anterior temporal spike and slow wave complexes and bursts and trains of right anterior temporal sharp waves. Testing is performed including a request for the patient to remember a word during one of these prolonged discharges, which is compatible with an electrographic seizure. The patient is able to remember a word during the discharge.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Right temporal focal slowing.
2. Right temporal spike and slow wave complexes.
3. Bursts of right temporal sharp waves, which at least on 2 occasions are clearly compatible with a focal epileptiform seizure, but without clear clinical correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The patient is more interactive with more eyes opening when she is not having the discharges. Alternative ways of evaluating the patient may include asking the patient to look at visual information rather than verbal memory which remained intact during these events.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 39-year-old woman admitted on the 7th with multiple seizures.  Previous EEG is not available for comparison.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the patient is awake.  The background is diffusely slow with a mixture of theta and smaller amounts of delta.  Occasional, right or left anterior temporal spikes were noted in the background.  There are independent, right or left temporal sharp waves and spikes noted in wakefulness.  There are more noted on the right in comparison to the left.  In addition, the epileptiform activity is at times complex with an extensive field of spread or some variability in terms of maximum at T2 and/or spread to the frontal regions.  As the patient became a bit drowsy, epileptiform activity with the field of spread which included posterotemporal regions and even a polyspike component was noted.  During photic stimulation, there are independent sharp waves or spikes noted.  In addition, during the 3 Hz stimulation, there is a run of rhythmic 4 Hz activity, but without frequency evolution.  Similar activity was not seen on the left.
Heart rate 96 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Complex epileptiform activity with independent sharp waves or spikes noted from either hemisphere typically with a temporal maximum, T1 or T2, but sometimes with a polyspike component or spread to the frontal regions or occipital regions.
An unusual discharge during the 3 Hz stimulation which may have represented a subclinical seizure.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.  The epileptiform activity is more complex than is typically seen in garden variety temporal lobe epilepsy.  There is a polyspike component and a generous field of spread.  In this particular EEG, there is more epileptiform activity on the right.
