INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation is performed.  Technically this EEG is remarkable for a great deal of muscle and motion artifact.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is somewhat poorly organized. There is also a great degree of muscle artifact.  Superimposed upon this are bursts of rhythmic and arrhythmic delta activity in the right hemisphere.   The activity from the right frontal region tends to be rhythmic delta activity.  Underlying sharp waves are noted in this sharply contoured record and include T4/C4 and FP2. Features of drowsiness include additional bursts of paroxysmal high amplitude delta with an underlying right frontal sharp wave.	Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.

HR:   84 bpm

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1. 	FIRDA.
2. 	Paroxysmal slowing in the right frontal region.
3.	Sharp waves from the right, many of which are frontal, but some of which are temporal.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  28 minutes.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single lead EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 58-year-old woman who presents with generalized tonic-clonic convulsions.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of moderate amplitude polymorphic 8-9 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eye opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient that is at times unstable.  Additional diffuse polymorphic theta is captured.  Additional excess diffuse beta is observed.  During sleep phase, sleep spindles and K-complexes are observed.  Intermittent, primarily independent, and rarely synchronous bitemporal moderate to high amplitude sharp waves with after slow waves are captured over the anterior temporal regions.  Phase reversal occurs over F7/T1 and F8/T2 electrodes.  Left temporal epileptiform discharges are more present and more frequent.  Additional intermittent polymorphic theta and delta are captured over the anterior temporal regions.  Hyperventilation was performed with good effort and results in symmetrical diffuse background slowing.  Photic stimulation does not result in additional abnormalities.
FINDINGS:
Mild diffuse slowing.
Excess beta.
Independent greater than synchronous bilateral anterior temporal sharp waves with after going slow waves with phase reversal over F7/T1 and F8/T2 electrodes.  No electrographic seizures.  Additionally, intermittent bitemporal mild to moderate focal slowing.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and asleep 28-minute EEG due to mild diffuse slowing, intermittent mild to moderate bilateral anterior temporal slowing, and intermittent left greater than right independent and synchronous bilateral anterior temporal epileptiform discharges.  Diffuse background slowing indicates etiologic and nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  Focal bitemporal slowing and bitemporal epileptiform discharges indicate focal cerebral dysfunction, with increased epileptogenic potential, structural in etiology.  Excess beta could be secondary to medication effect such as benzodiazepines and barbiturates.

Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:1. A slow and disorganized background.2. Superimposed focal slowing from the left hemisphere. 3. Sharply contoured activity in the left posterior quadrant.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Episodes of unconsciousness.

The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep, stage I and stage II. Activating procedures, including hyperventilation and photic stimulation, were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some frontal temporal electrode artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Heart rate:  84 and regular.
The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz and is reactive to eye opening.  There is a prominent frontal, and mainly central beta, which at times is slightly sharply contoured.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness, stage I and stage II sleep.
Activating procedures were performed.  She has a nice hyperventilation effort with no clear abnormalities and her photic stimulation does not reveal any abnormalities.
Abnormal discharges:  None.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 70 year old right handed gentleman with an episode of loss of
consciousness several months ago, previously treated with Dilantin in 2009. History of
diabetes, hearing loss, and childhood epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Unknown.
Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.
OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 9.5 Hz posterior dominant
rhythm with a small amount of low voltage frontal central beta activity. Drowsiness is
characterized by anterior spread of the alpha rhythm with an increase in theta. There is
some single channel artifact picked up in the right frontal central region as the patient
becomes drowsy. In addition to this single channel artifact, there is a suggestion of
focal, rhythmic frontal theta, which persists throughout photic stimulation. Photic
stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Right frontal theta.
CLINICAL No epileptiform features were observed, but the right
frontal rhythmic theta is sometimes seen in localization related epilepsy. It was not
identified in previous years. Clinical evaluation is suggested. Of note, this patient had
a previous craniotomy with a breech rhythm which might explain the rhythmic theta
discharge.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 65 -year-old woman with 2 previous strokes, right-sided weakness.  The patient had an episode with loss of consciousness and had persistent confusion and cognitive slowing.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Zocor, simvastatin, metoprolol, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was not possible.  Photic stimulation was completed.  This was an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a dynamic pattern. As the EEG begins, the overall pattern is diffusely slow and poorly organized.  There are bursts of high amplitude, generalized transients followed by brief attenuations. In addition, there is a subtle asymmetry with disruption of faster frequency activity on the left compared to the right.  Stimulation of the patient enhances that asymmetry. An alpha rhythm appears on the right of approximately 8 Hz with slower activity on the left.  When the patient is unstimulated, she drifts back into a drowsy pattern. In later portions of the record, this is a lower voltage more featureless pattern.
Photic stimulation was attempted and was complicated by significant photoelectric artifact.  It serve to alert the patient but there was no definitive driving response.  Heart rate 84 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slowing and disorganization.
Focal slowing on the left with disruption of faster frequency activity as well as more slow theta and delta.
Metabolic features with intermittent higher amplitude paroxysmal  discharges followed by attenuation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function but one that involves both gray and white matter on the left, more significantly than the right. No epileptiform features were identified.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  52 year old right handed woman with a 2-year history of epilepsy.  Last seizure August 20, 2011.  Seizures characterized by an aura of a funny taste in her mouth followed by tonic clonic seizures.  Sleepiness.  Depression.  Alcohol abuse.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Seroquel
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates a well-organized pattern on the left with an alpha rhythm of 10 Hz.  On the right, the alpha rhythm is sometimes disrupted.  In the right posterior region, there is a mixture of 2.5 and 4 Hz beta activity.  This is most prominent on the right but is really seen throughout the right central temporal and frontotemporal regions.  Discrete sharp waves and spikes are noted in the right hemisphere.  They have some variability and may be O2 maximum, T6 maximum, or they may start at O2 and transition to T4.  They may occur as couplets.  Drowsiness seems to accentuate the epileptiform activity in the right occipital region.  Hyperventilation also seemed to accentuate both the focal slowing and sharp waves.  Other features of drowsiness include an increase in beta.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:    102 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing in the right hemisphere particularly posteriorly as well as central temporally.
Sharp waves in the right hemisphere with variable maximum most prominently O2 but also T6 and T4.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the fifth EEG for this individual.  Only one of them has been normal and all other EEGs demonstrate epileptiform activity in the same area.  If seizures are not controlled, additional monitoring and intervention may be of value.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  21 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 38-year-old woman with a history of neurosarcoidosis who now presents with an increase in her seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Vimpat, Keppra, Lamictal, Plavix, aspirin, and others.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  The EEG technologist was unable to get all of the impedances under 5 due to a weave present in the patient's hair.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated 10 to 11 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During sleep, POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep), symmetrical vertex waves, sleep spindles, and K complexes are captured.  Hyperventilation is not performed.  Photic stimulation is not performed.  Sinus tachycardia is captured in the single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:
Stage II sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep 21-minute EEG.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 50 year old right handed woman status post left MCA aneurysm repaired in 2003 with annual exacerbation of complex partial seizures and low serum levels.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Keppra,
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is a prolonged study for a patient who appeared to have had a subclinical seizure. She was confused during the EEG and somewhat lethargic.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is markedly abnormal. The background from the right hemisphere is slow and disorganized. The left hemisphere includes a high amplitude breech rhythm with a left frontal sharp and slow complex with arrhythmic delta activity.
At 9:15 the patient is relatively inattentive and the technologist wraps the head. At some point essentially continuous spiking is noted in the left frontal region.
A seizure is identified at 9:19 characterized by evolution of epileptiform activity in the left frontal region, which is high amplitude with a generous field of spread. The seizure duration is from 19:13:30 to 19:19:59 suggesting that this is a relatively brief seizure. The technologist transitions from this to additional recording at 09:21. After the first event with impaired responsiveness, high amplitude left frontal spiking is noted with a breech rhythm in the abnormal background. The patient's mental status actually improves somewhat. She moves about, although she is confused. The activity remains quite slow in both hemispheres.
There was another brief build up again at 9:40. Artifacts are picked up at 9:35, but again there is prominent spiking in the background with very prominent epileptiform activity.
A third electrographic seizure occurs at 9:58:57. The patient is relatively somnolent. Stimulation of the patient does not occur during this testing, but the seizure stops by itself and as it does the patient moves about.
By the morning of the 7th, she is more consistently awake, out of bed with more rhythmic theta frequency in the background although the patterns in both hemispheres are slow.
Throughout the record, there are intermittent bursts of rhythmic delta which do not have a clear clinical correlate.
Seizure: The patient is in bed and she has just off the monitor. Her head is off the monitor. She appears to be sleepy. At  13:35 she was awake and the seizure is 12 minutes later. At 13:44 with the patient with someone at the bedside, in fact a physician examining her, the left frontal delta is prominent as are some sharp waves but she is interactive somewhat with the individual examining her. As the student leaves, the patient drifts over to the right.
The electrographic seizure is at 13:47:13 and the patient is not really moving during the event but starts to reposition afterwards.
This event is characterized by rhythmic, faster frequency activity in the left frontal and temporal region with also a beta accentuation.
After the seizure was over, the patient looks about.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal continuous EEG monitoring due to:
1. Well-defined electrographic seizures noted but with only one seizure In the last 24 hours of recording.
2. Left frontotemporal focus.
3. Focal slowing from the left.
4. Generalized background slowing quite marked in the beginning of the record but better at the close of the record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is diagnostic of a localization-related
mechanism for epilepsy. Additional recording may be appropriate if this patient's mental status does not improve.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with anterior temporal and single lead electrocardiogram electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, rifampin, simvastatin, evase (?), lisinopril, metformin, gabapentin, glipizide, ranitidine, carbamazepine, calcium.
HISTORY:  This is a 59-year-old woman with a history of epilepsy as well as childhood seizure and a previous craniotomy, left occipitoparietal craniotomy here with an EEG due to recurrent seizures.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some T3 and A2 electrode artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to diffusely slow background, however, in the limited wakefulness, she has a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontocentral beta.  The patient does appear to go into stage I deeper stages and stage II deeper stages of sleep.  However, the architecture is slightly atypical.
Activating Procedures:  Specifically, hyperventilation accentuate the abnormal discharges which I will describe in the next paragraph.  However, photic stimulation produces no abnormal discharges.
Abnormal Discharges:
Focal sharp waves seen at T3, at times at T5 and sometimes at 01 occurring during sleep mainly, but sometimes during  wakefulness.
Focal sharp waves seen intermittently at T4.
Focal slow waves seen frequently at F7-T3, at T3, at T5 and at O1 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.   There is increased amplitude and increased frequency consistently with a breach rhythm over that region.
Focal slow waves seen at T4 intermittently at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
Please note that the focal slowing at times occurs in burst lasting up to 5-6 seconds that appear to be very high amplitude and with intermixed sharp waves specifically over the left hemisphere.
Heart Rate:  84, regular.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left posterior quadrant sharp waves and frequent focal slowing associated with breach rhythm as well as right mid temporal sharp waves and focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural dysfunction and irritability in the left posterior quadrant, which is consistent with a known lesion in that region.  In addition, there is evidence of right mid temporal focal cerebral dysfunction and irritability which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  Overall, this EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with multiple roci of irritability.  No clear seizures were seen during this recording.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 hertz alpha rhythm.
Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing an increase in background slowing. In addition, the breach rhythm and focal slowing from the left hemisphere particularly frontocentral and frontotemporal is noted. There is also some shifting slowing. CLINICAL HISTORY: 36 year old right handed male with childhood epilepsy, currently experiencing seizures described by a funny feeling in his body lasting minutes. He also reports tonic clonic seizures, profound psychiatric impairment.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is a 1-hour EEG. Photic stimulation and hyperventilation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the overall background EEG is reasonably well organized with a 10.3 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of shifting slowing. Notable in this record are just prior, during, and after hyperventilation are bursts of high amplitude frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike and slow wave complexes. These are high amplitude, frontally predominant, symmetric, and typically occur in bursts lasting 2 seconds, but up to 3 seconds. They are symmetric, bifrontal, with a polyspike component. Features of drowsiness include vertex waves. K-complexes are noted in stage 2 sleep. Dyshormia is noted as the patient transitions into sleep. In the transition to and from sleep there is some isolated high amplitude or more subtle spike and wave complexes also observed.
Photic stimulation is remarkable for a driving response. In addition, just following 11 Hz spike and wave activity and in the intermediate/frequencies, such as 17 Hz, spike and wave activity is observed.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Frontally predominant spike and wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is significantly different from the initial EEG November 4, 2009 which did not identify generalized spike and wave activity. In that study, hyperventilation was not performed. This EEG is much more supportive of a generalized and focal mechanism for epilepsy. It is also different in that there is no generalized background slowing noted today.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There are bursts of theta on the left but occasionally during drowsiness is seen bilaterally. He does reach an alpha rhythm of 10.5 Hz on the right. He has episodes of 3 to 4 Hz slowing, predominantly in the left temporal region. As the patient becomes sleepy during the exam, there are bilateral changes with alpha rhythm on the right but is not seen on the left. Also positive WICKETS. Photic stimulation does trigger driving of the record. Again, hyperventilation does increase amplitude and accentuates theta bilaterally, left greater than right.

HR: 72 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Left 3 to 4Hz pattern, TIRDA; the TIRDA is accentuated in hyperventilation and drowsiness.
2. Disruption of the alpha rhythm in drowsiness.
3. WICKETS.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: There is no actual epileptiform activity. However, with the presence of sustained TIRDA, this is suggestive of a left focus in the temporal region and although TIRDA is not seizure activity, it is associated with a temporal lobe epilepsy. Further clinical correlation is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 38 year old gentleman status post slab injury and acute trauma on May 9th. Episode of cardiac arrest in the trauma bay with shaking. Evaluate for myoclonus.

MEDICATIONS: Versed, Dilantin, Ciprofloxacin, Flagyl

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. The patient is intubated and febrile as described above. Current body temperature 103.8.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG does demonstrate a preserved cerebral pattern. There is low to medium voltage, mixed frequency primary theta frequency activity of 5.4 hertz, but there is also some 3.5 hertz delta activity and smaller amounts of beta. In this video study, the patient is postured with his head looking to the right. The big EEG machine and video camera are on the left. The camera demonstrates intermittent jerking of the chest and this correlates with some muscle artifact seen diffusely through the EEG. The brief jerks of muscle artifact are not clearly associated with epileptiform activity. There is a suggestion of a vertex sharp wave seen independently of the jerks and on 1 or 2 occasions, as the recording continues, there does appear to be a slow wave that follows some of the jerks. There is a small degree of discontinuity.

HR: 144 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. A primarily theta/theta delta pattern following cardiac arrest.
2. High amplitude myoclonic jerks, but some of these seem to have an after going slow wave.
3. Vertex sharp waves.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The presence of an after going slow wave would suggest that the myoclonus is epileptiform in nature. Additional intervention may be appropriate.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Hypoxic respiratory failure and change in mental status.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 33-year-old man status post motor vehicle accident in 2009, paraplegic with tracheostomy and requiring oxygen, who complains of shortness of breath, found to have hypoxic respiratory failure secondary to a mucous plug, and a witnessed episode of left upper extremity jerking with eye blinking for 1 minute that resolved spontaneously.
PAST MEDICAL HISTORY:  In addition to the above, end-stage renal disease, DVT, PE, and an IVC filter on anticoagulation.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilaudid, pantoprazole, Coumadin, Keppra, baclofen, gabapentin, gentamicin, cefepime, vancomycin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrodes.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 8 Hz.  There is some frontal central beta at times.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness but has some architecture seen in sleep, stage I.  Overall, the background has moderate slowing in the delta/beta frequencies and has intermittent bursts of generalized slowing, which I will describe in the abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen intermittently at T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.
Mild to moderate generalized slowing at 4 Hz and at a frequency of 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts seen continuously throughout the recording.  Please note that at times he has bursts that may last up to 10-12 seconds of frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA).
HEART RATE:  90.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to mid temporal focal slowing as well as mild to moderate generalized slow waves with FIRDA.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right mid temporal region in addition to mild to moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or clear epileptiform discharges are seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 48 year old male with a 26 year history of HIV disease, stroke many years ago, refractory complex partial epilepsy.
MEDICATION: Keppra, Dilantin, Lacosamide, ASA, Truvada, Kaletra, Valacyclovir, Raltegravir, Famotidine, Megestrol, Diovan, Lovenox
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is confused.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates an interhemispheric asymmetry. There is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm on the right. The right hemisphere demonstrates generous beta, a small amount of disorganization, and excess theta. The left hemisphere includes a great deal of muscle and motion artifact, but includes nearly continuous arrhythmic delta activity with sharp waves mixed in. In addition to the sharp waves, there are features that suggest that this is an ongoing, ictal pattern, and that the activity in the left mid temporal region waxes and wanes. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta frequency activity. The record has ongoing sharp waves and rhythmic mixed theta delta, but not the same frequency evolution as when the patient started to become sleepy. He is awakened for photic stimulation. Again, there is a bit more rhythmic theta and the sharp waves. No definitive photic driving is noted.
HR: 150 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Nearly continuous, rhythmic sharp waves, rhythmic theta from the left anterior temporal region.
2. Focal slowing from the left anterior temporal region.
3. Excess beta from the right.
4. Mildly disorganized on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a highly epileptogenic focus. Additional evaluation to make sure that this is an ongoing ictal pattern is suggested.

Right anterior temporal and midtemporal sharp waves.

Mild generalized slowing.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. The patient is intubated, but is responsive
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG includes a mixed frequency pattern. It is disorganized and both hemispheres are abnormal. In addition, there is shifting asymmetry. On some occasions, the activity is a bit better organized on the left and on others on the right. The alpha rhythm can be seen at 8.3 hertz. In addition, there is a left posterior temporal sharp wave observed as well as prominent shifting arrhythmic delta activity identified from either hemisphere. The activity in both hemispheres is sharply contoured and although there is some artifact, there is also suggestion of a T4 sharp wave not well evaluated by this study nor well defined sharply contoured delta at T3. Using alternative montages, the sharp activity does seem to be a bit more 01 than T3 or T5.
HR: 160 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowing and disorganization.
2. In the sharply contoured record, primarily a left posterior sharp.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is most supportive of a focal mechanism for epileptic procedures. If additional information is needed, a follow up study as this patient improves may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 31 year old woman with cerebral palsy, refractory epilepsy, seizure-free for the past 4 years until she had a tonic-Donnie seizure 1 month ago followed by multiple seizures. Past history of stroke and epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1. channel of EKG. The patient is awake. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG Is markedly abnormal with
primarily a theta frequency background. There are bursts of generalized spike and wave and slow spike and wave activity. 'The bursts are typically 3 to 5 seconds in duration. There is also some more restricted frontally predominant spike and wave activity, a little more at the midline. Focal epileptiform activity is also observed including CZ, C3, and left anterior temporal. What appears to be generalized paroxysmal fast activity of approximately alpha frequency is noted. The patient drifts off to sleep with vertex waves and in sleep there seems to be ongoing slow spike and wave activity. In the transition to sleep, felt parietal sharp waves are noted. Photic stimulation does no activate the record.
HR: 60 to 70 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1, Abnormal background.
2, Slow spike and wave activity with variable maximum, sometimes a bit more prominent in the left parietal region.
3. Focal epileptiform activity.
4. Background slowing and disorganization.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are relatively characteristic in individuals with a Lennox-Gastaut type syndrome in terms of epilepsy. They are associated with cognitive impairment and typically more refractory epilepsy with multiple seizure types. These findings observed today were not associated with clinical changes but if there are additional questions, additional EEG recording may be obtained. Correlation with the patient's imaging and anti epileptic drug levels is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 52 year old right handed mate with head trauma, epilepsy, evaluate for 2-3 days.
Change in mental statue.
Dilantin, Depakote, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode
placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. The patient Is
agitated during the EEG and receives Ativan.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, the background is a bit slow when the patient
becomes agitated, he wakes up and there is a prominent 12. hertz alpha rhythm noted bilaterally.
Approximately 10 seconds Into the arousal state with the bilateral alpha as the patient becomes agitated,
more rhythmic4-5 hertz activity emerges from the left central and parietal regions. The behavior of of the
patient is difficult to observe because the caregiver is trying to restrain the patient. The patient is
described as agitated and poor1y responsive by the caregiver during the seizure. He seems to have
looked to his right during the seizure although the caregiver approaches from the left obscuring the view.
A second seizure occurs and again Is characterized by first a somewhat slow background and then in this
case at 16:56:05, a burst of bilateral fast activity following the appearance of the theta on the left at
16:56:11 and then as this occurs, there is more fast activity bilaterally, more clear evidence of a breach
with higher amplitude fast activity more so on the left than the right and then more definitive frequency
evolution is noted at 16:57:11 as the patient postures through to the right with head turning to the right
and what seems like a decorticate or dystonic posturing of the right hand more so than the left. He also
has some irregular respirations and then some clonic activity. There is a problem with the EEG and the
EEG stops recording although the video continues through the end of the seizure. The technologist
attempts to fix the EEG problems while the patient seems to have had a 3rd seizure during the EEG. A
4th event is noted at 17:04:44 again with the patient turning to the left and this seems to merge onto a 5th
at0:07.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Complex partial status epilepticus characterized by recurrent seizures from the left hemisphere
although they do begin with some bilateral fast activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 36 year old right handed woman with new onset seizures characterized by right leg jerking movements and unresponsiveness. History of anxiety disorder. First ever seizure on 9/29/2010.

MEDICATIONS: None.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient reports feeling anxious at the start of the study. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the background EEG opens, the patient has generous background beta. There is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm with rhythmic activity in the right temporal region. For some reason, there is a pause in the EEG at the beginning of the record. The patient is staring forward. When the EEG resumes at 1:27:01, there is artifact, but the minute that the artifact stops, the EEG demonstrates a clear, high amplitude, right anterior temporal seizure with 4 to 5 Hz activity in the right temporal region with an admix spike.

The activity is extremely high amplitude with a phase reversal at F8 and T2. The activity ends abruptly at 1:38:56. The overall duration of the seizure appears to be approximately 3 minutes but the seizure onset is unclear. By the end of the seizure, the activity is involving the right frontal region and also the midline and to a lesser extent the left frontal region.

Immediately afterward, the patient is able to answer questions but is amnestic for the event. Following the seizure, occasional arrhythmic delta activity is seen in the right temporal region with a complex. The patient drifts into stage II sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, spindles and posts. The patient is in stage II sleep during photic stimulation.

HR: 72 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Complex partial seizure from the right temporal region.
2. Right temporal sharp waves.
3. Rhythmic slowing from the right temporal region noted prior to the seizure.

Please note that this report is likely different than previous, where focal slowing has been seen.  This may be due to overall diffuse cerebral dysfunction and medication effect.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 53-year-old man with history of stroke with left sided weakness with recent increase in seizure frequency described as sudden body jerks 3-5 times per day.
MEDICATIONS:  Folic acid, levetiracetam, aspirin, Crestor, carbamazepine, lisinopril.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Posterior dominant rhythm reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontal central beta seen best over the left hemisphere.
Activating procedures, including photic stimulation, produce no abnormal discharges.  Some drowsiness and stage 1 sleep could be seen.
Heart rate:  72.
Abnormal discharges:
Frequent sharp waves are seen at F8/T4 with a field that sometimes goes to F4.  At the same time sharp waves are also seen at F7/T3 with also a frontal field at times that may even spread to FP1.
Focal slow waves are seen over the entire right hemisphere with associated attenuation which appears to be maximal at F8/T4 with a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20 mV.
Focal slow waves are also seen over the left hemisphere at F7/T3 intermittently at a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to right frontal temporal and more than left frontal temporal sharp waves, as well as right hemispheric focal slowing with intermittent left anterior temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures possibly arising from either frontal temporal regions.  In addition, there is evidence of focal structural cerebral dysfunction over the right hemisphere maximal in the anterior temporal region consistent with a known stroke.  Lastly, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures were seen.
Note:  The previous EEG that was performed on 11/11/2010 revealed some of the right temporal sharp waves, but also some generalized frontally predominant spike or wave which appeared to be maximum on the left which was not clearly seen today.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient had a seizure just prior to the EEG.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: This EEG demonstrates some low voltage, subtlety discontinuous background. Some attenuation of about 3 seconds are interspersed with periods of low voltage, mixed theta delta. As the recording continues, the EEG is more continuous. There is some shifting asymmetries with more attenuation on the left compared to the right.

Seizure: The patient is in the ICU at the bedside. She starts to have rhythmic mixed theta delta out of the left hemisphere, particularly the temporal region at 10:36:43. This gradually builds up, but at 10:36:55 she starts to have a burst of fast activity out of the right hemisphere. The bursts of fast activity builds up exquisitely, while the left hemisphere as a different frequency of activity with rhythmic delta. This is followed by more of a generalized pattern characteristic of more of a tonic clonic pattern, although behaviorally the patient is only observed to be having facial and head twitching. The activity starts to slow at 10:37:41. As it stops, it shuts off at 10:38 on the right, but continues on the left before terminating abruptly at 10:38:20. Postictally there is prominent background suppression as was noted in the early portions of the record.

HR: 162 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. A markedly abnormal background starting out with burst suppression pattern and actually ending with a burst suppression pattern.
2. A very complex seizure, which likely began on the left, generated to the right, with different frequencies of activity from the different hemispheres and a differential termination of the procedure.
3. Following the seizure there are handful of sharp waves on the left.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe underlying encephalopathy, as well as very unusual mechanism for epilepsy. This seizure pattern is more typical of a chronic epilepsy than acute reactive seizure.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. The patient is poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a slow and disorganized pattern. The overall pattern is a mixture of delta and theta frequency activity. Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in muscle artifact.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Slow and disorganized background.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are nonspecific and can be seen in a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function. The prominent rhythmicity of the background particularly at the end when the theta frequency activity increases more toward a 6 Hz pattern which is compatible with a chronic dementing illness, but, again, the findings are nonspecific.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  58 year old right handed woman with history of epilepsy who stopped taking her medication now presents for recurrent seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Mirtazapine, Lisinopril, Hydrochlorothiazide, Oxcarbazepine, Naproxen.
REASON FOR EEG:  History of seizures
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with anterior temporal and EKG electrodes. Wakefulness and sleep was recorded. Activating procedures with photic stimulation and hyperventilation were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9 Hz with low amplitude 20-60 microvolts, which is reactive to eye opening. There is normal central beta. Sleep, stage 1 architecture is seen. Activating procedures, including photic stimulation and hyperventilation does not reveal abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen independently at F7/T3 and F8/T4 frequently at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-70 microvolts. Some of the discharges, specifically the ones on the right, have a suspiciously sharp contour but are not clearly epileptiform.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
independent bilateral anterior temporal focal slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of independent bilateral anterior temporal cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology. No seizures nor epileptiform discharges were seen. Please note, that more prolonged recording may aid in eliciting epileptiform discharges.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 27 year old right handed male with epilepsy since childhood. The patient previously on Depakote but not on medicines at this time. History of childhood epilepsy with strong family history of epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: None
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for an adult of this age with an 11 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing an increase in amplitude of the background and a small amount of slowing. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta and an increase in theta. Brief vertex waves are noted but sleep is not sustained. There is a burst of fast activity seen in the transition to sleep but no definitive spike and wave activity. POSTS are also noted in sleep. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed in this record, however, a normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. In this individual who may have an inherited, childhood epilepsy, a repeat study with some sleep deprivation, fasting and additional hyperventilation and photic stimulation may be necessary to bring out generalized spike and wave activity.

There is a fair amount of head rocking artifact in the right posterior quadrant, but this does not otherwise preclude the interpretation of this record. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a more prolonged sleep study may be considered.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 39-year-old female with uncontrolled right hand shaking, as well as seizure disorder 20 years ago, follow-up EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, gabapentin, clorazepate, quetiapine, hydroxyzine, oxycodone, alprazolam, Ventolin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 8 Hz which appears to be somewhat reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.  In general, the background appears to be disorganized and appears to be polymorphic including bursts of delta that at times are more focal in the bilateral temporal regions and sometimes in the central regions.  Overall, the background is in the theta range of slowing 5-7 Hz, although at times it becomes even more slow at 2-4 Hz.  Patient does appear to have some normal sleep architecture in stage 1 sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz with intermittent bursts of 2-4 Hz diffuse delta.
Focal slowing in both F7/T3 and F8/T4 and at times more centrally at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to generalized slowing as well as independent bitemporal as well as some central focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction seen independently in the bilateral temporal region as well as the central regions as well as generalized cerebral dysfunction, both of which are nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year old right handed gentleman with lightheadedness, syncope, diabetes, asthma, hepatitis B and a sleep disturbance.
MEDICATIONS: Metformin, Lovenox, Protonix, Metformin, Lisinopril, Novolin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Photic stimulation is performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is an 11 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm. In a transition to drowsiness rhythmic 5-6 Hertz temporal theta which is sharply contoured and has the characteristic morphology of rhythmic temporal theta of drowsiness is observed. Vertex waves, K-complexes, spindles and posts are observed in stage 2 sleep. The 5 Hertz activity can be identified in the frontotemporal regions bilaterally as the patient is disrupted from sleep. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is in stage 2 sleep and does not significantly activate the record.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The findings described above with rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness are considered a normal variant. However, they can also be seen in individuals with epilepsy and if seizures are an important consideration a follow up study is suggested.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 60-year-old woman status post aneurysm, right MCA stroke as well as seizures with most recent seizures in sleep 2 weeks ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Celexa, gabapentin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using a standard 10-20 system of electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some temporalis muscle artifact throughout the recording.
HEART RATE:  60.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontal central beta.  Activating procedures include photic stimulation.  There are no abnormal discharges.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness, although mainly wakefulness.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen very frequently in the right hemisphere at T4 and sometimes at P4 or C4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV.  At times these are sharply contoured, but not clearly epileptic.
There is also focal slowing at times independently at T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to right midtemporal and central and parietal focal slowing in addition to independent left midtemporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right midtemporal and central parietal region, which is consistent with an old stroke.  In addition, there is evidence of left midtemporal focal cerebral dysfunction which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or clear epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 59 year old right handed female with an episode of blurry vision,
numbness of the face and feet with jerking of the left arm. Multiple sclerosis, asthma, and possible complex partial seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 25 year old woman with refractory epilepsy following herpes
encephalitis, recent miscarriage now 5 weeks pregnant with increasingly aggressive seizures,
status post phenobarbital cessation.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Lamictal, Phenobarb, Zonegran
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are
performed. The family reports that the patient had a seizure earlier this morning.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is awake and cooperative. The overall
background is slow, disorganized with primarily a theta frequency background. Lambda is noted
in the background. Independent bursts of high amplitude, sharp waves of approximately 160
microseconds and greater than 100 millivolts are identified in brief bursts typically lasting less
than 10 seconds from the right or left temporal region. The sharp waves also occur individually
and there are some sharply contoured slowing. Features of drowsiness include an increase in
beta activity. The epileptiform activity has a more extensive field of spread into the anterior
temporal regions in drowsiness and even into T6/02 as the patient becomes sleepy. This
phenomenon is also seen on the left with more and more of a mid to posterior temporal
localization as the patient drifts off to sleep. Photic stimulation does elicit a driving response. It
increases the epileptiform activity which is, however, quite prominent during photic stimulation.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowing and disorganization.
2. Prominent epileptiform activity from the right or left temporal region which is independent
and may be mid or posterior temporal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a highly epileptogenic focus. No seizures were
recorded. These findings are similar to previous studies.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 57 year old female who has encephalopathy with acute left PCA and MCA infarct. Tonoclonic seizure at 10 a.m. on September 1, 2010.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Cipro, Heparin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is intubated and poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates continuous, high amplitude left frontal delta which is periodic in nature. There is a bit of faster frequency activity picked at T1 and at 7 but there are also some left frontal or frontotemporal sharp waves associated with these activities. The high-amplitude delta can be reviewed at a slower paper speed and does not have frequency evolution. Its overall frequency is 2 Hz. As times there is a suggestion of an 8.3 Hz alpha rhythm in the right posterior quadrant but there is significant slowing in the right frontal region. At times the delta in the left posterior quadrant is slower than that in the anterior quadrant.
HR: 84bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1: Continuous delta from the left hemisphere.
2. Bilateral FIRDA.
3. Occasional left frontal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe disturbance in the left hemisphere affecting both gray and while matter. The sharp waves are congruent with the history of acute seizures. No seizures were recorded. Ongoing evaluation is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 60 year old woman with pontine hemorrhage and locked-in syndrome.

MEDICATIONS: Ciprofloxacin, Hydralazine, Zosyn, Pantoprazole, Metoprolol

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.

Much of the theta frequency activity is 7 Hz with smaller quantities of5.5 Hz activity. Intermittent coughing is observed. It is not specifically associated with a change in-the background. There ate occasional bursts of arrhythmic delta activity identified from either hemisphere. Stimulation of the patient does not particularly impact the record. The record is not long enough to record definitive sleep cycles.

HR: 60 bpm

1. Replacement of normal background primarily with a theta frequency pattern.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed. If appropriate, a longer study to identify sleep/wake cycles may be of value. An alternative would be to consider SSEPs.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 17 year old woman with ticks, staring spells, attention deficit disorder, recent gastroenteritis, drop attacks, and a tonic clonic seizure.
MEDICATIONS: Bactrim and inhaler.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is abnormal. The background is primarily rhythmic theta with smaller amounts of delta. The definable posterior dominant rhythm is 5 Hz in a background with theta and delta. There are bursts of frontally predominantly spike and wave complexes noted in relaxed wakefulness. These are slightly asynchronous. Most are 3-5 Hz and in relaxed
wakefulness the bursts of generalized spike and wave activity are 1-3 seconds in duration. There are also some independent, isolated right or left temporal sharp waves noted in the background.
Hyperventilation is performed and produces an increase in the activity. In addition, during hyperventilation the patient complains of rapid or prominent heart rate.
Her baseline heart rate exceeds 100 beats per minute and in fact averages 110, actually dropping briefly to 96 during hyperventilation and then returning to tachycardia. Brief drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic slowing with spontaneous arousals. Lambda is observed in wakefulness.
Photic stimulation does elicit a driving response with supraharmonic driving at 11 Hz. In addition, there is a suggestion of a photo paroxysmal response as well. This is more clearly defined with frontally predominant polyspike activity with 19 Hz photic stimulation.
HR: 120 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Frontally predominant spike and wave activity.
2. Background slowing and disorganization.
3. A suggestion of focal epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This patient's frequent seizures may contribute to the background disorganization. The epileptiform activity may represent a primary generalized or secondary generalized focus. Additional recording may be helpful following initiation of treatment.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:

CLINICAL CORRELATION: In the context of this patient's age, the background is well organized. This EEG supports a structural process on the left.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 43 year old right handed woman with epilepsy since age 13, stroke in 2008, left-sided weakness, migraine headaches, pituitary tumor and multiple neoplastic processes. Epilepsy with 2 tonic-clonic seizures last month as well as complex partial seizures.

MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Topamax, Percocet, Nasonex, Albuterol, Flovent, Singulair

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10?20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness the background EEG is well organized. Hyperventilation is performed early in the record which produces some rhythmic slowing but it also produces rhythmic, sharply contoured, 3 Hz to 5 Hz activity from the left temporal region some of which has a well-defined left temporal sharp wave mixed in with it. INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake record.

After the photic stimulation continues, the recording continues and the patient had intermittent jerking of her shoulders. The shoulders jerk forwards and backwards.

The shoulder jerking is not associated with epileptiform activity in the EEG. It is sometimes associated with upwards thrusting of her upper chest. She stares straight ahead during the events.

As the record continues, a physician examines the patient. The interaction with the physician and the patient is associated with increasing motor activity including eye blinking, mouth opening and closing, a little bit of alternating movements to right or left, and then some rotatory movements of the torso. When the movements stop, the EEG shows a normal awake pattern. The patient is staring off to space after the event ends.

The event begins at 9:58 and lasts 7 minutes. Afterwards, there is intermittent jerking. Cognitive testing is not performed to make certain that the patient is responsive at the end of the EEG.

HR: 60 bpm


IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This patient had a 7-minute behavioral episode without EEG change. This recording suggests a behavioral event rather than an electrical seizure.

There
seems to be some electropositivity in the central or parietal region.
Arousal of the patient produces an increase in organization, although there is some focal slowing that remains on the left. 3. Intermittent slowing and disorganization, left greater than right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a localization mechanism for epilepsy. No focal slowing is in the region of the epileptiform activity. Correlation with clinical history and imaging is appropriate.

Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Some focal slow waves are noted at F3/C3 with some increase in faster frequencies at times in that region consistent with a breech.  The slow waves are noticed mainly at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-40 mV.

Left frontal central slowing and breech.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left frontal central region which is consistent with the known surgery.  The absence of normal posterior dominant rhythm, although atypical, could be a normal variant.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 48 year old male with a 5-minute syncopal event 6 weeks ago. No other neurologic history is provided.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz, 50 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm. In wakefulness there are also right anterior temporal sharp waves. During the hyperventilation part of the record there is an area of initially a low voltage, slightly irregular slowing out of the right central temporal region, followed by more rhythmic activity of initially 2-3 Hz, and then higher amplitude activity of increasing
rhythmicity in hyperventilation, which is in the right central temporal region. This activity out of the right central region occurs in the context of generalized, frontally predominant rhythmic slowing. In the post hyperventilation record, there is prominent rhythmic 7 Hz activity out of the left central region and then more definitive Mu like activity which can be seen bilaterally. The activity that looks like Mu on the left Is a lower voltage from that on the right, although the frequency is identical. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta frequency activity. Photic stimulation elicits supraharmonic driving.
HR: 66 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Rare right temporal sharp waves.
2. Subtle underlying focal slowing in the right central temporal region.
3. An unusual Mu activity that is slower that it is typically expected in higher amplitude  on the right.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The sharp waves should be correlated in this patients history, but support a focal mechanism for epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  28 year old woman, pregnant with twins, presents with recurrent seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Keppra
REASON FOR  STUDY:  Seizures
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long-term EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes. The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient's EEG was reviewed using continuous spike and seizure detection software, in addition to the patient's learned event as well as nurses' notes.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 to 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a mild excessive amount of beta seen throughout the recording.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and stage I, stage II, and stage III sleep, as well as stage IV.  Activating procedures were not performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:   None
SEIZURE/EVENT:  During the recording, the patient presses the alarm around 7:39 p.m. and describes that she feels like she is going to have an event.  There are no EEG changes at that time.  At 09:24:51, the patient presses the alarm and starts shaking her body, arching her back, and stretching her legs.  She lifts up the sheets at times and cannot be seen in the video.  She continues to do this for about 7 to 8 minutes until nurses come in and she is unresponsive to questions.  She remains having irregular jerking movements.  During this entire time, the EEG remains normal with no epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The episode captured during this EEG had no EEG correlate, which is consistent with a nonepileptic psychogenic event.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 26-year-old gentleman with history of TBI in 2010, status post craniotomy, VP shunt, ICH, and seizures.  The patient has left craniotomy.  On head CT, there is left frontal gliosis, right ventricular shunt placement, and bifrontal subdural hygroma.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the background rhythm was slow in theta and delta frequencies.  There was an asymmetry of activity in parasagittal and temporal region with activity being of faster frequency with higher voltage on the left cerebral hemisphere most pronounced in T5/T3 with polymorphic theta and delta sharply contoured discharges.  There was breach rhythm seen at the left mid and posterior temporal and left central region.  There were occasional sharp wave discharges in frontotemporal region with no evolution.  Drowsiness was characterized by further slowing of the background and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies with no abnormal responses.  Heart rate was 90 to 100 beats per minute with occasional PVCs.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to:
No posterior dominant rhythm.
Generalized slowing of the background activity in theta and delta range.
Polymorphic theta and delta activity at the left frontotemporal and central region.
Occasional sharp waves seen arising from the left frontotemporal region.
Left breach rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Diffuse slowing of the background activity during wakefulness could be due to toxic, metabolic, or infectious encephalopathy, effect of sedating medication or bilateral cerebral dysfunction.  Breach rhythm is consistent with the patient's history of craniotomy.  Almost continuous polymorphic theta and delta activity seen at the left temporal region suggesting of an underlying structural abnormality in the subcortical white matter of the left hemisphere.  The sharp waves seen arising from the left frontotemporal region are suggestive of epileptogenicity in the left cerebral cortex. There were no electrographic or clinical seizures seen during this recording.  Note that the patient was tachycardic with occasional PVC.

stimulation are performed. The patient is comfortable, but relatively somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is abnormal and relatively
slow. There is a lower voltage in the theta and delta pattern on the right. In contrast, the
left has less faster frequency activity. Stimulation of the patient produces some faster
alpha and beta frequency activity on the right, but less so on the left. The patient is
restless. Shifting arrhythmic delta activity is observed. A critical team was called to
administer medications which do slow the heart rate, but this intervention does not
change the EEG. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
HR: 150 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Lateral background slowing.
2. Asymmetry with slower pattern on the left compared to the right and disruption of
faster frequency activity on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In contrast to previous EEGs, no epileptiform features
were seen. This EEG supports a bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function
affecting gray and white matter, the left more significantly than the right.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 78 year old male with a history of epilepsy, heart failure and delirium, admitted with delirium
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Keppra, Ativan.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is markedly abnormal and includes a continuous, high amplitude periodic complex in the right posterior quadrant at

The amplitude of the activity exceeds 250 microvolts. It has the characteristic of PEDS PLUS. In addition, in some points it is essentially a left hemispheric spike and slow wave complex. No clinical seizures are noted during the record, but at one point the activity starts to transition to more of a rhythmic theta-delta. Photic stimulation does not activate the record. At the close of the record, despite the high amplitude periodic complex in the right occipital region, the patient is conversant.

1. Essentially continuous periodic complex from the left occipital parietal region.
2. Potentially a subclinical seizure when the continuous sharp waves transition to more of a rhythmic theta-delta pattern.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a highly irritative process. No clinical seizures were recorded. The EEG technologist did contact the clinical team on call to review this study.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 23 year old male with new onset seizures.
MEDICATIONS: None
INTRODUCTION: Continuous digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient keeps a log. He is able to push the button for all of the events that he experiences. He has multiple episodes of dizziness or disorienting feeling.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 hertz posterior dominant rhythm which is symmetrically reactive. Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background theta with vertex waves, spindles and stage II sleep. There is an epoch in which REM sleep is seen.
In the interictal EEG, there is a single left temporal sharp wave.
Events: The patient has multiple dizzy spells including 1:29, 1:25, 3:12, 3:36, 5:36, 5:46 and then there are no additional push buttons noted.
Although not all of the seizures have a clear clinical correlate and some have only either subtle theta or subtle disruption of faster frequency activity in the left temporal region, some have clear, rhythmic 4 hertz theta from the left temporal region with some spread to the frontocentral region bilaterally, typically lasting 20-40 seconds. The patient receives Depakote at 2:20 p.m., the discharges are briefer, more evanescent more allusive.
Event time 12930: the patient has a dizzy spell characterized by decreased alpha frequency activity from the left temporal region and a brief burst of left temporal theta.
Event time: 2:32 p.m.: There is a brief burst of left temporal theta which differs from the background.
Event time: 3:12p.m.: Aura of dizziness, left temporal theta.
Event #3: Aura characterized by dizziness time 335 to 33729, rhythmic temporal theta as described above.
Event #4: Subtle left temporal theta at 3:53:52.
Event #5: 536, very subtle left temporal theta.
Event #6: Aura 5:46:13, brief burst of left temporal theta.
HR: 100 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG monitoring due to:
1. Subtle, intermittent attenuation of alpha frequency activity in the left temporal region.
2. A handful of well defined auras characterized by rhythmic 4 hertz theta with clear frequency evolution. The characteristic seizure pattern for this patient includes attenuation of alpha in the region, then the theta and then some bilateral frontocentral spread.
3. Rare interictal findings including sharp waves in the left temporal region and sharply contoured theta. An example of this is at 4:35:37 a.m. on the morning of the second.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is diagnostic of a localization related mechanism for epilepsy. These findings were reviewed with the patient during the hospitalization.

elicits a brief driving response.

or left hand movements. There is no definitive EEG signature for these behaviors.
HR: 80 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits but with unusual behavior.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Despite the electrode problems, there was no EEG scalp
signature for this patient's behavior.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient has a craniotomy defect on the right. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. A subtle breech rhythm is identified in the right hemisphere with an increase in amplitude in that region. Drowsiness is characterized by slow-rolling eye movements. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving. Hyperventilation does not activate the record.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features were observed in the record. A breech rhythm is an anticipated finding following craniotomy and in this case is a relatively subtle pattern.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   84 year old woman with advanced dementia and cardiac pacemaker, admitted approximately 4 days ago with aspiration pneumonia, status post sedation but no sedation for 72 hours.  The patient is not awakening from sedation.

Stimulation of the patient produces artifact but does not significantly activate the record.  There is a small degree of variability in the amount of theta and delta.
HR:    66 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Marked background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  This EEG supports a relatively severe disturbance of cerebral function but is not specific as to etiology. function with associated impact on cerebral pattern may also play a role in the findings described above.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 25 year old right handed woman with episodes which are described as spasms. They include eye fluttering, head rocking and crying. Her brother and her child both have epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Gabapentin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient had one of her behavioral events during the EEG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a symmetric, 11 Hz, 70 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and produces a great deal of blinking. Brief drowsiness is characterized by a small amount of theta and some bursts of rhythmic, hypnagogic hypersynchrony. Photic stimulation elicits abundant, symmetric driving. The patient has an event during photic stimulation characterized by frequent eye blink. The eye blink frequency increases after the photic stimulation stops. She has shaking of her legs and impaired responsiveness. This is followed by moaning. No epileptiform features are associated with these behaviors. The EEG demonstrates a normal awake pattern throughout these behaviors which began at 11:44. unfortunately, the camera is primarily on her face and upper body and this is the lower extremity activity. Afterward, the patient has intermittent arm shaking noted at 11:47, again difficult to see on the camera. Afterward she feels drained and tired but the EEG continues to demonstrate a normal awake pattern.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is the second EEG for this individual. During both EEGs, the patient had behaviors characteristic of nonepileptic seizures with characteristic behavior, crying in the absence of epileptiform activity.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Slowing of the alpha rhythm.

This phenomenon can be seen in dementia, but it could also be seen in medication phenomenon. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow-up study is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 61 year old male with altered mental status, intermittent paroxysmal spells of tremulousness and tachycardia. Past history of stroke, multiple seizures on the morning of the 4th followed by obtundation.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Keppra
INTRODUCTION: Continuous digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Seizure and spike detection software is used.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: This long term 24 hour video EEG monitor demonstrates a slow background. The initial sections are primarily delta. As the recording continues, there is more theta frequency noted in the background with 1.5 hertz, 4.2 hertz activity and 6 hertz activity in the background. Stimulation of the patient produces an alerting response with an increase in muscle. Some sections of the record demonstrate medium amplitude FIRDA. Others demonstrate theta. Multiple clinical events are documented by the team. These include impaired mental status. Episodes of tremulousness are noted at 1:56 a.m. and 3:48 a.m. These are not associated with change in awareness. On a handful of occasions, an asymmetry is noted with a 6 hertz alpha rhythm identified on the left, not so clearly identified on the right
HR: 120 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal electroencephalogram due to:
1. Markedly slow background.
2. Frontal intermittent and rhythmic delta activity.
3. On occasion, an asymmetric alpha rhythm, present only on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are compatible with a generalized disturbance of cerebral function. This is a nonspecific finding and can be seen in the toxic or metabolic encephalopathy as well as other causes. There are no epileptiform features noted. Although a Holter devise was not utilized, the patient has persistent tachycardia rather than intermittent paroxysmal tachycardia.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 50 year old right handed male with 4 tonic clonic seizures, past history of epilepsy, MVA trauma, burns. Post traumatic epilepsy since the age of 16 and psychiatric disorder.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is slow and disorganized. It is primarily a theta delta pattern with a glimpse of a 9 hertz alpha rhythm on the right. There seems to be a breech rhythm with higher amplitude activity on the left compared to the right. Sharp waves are identified most of which have a T1 phase reversal, but there are a handful of sharp waves which start at T2, lower voltage and then higher amplitude, left anterior temporal T2-F7. The sharp waves seem to be accentuated by hyperventilation. The focal slowing on the left is also accentuated by hyperventilation. Although there is no mention of a previous craniotomy, there is higher amplitude activity on the left and as the patient becomes drowsy, there is a bit more focal left frontal temporal delta. Photic stimulation produces scant driving more apparent on the right than the left.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Focal slowing on the left compared to the right.
3. Sharp waves seem primarily from the left, but some of which start on the right and end on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a focal process on the left involving gray and white matter. In addition, the overall background is slow suggesting a bihemispheric process. Correlation with imaging is appropriate, but overall, this EEG supports a focal mechanism for seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 61 year old right handed male with multiple aneurysms on the right but first ever tonic clonic seizures with persistent confusion. Question also of complex partial seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Hydralazine, Amlodipine
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is somewhat confused.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Although the patient is able to answer questions, the background EEG is markedly abnormal. The left hemisphere is somewhat lower voltage. The right hemisphere includes a rhythmic delta activity with a high amplitude spike and slow wave complex in the right frontocentral region with some variability typically C4.
When the patient is asked to count to 10, 8 Hz activity appears out of the right hemisphere. At one point, the pattern almost looks like an alerting but at another point during this, it almost looks as if an ictal pattern is generated during this testing. There is variability in the record with some sections demonstrating more alpha frequency activity than others. The right hemisphere demonstrates a significant breech rhythm.
The spike and wave activity has a slower periodicity demonstrating some waxing and waning but its alpha theta frequency activity which may represent an ictal pattern for this individual versus an arousal. Photic stimulation does not clearly activate the record.
HR: 84 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Prominent epileptiform activity in the right central region.
2. Questionable subclinical seizures characterized by more rhythmic delta theta from the right and/or perhaps a pattern of more rhythmic alpha theta frequency activity.
3. Relatively lower voltage featureless pattern on the right.
4. Breech rhythm with much higher amplitude activity on the right
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a structural process on the right involving gray and white matter. There is a highly epileptogenic focus on the right. Additional recording is suggested to make sure that clinical seizures are not missed.
