LENGTH OF RECORDING:  23 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 51-year-old woman with a history of right MCA stroke and bipolar disorder as well as seizure disorder.  She now presents with being found unresponsive on the floor.  She has approximately 1 seizure a month.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  The recording was performed at bedside.  Some of the electrodes had high impedances due to poor patient cooperation throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is a right to left interhemispheric asymmetry with faster frequencies observed over the left hemisphere.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the left hemisphere consists of polymorphic moderate amplitude 8.5 to 9 Hz alpha activity.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the right hemisphere consists of polymorphic low to moderate amplitude 7 to 8 Hz theta.  The anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient is weak bilaterally.  No normal sleep architecture is captured.  Additional diffuse polymorphic theta is observed.  Intermittent left hemispheric sharp waves are captured.  Phase reversal occurs over F7, T1, T3 and Fp1, F3 electrodes.  There is nearly continuous EMG artifact that effects variable leads.  Premature QRS complexes are captured on a single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:
Mild diffuse slowing.
Mild to moderate right hemispheric slowing.
Intermittent sharp waves over the left frontal/anterior temporal region.
Occasional premature QRS complexes seen on EKG.
EMG artifact that is nearly continuous effecting variable leads throughout the recording.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake only 23 minute EEG due to mild diffuse slowing, mild to moderate right hemispheric slowing, as well as intermittent left frontal/anterior temporal epileptiform discharges.  Diffuse slowing indicates etiologically nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  Focal right hemispheric slowing indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural in etiology, and is consistent with the patient's history of right MCA territory stroke.  There is an epileptogenic focus over the left frontal/anterior temporal region.  A large amount of EMG artifact is present throughout the recording, so subtle abnormalities might have been missed.  No clear electrographic seizures are captured.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The overall background is somewhat slow and disorganized. High amplitude temporal sharp and slow wave complexes are noted which can be seen independently from the right or left temporal region. Features of drowsiness include vertex waves. Photic stimulation does not significantly activate the record. Hyperventilation accentuates left temporal sharp waves.
HR: 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Significant slowing of the alpha rhythm.
3. Independent, right or left temporal sharp waves.
4. Some rhythmic temporal slowing which is a bit more prominent on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings maybe correlated with imaging. Hyperventilation did seem to accentuate the left temporal sharp waves. This EEG supports a localization related mechanism for epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 66 year old woman with complex partial seizures with loss of consciousness, past history of hypertension.
MEDICATIONS: Aspirin, Dilantin, Phenytoin, HCTZ
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Much of the record includes relaxed wakefulness or drowsiness. In this drowsy state there is more of a theta and beta frequency pattern. In addition, there are bursts of sharply contoured focal slowing in the left anterior temporal region. Some of the bursts occur with pairs or brief bursts of sharply contoured theta frequency activity. Photic stimulation produces scant driving, as well as some electrode artifact. The left anterior temporal, irregular, sharply contoured slowing is identified at that time as well. There appears to be a T1/T3 sharp wave mixed with this. As the patient becomes a bit more drowsy, there is also some rhythmic theta in the left frontal region. The normal testing to search for an alpha rhythm was not performed. Spontaneous eye opening and eye closure was identified, but there appeared to be scant, lower voltage, 10.5 Hz alpha activity, better defined on the right compared to the left.
HR: 90bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Irregular bursts of left mid to anterior temporal sharply contoured theta.
2. Subtle and mixed left mid to anterior temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a localization related mechanism for epilepsy. The primary features were in the temporal region, spreading to the frontal region as the patient became drowsy. The overall awake background was likely, Inadequately assessed for an adult of this age due to communication difficulties.

RECORDING LENGTH:  Almost 21 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 40-year-old woman with a seizures characterized by loss of consciousness and postictal confusion.  The patient has been seizure free since 2011.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed in the laboratory.  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well formed and modulated 10-10.5 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  Fast alpha variant is occasionally observed.  Additionally, the patient has frequent eye fluttering throughout the recording.
During brief drowsiness the posterior dominant rhythm attenuates and bursts of diffuse theta are captured.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and results in mild  diffuse background slowing.
Step photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.
FINDINGS:
No stage 2 sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
Blinking artifact.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy 21-minute EEG.  No epileptiform discharges were captured, however, stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indications for seizures persist, a repeat study with stage 2 sleep may be of benefit.  Frequent blinking artifact is captured throughout the recording.  This could limit interpretation of the activity over the right frontal regions.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 60 year old male with a history of schizophrenia and right frontal

MEDICATIONS: Temazepam, Haldol, Zyprexa. Ativan,
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 1020 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient has been somewhat sedated and is
relatively motionless throughout the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG includes an abnormal pattern. There
is generous beta In the frontocentral regions and a suggestion of a breech rhythm in the central
regions. Prominent arrhythmic delta activity and disruption of faster frequency activity is noted in
the frontotemporal regions bilaterally, more so on the right than on the left, and the activity from
the right frontal region is a bit more featureless when compared to the left. Vertex waves are
noted as the patient transitions into sleep. There is significant variability in the record in terms of
the amount of beta frequency activity. As the patient becomes drowsy, the EEG becomes lower
voltage, slower and intermittently attenuates although it is not frankly discontinuous. Sharply
contoured slowing is noted Intermittently in the frontocentral reg ions.
HR: 120bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Marked background slowing.
2. Prominent arrhythmic delta activity and disruption of faster frequency activity in the
frontotemporal regions, right more so than the left.
3. Occasional sharp waves in the right frontocentral region.
4. Intermittent attenuation of the background.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a significant bihemispheric disturbance, in
particular, one that involves the frontotemporal regions. Although there are a handful of sharp
waves, there are no prominent epileptiform features. Overall this EEG supports a bilateral,
significant disturbance of cerebral function.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 84 year old woman with a left meningioma resection, postoperative day 3

Lovenox, Zofran, Dexamethasone
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is markedly abnormal. The overall
background is a mixture of irregular theta and delta. There are posteriorly predominant sharp
waves, includes P5, and independently T6 02. There are bursts of faster frequency activity
which are picked up at the midline. The activity from the left frontal region is more or less
suppressed and there is more arrhythmic delta activity noted on the right. Tactile stimulation of
the patient seems to elicit a run of epileptiform activity. The epileptiform activity from the right
and left do not seem to be connected, but tactile stimulation seems to have produced
asynchronous train of sharp waves and spikes from either hemisphere, each of which have its
own periodicity. Additional spontaneous bursts of this epileptiform activity are noted. Again,
right occipital temporal and left occipital, again, without clear linkage between the 2 bursts.
96bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Relative suppression of activity from the frontal regions.
2. Occipitally temporal predominant epileptiform activity.
3. Marked background slowing and disorganization.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a highly epileptogenic process. The
epileptiform activity is generous posteriorly, not anteriorly. These findings may be
correlated with this patient's clinical exam and history. The possibility of subclinical seizures
should be considered in this individual.

MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Tegretol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz symmetric and reactive alpha rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage frontocentral beta activity. Features of drowsiness include a prominent increase in beta. Occasional temporal wicket is noted in the transition to drowsiness as is electrocardiogram artifact particularly on the right. Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained although there are occasional vertex waves. Hyperventilation produces a small increase in amplitude of the background and a small amount of slowing. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.
HR: 66bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage 1 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed in this EEG. There were no frontal sharp waves identified in this 28 minute EEG. If further characterization of this patient's epilepsy is needed, a followup study with more extensive sleep is suggested particularly as a right frontal sharp wave was noted on a single previous EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 45 year old male with epilepsy since age 6, recent 4 seizures in a row. Typical seizures are tonic clonic with postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm which is symmetric and reactive and a small amount of 11 Hz activity noted in the background bilaterally. Features of drowsiness include anterior spread of alpha rhythm and disruption of the alpha rhythm. Notable findings in this record include sharply contoured delta or bursts of rhythmic frontal sharply contoured theta in the right frontal region typically at F8 or T2, reaching amplitudes up to 80 microvolts. While there are no definitive sharp and slow wave complexes, in some cases this is simply because of the duration of the discharge, not the actual morphology. Hyperventilation and drowsiness seem to accentuate this finding. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving at faster flash frequencies.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Sharply contoured rhythmic, delta in the right frontal temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Although there was some eye artifact noted in the record, the eye artifact can be excluded with the use of an average reference and there is clearly a focus in the right frontal temporal region which can be differentiated from the eye movement.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 89 year old woman with large left meningioma, recent
craniotomy, evaluate for subclinical seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, there is a 7.5 Hz alpha
rhythm identified more so on the right than the left. There is an asymmetry with more of
a suppressed pattern on the left compared to the right but this waxes and wanes. In the
overnight sleep section of the record, there are some occasional sharp waves noted on
the left. There are also some bilateral bifrontal sharp waves noted in sleep with almost
a metabolic appearance.
As the recording continues, there are more triphasic wave forms observed in the
overnight sleep record, but by 5 a.m. these seem to have resolved. On the morning of
the 8th, the background EEG is quite well organized but occasional left frontal sharp
waves are noted.
In addition, again intermittently, there are both bursts of bifrontal sharp waves, triphasic
waves. and left temporal sharp waves. These do not appear to be associated with a
change in the patient's clinical status. These bursts are not associated with defined
clinical changes in the patient.
By 1:55, the EEG is now better organized. At 2:11, the bifrontal sharp waves appear.
They appear in paroxysmal bursts with a background slowing almost as if it is a
metabolic pattern.
There is no baseline for this long-term EEG monitoring session.
HR: 70 to 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowing.
2. Focal slowing from the left temporal region which seems to be improving over time.
3. Triphasic waves.
4. Bursts of bifrontal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG suggests more than one process. The first is a
postoperative process which gets better over time in terms of focal slowing. Sharp
waves on the left are anticipated following craniotomy. The paroxysmal bursts both
triphasic waves and bilateral sharp waves may be a metabolic phenomenon or part of
her underlying dementia.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  75 year old male with a right hemiparesis, left MCA stroke or bleed with edema, admitted on June 3, 2011.
MEDICATIONS:  Lisinopril, Norvasc, Tramadol, Isosorbide, ASA
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  The patient is restless and moving about.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a remarkable and fluctuating asymmetry.  Some sections of the record demonstrate attenuation of faster frequency activity on the right with the exception of bursts of beta more prominent on the right.  Other sections of the record demonstrate much more significant underlying arrhythmic delta activity underneath the alpha-frequency activity in the left hemisphere.  A 9 Hz alpha rhythm can be identified from either hemisphere, sometimes symmetrically, sometimes asymmetrically.  There is also some sharply contoured slowing and a handful of T1, T3 sharp waves on the left.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in beta, particularly on the right.
HR:    72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  This is an interesting and abnormal EEG due to:
Fluctuating asymmetries with at times more underlying arrhythmic delta on the left or right.
Asymmetries on the right, some of which would suggest a cortical process on the right such as disruption of faster frequency activity with disruption of the alpha frequency, but an increase in beta would contradict this.
Very sharply contoured waves at T1 and T3.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures were identified.  This EEG supports a dynamic bihemispheric disturbance.

Background slowing.
Disorganization.

A slow alpha rhythm which is also somewhat asymmetric.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 19-year-old woman with a history of several concussions in 2010 and 2011.  She now presents with left shoulder pain and numbness, twitching followed left arm spasms as well as full body spasms.
MEDICATIONS:  Benadryl, Reglan, Toradol, lorazepam, amitriptyline.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.    Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were  performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of well formed and modulated 12 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  Excess beta is present.  During sleep vertex waves, sleep spindles, K complexes and POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep) are captured.  Additionally, several diffuse body jerks are captured during drowsiness and sleep.  These are associated with brief EMG artifacts seen on the scalp EEG.  Hyperventilation is performed with poor effort and produces no significant change in the background.  Step photic stimulation induces symmetrical photic driving at medium range flash frequencies.  A regular heart rhythm with a heart rate of less than 60 beats per minute is captured on the EKG.
FINDINGS:
No epileptiform discharges.
Stage II sleep.
Several diffuse body jerks during drowsiness and sleep without an abnormal interictal correlate.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and sleep 26 minute EEG.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not preclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Several diffuse body jerks were captured during drowsiness and sleep.  These were associated only with a brief diffuse EMG artifact seen on the scalp EEG.

TYPE OF STUDY:  Routine EEG.
DIAGNOSIS:  Rule out seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 55-year-old female with prior EEG and presents with history of diabetes, hypertension, anemia, hyperlipidemia, coronary artery disease, bypass surgery.
MEDICATIONS:  Patient is taking medications for diabetes and high blood pressure.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the lab using the standard International 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to one channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation was not performed and photic stimulation was performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness and stage I and II sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, alpha rhythm is 8-8.5 Hz in frequency, 30-50 microvolts in amplitude seen in occipital region which attenuates with eye opening.  There is 6-7 Hz diffuse theta activity seen during wakefulness which is distributed symmetrically.  There was a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity which is distributed symmetrically.  A stage I and stage II sleep is characterized with disappearance of alpha rhythm, slowing of the background activity, and absence of motion and eye-blink artifact as well as presence of the vertex sharp waves, sleep spindles, and K complexes.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple frequencies and did not resolve in a driving response.  Heart rate was 60-70 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is mildly abnormal EEG due to excess theta activity during wakefulness.  There was no epileptiform discharge or seizure activity noted during this recording.  The above finding could be due to metabolic, toxic, hypoxic, or infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to effect of sedating medication, bilateral cerebral dysfunction, degenerative brain disease.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were captured or recorded.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 22-year-old female with a history of seizures after a stereotactic frontal craniotomy for a central neurocytoma and VP shunt, now with recurrent seizures, low Dilantin levels.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin 1 gram, Ativan 12 mg, as well as added Ativan afterward; later intubated and placed on propofol.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long-term EEG for 18 hours was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional EKG and anterior temporal electrodes.  The patient was comatose and unresponsive during the EEG.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffuse background which is disorganized, mainly in the delta/theta frequencies with no normal posterior dominant rhythm and no normal frontocentral beta.  No normal sleep architecture is also seen.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges seen at T4-T6 at a frequency of 2 Hz with amplitude of 20 to 75 microvolts.  These discharges are seen continuously but appear to evolve as described in the seizure paragraph.  During the recording, these PLEDs become more blunted and less frequent, but they are continuously seen.  At times during the last part of the recording, they appeared to have more anterior predominance, moving from T4 forward to the F8 region.
Diffuse slow waves seen in the recording.
SEIZURES:   Frequent seizures are seen emanating from the T6-T4 electrode which evolve from PLEDs and stop.  There is a contralateral left hemisphere artifact as well as in the video left arm trembling can be seen during these seizures.  There are multiple of these occurring at the beginning of the recording, almost continuously. However, as the over time the recording improves, the periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges become more blunted and the seizures stop.  During the rest of the EEG, the last 10 hours of the EEG, there is only intermittent muscle artifact on the left hemisphere but no clear actual seizures being seen.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Frequent seizures arising from the left posterotemporal region, which later improve, and none seen during the last 10 hours.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of localization epilepsy arising from the right posterotemporal region, with multiple seizures seen from that region.  Please note that the seizures improve and none are seen during the last 10 hours. In addition there is continuous evidence of acute focal dysfunction and irritability in the right hemisphere.  Lastly, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction which in this patient is likely due, at least in part, to medication affect.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  55 year old female who presented to ER with sore throat felt to have epiglottitis, multiple intubation attempts failed, ended up having a PEA code with 3 rounds of epinephrine, pulse finally returned.  Circulation now about 4-6 hours later noted to have convulsive seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Versed drip, Dilantin.
REASON FOR EEG:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Long term digital video EEG was performed for 14 hours using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with a 1 channel EKG and anterior temporal electrodes.  The study was recorded while the patient was comatose.  No activity procedures were performed.  Continuous EEG monitoring was performed and reviewed using spike detection and seizure detection software as well as nursing noted events.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a low amplitude diffusely slow background with frequencies mainly in the delta range.  No normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta is seen.  No sleep architecture is seen.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized periodic epileptiform discharges (GPEDs) were seen with anterior central maximum at a frequency of 1-2 Hz.  At times this would evolve, see description of seizures below.
Generalized slow waves seen at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  There are multiple seizures occurring per hour seen at the beginning of the recording which originate from GPEDs which increase in frequency and amplitude in seconds and later are obscured by a rhythmic intermittent muscle artifact.  The longest of these last about 40 seconds and afterwards  the background returns to baseline.  These seizures appear to subside 4 hours into the recording and after 10:30 at night no more are seen.  After this time the GPEDs appear to become slightly blunted and lower in amplitude, although at times intermittently the morphology changes to more sharply contoured but never clearly evolve into seizures.  Later in the recording in the morning hours there is some intermittent diffuse muscle artifact but no underlying evolution of seizures or epileptiform activity could be clearly seen in between the bursts of muscle.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized seizures.
Diffuse slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals multiple seizures with a generalized onset and interictal evidence of diffuse brain dysfunction and irritability.  These findings are consistent with a diffuse cortical injury and with a history of hypoxic injury.  The EEG appears to improve with time and during the last 10 hours of the recording no seizures can be clearly seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  72 year old right handed female with episode of driving with loss of memory, afterward was found in an accident.

TECHNICAL DIFFICULTY:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  Normal frontocentral beta was seen.  Sleep is seen, stage I and stage II.  Photic stimulation produces no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen at T1/F7, occasionally, as well as a single F8/T2 sharp wave.
Focal slow waves seen in the anterior temporal regions bilaterally at 2 to 4 Hz, also occasionally.  At one point in the left anterior temporal region there is a monomorphic discharge of delta for 2 to 3 seconds.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal sharp waves in the bilateral anterior temporal regions with associated slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of acute structural irritability in the bilateral anterior temporal regions, which has a high correlation with seizures arising from that region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the bilateral anterior temporal regions, which is nonspecific in regard to etiology.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  79 year old female with history of stroke, diabetes, hypertension, hyperlipidemia presents with a left MCA stroke and right-sided weakness found unresponsive.

TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to mildly diffusely slow background with posterior dominant rhythm which is best seen over the right hemisphere and at best reaches 8 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.  Some frontocentral beta seen over the right hemisphere.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  Photic stimulation reveals no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen continuously over the left hemisphere maximal in the T3 electrode.  There is also related loss of faster frequencies over that hemisphere.
Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz occurring during wakefulness.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Continuous left hemispheric slowing maximum on the mid temporal region.
Mild excessive theta during wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with focal structural cerebral dysfunction in the left hemisphere maximal the mid temporal region which is consistent with the known stroke in that region.  In addition, there is evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  54 year old male with a history of hepatitis C cirrhosis, IV drug abuse, hypertension, and epididymitis who presents with change in mental status, confused and lethargic.

REASON FOR EEG:  Rule out seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior and temporal electrodes and EKG electrodes.  The patient was obtunded during this study.  No activating procedures were performed
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG opens to a diffuse slow background with an asymmetric pattern over each hemisphere.  The left hemisphere is mainly in the theta-delta frequencies with maximum slowing seen in the left midtemporal region.  The right hemisphere reveals a low-voltage discharge with minimal normal cortical frequencies seen, mainly in the delta frequency.
No normal posterior dominant rhythm is seen and normal frontocentral beta is absent.  At times the patient coughs and the frequencies appeared to improve to a theta pattern.  No normal sleep architecture was seen, and no activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Left hemispheric slowing maximum on the midtemporal region.
Right hemispheric attenuation.
Infrequent sharply contoured C3 sharp transients, possibly asymmetric vertex.
SEIZURES  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left temporal slowing.
Right hemispheric attenuation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural dysfunction in the left hemisphere, maximum in the temporal region, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology but has a high correlation with a lesion in that region.  The right-sided attenuation may be due to cortical dysfunction sometimes seen in stroke or overlying structural lesion like a subdural hemorrhage causing decreased attenuation.  Clinical correlation was recommended.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  Adult male status post gunshot wound to chest and back.  At 4:00 a.m. today the patient had generalized tonic-clonic seizures requiring 7 mg of Ativan.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Fentanyl, Ativan.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is comatose, unresponsive, with intermittent eye blinking.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal and includes multiple electrographic seizures which are clinically associated with eye blink.  Much of the EEG is, in fact, ictal with seizures seeming to wax and wane.  It is difficult at this point to determine when seizures begin and end, but the very first seizure for this patient seems to begin with a burst of rhythmic higher amplitude sharply contoured activity on the left.  Many of the seizures are characterized by high amplitude rhythmic theta-delta or spike-and-wave activity which is essentially bilateral.  Some seizures end with T6 spiking.  Others end with rhythmic sharply contoured activity on the left.  As the recording continues, the seizures begin with faster frequency activity alpha and beta out of the frontal regions and then a paroxysmal evolution.  Some of the seizures do have a clearly defined ending with a slow background and then the T6 periodic sharp waves.  There are sections of the record where there is a T6 sharp wave and a T1 burst of sharply contoured delta.
As the recording continues, more of the epileptiform activity is in the right hemisphere and may be posterotemporal or anterior temporal.
By 12:34, the nurse is providing Ativan.  As the record ends at 12:40, epileptiform activity is noted and has not resolved.
HR:    120 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Multiple electrographic seizures which seem to emanate from the frontal regions but at least in some locations either begin or end with epileptiform activity in the left frontal or even right posterotemporal region.
Interictal epileptiform activity from multiple different localizations including T1, T3, T4, and T6.
Background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is diagnostic of a complex partial status epilepticus.  Based on these findings, continuous video EEG monitoring was initiated.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 46-year-old female with left posterior temporal AVM and clips brought in with first episode of seizure described as shaking all over with tongue biting.
MEDICATIONS:  Chlorhexidine and Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead  EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while confused, unresponsive, and lethargic.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 5-7 Hz and there is some frontal central beta.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  Activating procedures were not performed.
Abnormal discharges:
Frequent T5 sharp waves seen throughout the recording.  At times the sharp waves would suddenly become rhythmic and continue for about 2-3 minutes and then stop.  They did not clearly evolve, but became extremely arrhythmic throughout this time.
Focal slowing seen at T5 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
Moderate diffuse slowing at 5-7 Hz seen continuously throughout the recording.
Seizures:  As above mentioned there is bursts of T5 sharp waves that did not clearly evolve, but would start and stop suddenly, at times for minutes with no clinical correlate.  These are concerning for possible electrographic seizures.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left posterior temporal sharp waves and monomorphic discharges concerning for electrographic seizures, in addition to generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from the left posterior temporal region.  Note:  The bursts of rhythmic sharp waves were concerning for electrographic seizures, as they had no clinical correlate.  In addition, there is evidence of moderate diffuse slowing, which may due at least in part to medication effect.  These findings were reported to the primary team who decided to treat the patient and will place the patient on long term monitoring.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient has clinical seizures characterized by facial twitching and involuntary movements of the right arm.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins the patient has been having seizures and continues to have seizures.  The overall EEG is sharply contoured, almost a chaotic pattern, and intermittently discontinuous.  Left frontal sharp waves precede the seizure and the seizure includes a mixture of frontal and left hemispheric sharp activity and fast activity.  The activity is maximum in the front, but is really seen throughout the left hemisphere in the parasagittal region.  The fast activity is prominent in the central regions.  Some of the activity spreads to the right.
By 8:15 p.m. the epileptiform activity is a bit more isolated.  At 8:00 p.m. the patient receives a Dilantin load.  He develops respiratory distress and a pleural effusion.  He is placed on a propofol drip for respiratory management. No additional clinical seizures are observed.  The EEG demonstrates a pattern with left frontal or bifrontal sharp activity or fast activity with a discontinuous background.
HR:    104 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Initially status epilepticus pattern with repetitive seizures, improving to a discontinuous pattern with the use of both Dilantin and propofol.

LONG TERM MONITORING
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous digital video EEG monitoring was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is intubated, extremely ill, but responsive.

Markedly suppressed background.
Left frontal PLED with a generous field of spread.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with symmetric reactive 11 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity.  EPOC of sleep include stage II sleep with vertex waves, spindles, K-complexes, and POSTS.  The patient transitions between wakefulness and sleep. Hyperventilation produces a small amount of slowing.  In addition there is an increase in amplitude. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR:    96 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features were identified.  Previous EEGs were not available for comparison.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  58 year old right handed woman with a sharp headache followed by shortness of breath and a black out spell.  Past history of stroke with right sided numbness.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is well organized with a 10.5 Hz, 50 mV posterior dominant rhythm. Features of drowsiness include attenuation of the alpha rhythm and slow rolling eye movements. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude in background. Photic stimulation elicits a vigorous driving response.
HR:    72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are no focal or epileptiform features noted in this record.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of stroke or epilepsy.  If seizures are an important consideration a follow up study may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   49 year old male found with confusion.  With 2 seizures, hepatitis cirrhosis, markedly icteric.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Metoprolol, Prograf.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF BACKGROUND:  The background EEG is markedly low voltage and slow.  It is a mixture of low voltage beta at 15 Hz with smaller amounts of 2 to 2.5 Hz delta.  Stimulation of the patient produced a small amount of theta.  There is snore artifact.
HR:    108 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Markedly slow background.
Prominent delta.
Prominent beta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This electroencephalogram is compatible with a severe underlying encephalopathy.  Stimulation of the patient does produce reactivity.  A slow delta may be part of this patient's metabolic encephalopathy.  The beta reflects exposure to benzodiazepines.

IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  26 year old right handed male with post-traumatic epilepsy after a motor vehicle accident at age 19.  Three seizures out of sleep New Year's Eve followed by postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a well-identified 11 Hz alpha rhythm which reaches 70 microvolts.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record.  There is some eye movement artifact, but no definite focal slowing.  The tech uses eye pads to reduce eye blink artifact.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving with supra harmonic driving.
HR:    96 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the third EEG for this individual.  Epileptiform activity was identified on 2006 with rare sharp waves from the right hemisphere, but was not seen in 2008.  In this individual with a recent exacerbation of epilepsy, additional
recording capturing deeper stages of sleep may be helpful to characterize epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  56 year old female found by husband after drinking with a right ear laceration and inappropriate behavior.  CT demonstrated left temporal intracerebral hemorrhage and bilateral subarachnoid hemorrhage.  Evaluate for seizures.

There is subtle asymmetry with a bit more arrhythmic delta activity noted in the left temporal region than the right.  Stimulation of the patient clearly produces an increase in faster frequency activity.  Spontaneous arousals are noted.  Shifting asymmetries are also seen, which was characterized by vertex waves.
HR:    72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Diffusely slow pattern.
Shifting asymmetries with more disruption of faster frequency activity on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There were no epileptiform features identified.
This EEG supports a bihemispheric process, one impacting the left temporal region more than the right.  If addition information is needed or if there are additional concerns
about t
he seizures, a follow-up study as the patient improves may be performed in the lab.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  24 year old left handed woman with bipolar disorder, hyperprolactinemia, pituitary adenoma, hyperlipidemia.  Epilepsy, not otherwise described.  Born in a homeless shelter in 1987.  Prenatal drug exposure.  Developmental delay.
MEDICATIONS:  Topamax, Dilantin, Zocor, Seroquel, Lamictal, Cogentin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is excess theta noted in the background.  In the transition to sleep there is some 6 Hz theta activity which demonstrates a small amount of shifting asymmetry.  Brief vertex waves are noted in sleep, but sleep is not sustained. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is in a drowsy state and does not elicit a driving response.
HR:    86 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
A small amount of background theta.
A somewhat disorganized background.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are some normal variants noted in the EEG, including some of the theta activity described above.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow up study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  29 year old right handed male with myoclonic jerking of the upper extremities for the last several years now increasing and also a concussion 2 years ago. Head trauma at age 21 and seizures for a year after that. Migraine headaches, asthma and allergies.
MEDICATIONS:  Albuterol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a symmetric reactive 9 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. In relaxed wakefulness, there are bursts of frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity. Most bursts are under a second and all discharges are under 2 seconds in relaxed wakefulness. Hyperventilation clearly accentuates the frontally predominant spike and wave and poly spike and wave activity. The major of discharges are symmetric in the frontocentral region. Hyperventilation also produces an increase in burst duration with some bursts waxing and waning, but lasting up to 6 seconds in duration. In addition, there are more clearly developed frontally predominant spike and wave and even polyspike and wave complexes noted following hyperventilation.
The technologist tests the patient and does not identify clinical correlates with these bursts. There are a handful of eye movements sometimes seen around the bursts, but no definitive focal features. As the patient transitions in and out of drowsiness, the frontally predominant spike and wave discharges become higher amplitude. Sleep is not sustained. Photic stimulation also does seem to accentuate the discharges, but there are no discharges that outlast the photic stimulation.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Frontally predominant spike and wave complexes of 3.5 to 5 Hz.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No clinical seizures were recorded. These EEG characteristics are highly suggestive of a generalized or inherited mechanism for epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  54 year old male with epilepsy, multiple break through seizures which were tonic clonic, non-adherent with medications.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Topamax.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. The patient is poorly cooperative and poorly responsive during the EEG. He has had 5 seizures.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is quite abnormal. When the patient is not having a seizure, it is a lower voltage mixed frequency pattern with frontal bursts of left frontal theta frequency activity.  There are 5 seizures noted in the EEG which seem to be left frontal or frontotemporal maximum with high amplitude sharp activity. Characteristic frequency evolution is noted. During most of the seizures, the patient is motionless and afterward, he is confused. The technologist does not appear to recognize the seizures. The discharges are typically 1-2 minutes in duration. Additional seizures are characterized by oral automatisms. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is continuing to have seizures.
HR:    96 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Ictal pattern compatible with a focal status epilepticus complex partial status epileptics.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings were reported to the clinical team. Additional evaluation and intervention was implanted..

CLINICAL HISTORY:  44 year old male admitted on February 1, 2012 with stroke, left frontal hemorrhage, and aphasia.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This is an awake and sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is an 8.3 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is a small amount of shifting slowing and there is occasional left frontal focal slowing with isolated theta or delta waves. Features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing.  On rare occasions there are very brief bursts of bilateral attenuation as the patient drifts off to sleep.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Mild degree of background slowing and disorganization.
Shifting slowing with a little bit more shifting slowing identified in the left frontal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is more supportive of a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.  The focal features described above are quite subtle in view of this patient's history.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 42 year old female who is status post right craniectomy and left-sided weakness with change in mental status days after surgery for brain cancer, possible mets and status post radiation.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Decadron, Dilaudid.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Concern for seizures and change in mental status
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while lethargic.  No activating procedures were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a symmetric amplitude of frequencies which are increased over the right hemisphere, maximum in the temporal lobe.  Despite stimulation, there is only mild increase in the faster frequencies.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen continuously at T4/T6 at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-100 microvolts.  This pattern is seen continuously throughout the recording and at times becomes more monomorphic and almost rhythmic, but does not clearly evolve.  It also at times has a more contoured pattern.  This pattern has an associated breach rhythm to it.
Generalized slow waves as described at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts seen diffusely with intermittent periods of more suppressed activity.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due:
1.  Continuous mid to posterior temporal slowing in the setting of a breach.
2.  Marked generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right mid to posterior temporal region, which is consistent with a known surgery and tumor removal.  In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology and may be due to at least in part medication effect, bilateral white matter disease, or toxic metabolic encephalopathy.  No clear seizures were seen.  It would helpful if the patient continues to not improve to have a repeated EEG to reevaluate this intermittent rhythmic pattern in the right temporal lobe, especially is seizures remains a consideration.

HR:    68 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There were no epileptiform features identified.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are an important consideration, a follow-up study is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  42 year old right handed male with new onset seizures, chest pain, numbness and tingling in the fingers, generalized tonic-clonic seizure, tongue biting, and loss of consciousness.  He has a past medical history of anxiety, COPD, thyroid disorder, and degenerative disk disease.

The patient was recorded during wakefulness and stage I and stage II sleep.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation and hyperventilation were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.

There is an excessive amount of frontocentral beta seen throughout the recording.  The patient appears to go into stage I and stage II sleep. ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  46 year old right handed male with refractory epilepsy, 2 seizures recently.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  There are brief sections of the record where it is reasonably well organized with a 6.8 Hz alpha rhythm of 30 mV and a theta frequency background.  More commonly, there is frontally predominant mixed theta delta.  High amplitude or medium amplitude spike and slow wave and sharp and slow wave complexes are observed with many different localizations.  The majority of these are frontal, particularly FP2, but some are FP1, others F8, F7.  Some have a more temporal spread and others are maximum in the central or central parietal regions independently on the right or the left.  The epileptiform activity is focal, but is occasional bifrontal and generalized.
Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background slowing.  The epileptiform activity may occur in pairs, but the two pairs are not always identical epileptiform discharges, although they are usually similar in terms of both occurring on the same hemisphere.  There may be a bit more focal slowing on the right as the patient transitions to sleep. Photic stimulation is remarkable for frequent epileptiform discharges with frontal delta, some of which almost has a spike and wave component on the left, but given the abundance of epileptiform activity, it is not clear that photic stimulation activated the record.
HR:    72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Multifocal epileptiform activity with prominent activity in the right frontal region.
Spike and wave activity seen with photic stimulation, perhaps more on the left.
Background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG suggests an irritative process with epileptiform activity occurring from many different loci.  No seizures were recorded.

Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in slowing, particularly in the central regions and disappearance of the alpha rhythm.  Sleep is not sustained.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.  Hyperventilation did not significantly activate the record.
Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  A mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age in wakeful and limited drowsiness due to:
Mild excess theta.
Mild slowing of the alpha rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is similar to a previous study this year.  Neither EEG captured stage II sleep.  A repeat study capturing sleep is suggested to more completely characterize this patient's epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  31 year old right handed woman with intermittent episodes of lightheadedness and palpitations.
MEDICATIONS:  Metoprolol
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 55 year old right handed woman with recent left coronary who had a stroke, history of hypertension, diabetes, Bell's palsy and an episode of confusion presents for a follow up EEG.

Focal slow waves seen frequently at F7/T3 at a frequency at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
Mild generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz with an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.

Left arterial temporal slowing.
Mild generalized slowing.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  59 year old right handed woman who presents with confusion and change in mental status.  She is noted to have jerking movements of face, hands, and right sided weakness.  At baseline has trouble word finding.  Past medical history significant for hypertension and diabetes.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 9 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontal central beta seen.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Photic stimulation produces no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen at F7/T1 rarely.
Focal slow waves seen at F7/T1 frequently throughout the recording at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-80 mV.

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:

CLINICAL HISTORY:  49 year old right handed male with post traumatic epilepsy after a major cranial and facial trauma at age 19.  Tonic clonic seizures increased in the last 6-8 months ago.  Sinus pathology with sinus tubes.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.   Hyperventilation was not performed due to the sinus problems, but photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat disorganized, but there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is slight shifting asymmetries noted in the alpha rhythm and it is a little faster on the left than the right.  There is also a lit bit of slowing noted at some points when the alpha rhythm is identified and that slowing is on the right.  Arrhythmic delta is noted in the left hemisphere, particularly central temporal region.  There is a suggestion of a breech rhythm with both a beta accentuation noted at some points and some underlying sharp waves.  Unfortunately, artifacts are also noted in the same region.
Brief drowsiness includes vertex waves with transitions in and out of sleep.  Snore artifact is observed.  Photic stimulation elicits a driving response better identified on the right than the left.  The patient continues to transition in and out stage II sleep with vertex waves and spindles, again, some of which are asymmetric.
HR:    66  bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Shifting asymmetries and background disorganization.
Focal slowing in the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a process involving both hemispheres, the left perhaps more significantly than the right.  The sharply contoured slowing and sharp waves are on the left.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 52 year old female with a history of diabetes, hypertension, COPD, end stage renal disease, and stents, presents with seizure activities described as right arm, face movements during dialysis as well as in the setting of hypertensive urgency.
MEDICATIONS:  Clonidine, Lorazepam.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal electrode. Data was recorded in wakefulness and lethargy.  No activation procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background that, at best has a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 8 Hz which appears to be slightly reactive to eye opening.  No normal frontal beta activity is seen.  At times there is burst of frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA) seen throughout the recording.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slow waves at 5 to 7 Hz, 5-7 hertz seen throughout the recording along with intermittent FIRDA activity.
SEIZURES:   None
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Diffuse slow waves.
FIRDA.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  43 year old female with syncope with shoulder dislocation.

HR:    72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are an important consideration, a follow up study would be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 32 year old male with abrupt onset left-sided chest pain and difficulty speaking and abnormal CSF with discitis.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a briefly awake pattern with a 9 Hz alpha rhythm followed by 12 Hz beta frequency activity.  There is an asymmetry noted.  There is disruption of faster frequency activity on the right compared to the left.  With arousal the alpha rhythm appears on the right but not on the left and as the recording continues, there is some posterior delta again a bit more on the right than the left.
HR:    84 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Intermittent generalized background slowing.
Intermittent focal slowing on the right characterized by disruption of faster frequency activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings include and support a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.  In addition, however, the disruption of faster frequency activity on the right suggests an evolving focal process in the right hemisphere.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  38 year old right handed female with epilepsy since childhood.  The patient states she was in a coma for 8 months.  Last seizure about 3 weeks ago.

No sleep is captured. Hyperventilation produces no abnormal discharges. CLINICAL HISTORY:  65 year old woman found down after acute onset of headache in the frontal half subarachnoid status post partial coiling of an ACOM aneurysm, postprocedure noted to have left face, arm, and leg twitching. Past medical history is significant for alcohol abuse, hypertension, and diabetes.
MEDICATIONS:  Nimodipine, Gentamicin, Dilantin, Keppra.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded while comatose.  No activating procedures were performed, other than stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no clear posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  When the patient is stimulated during the recording, there is no clear change in the wave forms.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen at F4, continuously at a frequency of 0.5 to 1 Hz, representing periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLEDs).  It is apparent that with each of these discharges, although not always consistently, there seems to be clinical correlates in the middle of left shoulder twitching.
Generalized slow waves at 2 to 4 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 70 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  Based on the description above, it is likely that the accompaniment of the PLEDs at F4 with the left shoulder twitching is consistent with focal motor seizures.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right frontal PLEDs and focal motor seizures.
Generalized slow waves with intermittent periods of attenuation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals focal motor seizures arising from the right frontal region.  In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regard to etiology but may be partly due to medication effect or cortical injury from the subarachnoid hemorrhage.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 50 year old male with brain tumor, admitted with left sided headache, HIV disease, blurry vision, left sided weakness.
MEDICATIONS:  Percocet, Labetalol
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not possible.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat slow from the left hemisphere.  The alpha rhythm on the left is slow.  The alpha rhythm is disrupted on the right.  In addition, there is focal slowing on the right characterized by 3-5 Hz activity in the left hemisphere.  The focal slowing is a bit more prominent as the patient transitions towards sleep.  There is a slight accentuation of fast activity on the right frontal region seen in relaxed wakefulness and there are a handful of simple sharp waves in the right hemisphere, including F4 and T4.
HR:    90 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing characterized by 3-5 Hz activity on the right.
Disruption of faster frequency activity on the right.
A handful of simple sharp waves in the right hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is compatible with focal process on the right.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  69 year old right handed woman with epilepsy, breakthrough seizure last month when she was anemic.  Seizures include complex partial seizures with a dizzy feeling, automatisms and unresponsive for 10 minutes.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  34 year old right handed woman with VON Willebrand disease, hemophilia B, joint hyperlaxity, and recreational drug abuse.  The patient has episodes of tremors and convulsions which were diagnosed as panic attacks.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  44 year old woman with possible meningitis or encephalitis, headaches, and encephalopathy.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is intubated and poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a markedly slow delta pattern with arrhythmic delta, as well as rhythmic delta.  The frontal delta is relatively rhythmic and the remainder of the brain there is a more of a pattern of shifting asymmetries in terms of the delta.  There is little in the way of variability in the record.
Stimulation of the patient is not documented.
HR:    90 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
A very slow pattern with both frontally predominant rhythmic delta and shifting asymmetries.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a severe disturbance of cerebral function.  Although the pattern described is nonspecific, it can be seen in meningitis.
Characteristic features of a herpes encephalitis are not seen, but any severe brain disturbance could produce the pattern described above.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 48 year old right handed woman with epilepsy following stroke in 2004, last seizure 1 week ago with left arm jerking followed by confusion.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  67 year old woman with increased shortness of breath and productive sputum found to be hypoxic and in respiratory failure and acute kidney failure.  She was found to have decreased movement of the right side and a left MCA hypodensity on CAT scan.  Now she remains less responsive despite decreased sedation.
MEDICATIONS:  ASA, Atorvastatin, Cefepime, Vancomycin, Insulin, Heparin
REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts.  When the patient is stimulated, the background improves and at best posterior dominant rhythm can be seen of 8 Hz in between muscle artifacts; however, this quickly subsides and again there is generalized slowing.  No normal sleep architecture was seen.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slow waves as described above.
Frequent right mid-temporal T4 focal slow waves.
SEIZURES:  None.

Frequent right mid-temporal slow waves.
Generalized slow waves with good reactivity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right anterior temporal region, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology, although not clearly consistent with a clinical presentation of a left MCA stroke.  In addition, there
is diffuse cerebral dysfunction which is nonspecific with regard to etiology.  It may be due, at least in part, to medication effect.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  25 year old right handed male with history of Aspergers and seizures.  He had a seizure and has had frequent increase in seizures.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures, including hyperventilation and photic stimulation, were performed.

The patient appears to go into stage I and stage II sleep. Activating procedures, including photic stimulation and hyperventilation, produce no abnormal discharges.  During hyperventilation he develops a nice well formed delta response.  In addition, at the end of the recording there appeared to be a single benign epileptiform transient of sleep seen only once throughout the recording on the right temporal region at T4.  Also during the recording while he develops drowsiness there appears to be a nice delta burst during one part of the EEG.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  22 year old right handed woman with absence epilepsy since age 7, previously treated with Zarontin, but she recently stopped her medications.
MEDICATIONS:  Iron
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This patient had a clinical seizure during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The best organized EEG is at the end of the record with a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm in a symmetric background.
In the beginning of the EEG, there is a subtle asymmetry.  There seems to be a disruption of faster frequency activity in the right frontal region.  In addition, there is some sharply contoured activity in the left frontocentral region.  In this somewhat sharply contoured background, there seems to be a very subtle underlying sharp wave which can be seen at T3/T5 and C3.
A 10-second seizure is characterized by inability of the patient to respond.  That event occurs at 11:39:11.  It seems to begin with a burst of high amplitude 6.5 Hz activity which transitions to 3 Hz activity over 10 seconds.  Severe high amplitude discharge, but there seems to be a frontally predominant spike and wave discharge and interestingly, the focal features noted earlier on in the record disappear. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
The appearance of an absence seizure.
Focal features with some subtle focal slowing and sharp waves at T3, T5 and C3.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No previous EEGs were available for comparison.  We will try and identify this patient's care providers to arrange for follow-up care.

There is a normal amount of frontocentral beta seen diffusely throughout the recording.  The patient appears to go into stage I and II sleep, and that has been recording by showing posts and K-complexes throughout the recordings. CLINICAL HISTORY:  78 year old woman status post PEA code for 40 minutes, then 6 minutes in the emergency room, now with episodes of diffuse body shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Atropine, Lasix, Lipitor, Hydralazine, Pantoprazole
REASON FOR STUDY:  Myoclonus.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was unresponsive during the recording.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some sweat artifact and movement artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record has a diffusely slow background in between the bursts that I will describe in the next paragraph.  She has a markedly suppressed background with no clear electrocerebral activity.  However, this is in between much artifact which makes it difficult to make any clear final determinations about electrical activity.  In addition, she has bursts of generalized periodic epileptiform discharges with frontal predominant sharp waves and polyspikes that appear to at times increase in rhythmicity to a frequency of about 4-5 Hz and last for about 30-40 seconds.  During these bursts, which are usually symmetric, but at times slightly asymmetric, the patient appears to be clinically shaking and twitching and jerking.  These are consistent with myoclonic jerks.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  As above.
SEIZURES:  Multiple myoclonic seizures as described above.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Frequent myoclonic seizures of prolonged duration in between markedly abnormal suppressed background.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cortical injury and irritability with multiple bursts of generalized periodic discharges and associated jerks consistent with myoclonic seizures.  The interictal pattern as well as the presence of myoclonus in the setting of hypoxic injury suggests a very poor prognosis.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  32 year old right handed woman coming in with new-onset seizure and diagnosed with a right brain tumor for 3 years.  The patient has had a seizure during sleep, tonic-clonic, lasting for 1-2 minutes with no recall of events.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens with well-defined posterior dominant rhythm 9-12 Hz bilaterally which is reactive to eye opening.  There was a shifting and slowing throughout the EKG pattern more on the right than the left.
There is excessive amount of beta waves on the central leads on the right indicative of a breach  rhythm on that side.  The patient appears to go into stage I and II of sleep.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation produce no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Shifting and slowing more on the right side than the left.
Breach rhythm on the right side.
Occasional C4 sharp waves.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to
Shifting and slowing on the right side more than the left.
Breach rhythm on the right side.
Intermittent C4 sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to shifting and slowing more on the right than the left with a breach rhythm indicating focal structural brain lesion consistent with a right-sided brain tumor.  Occasional C4 sharp waves could indicate epileptiform potential

Focal slowing in the left hemisphere, specifically the mid temporal and frontal, as well as parietal region.
Slowing in the right temporal region,
Generalized slowing.

This EEG does not reveal any normal posterior dominant rhythm or sleep architecture.  There are intermittent bursts of diffuse slowing where the beta dissipates but comes back at times.  The patient is stimulated and there appears to be no improvement in the frequencies of the EEG.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slow waves at 2 to 4 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts.
Overlying diffuse beta rhythm that is not reactive to stimulation.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slow waves.
Increased beta activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction which is nonspecific with regard to etiology; however, in this case the overlying beta seen throughout the recording is suggestive of medication-induced encephalopathy,
sometimes seen with benzodiazepines or barbiturates and at times with lithium.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  34 year old woman with liver failure, long history of multiple body jolts with drop and loss of consciousness over the past 3-4 years.  The patient reports a single tonic clonic seizure after taking tramadol.  Scuba driving instruction license. Positive family history of epilepsy.  The patient previously on and off diazepam.  Symptoms alleviated with the use of diazepam.  Also history of anxiety and nervousness.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG includes excess theta.  There is an 8.3 Hz alpha rhythm, but there is excess 6 Hz and 4 Hz activity noted in the background. Features of drowsiness include hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing with some vertex waves, spindles, and POSTS noted in stage II sleep.  Stage II sleep is better organized. There is some more paroxysmal, sharply contoured bursts at C4/T4, but without focal slowing.  There is no after going slow wave that accompanies these discharges. Hyperventilation produces paroxysmal rhythmic slowing. Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR:    96 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Excess theta.
Background disorganization.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are no definite sharp waves or spikes noted in this EEG.  The features described above in terms of C4/T4 focus may represent a normal variant, particularly if there is no after going slow wave which accompanies the discharges.  In this individual with a history of myoclonus and/or tonic clonic seizures, a follow EEG, perhaps in 1 hour with sleep, may be helpful to more fully evaluate this patient.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  43 year old male with melanoma, mets, and status post brain surgery who presented with a generalized tonic clonic seizure.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed  in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with an asymmetry in the frontal central beta seen more on the right.  There is no normal posterior dominant rhythm of 8 Hz to 9 Hz is seen over the left hemisphere.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves and slowing are seen at T4/F8 continuously throughout the recording with associated breech.
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz are seen throughout the recording.  In addition, there is increased diffuse beta seen at times.
SEIZURES:  At times during the recording the frontal sharp waves which appear to become more rhythmic in a pattern of 1-3 Hz and at times evolve to faster frequencies and then stop and start.  This is most consistent with small electrographic seizures.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right anterior temporal sharp waves and slow waves.
Intermittent electrographic procedures in the setting of a breech.
Diffuse slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of localization related epilepsy, with electrographic seizures arising from the right anterior temporal region.  There is also evidence of focal structural dysfunction and irritability, which is
consistent with a known tumor.  These findings were communicated to the team as soon as the EEG was performed.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  18 year old right handed 18-weeks' pregnant with first-ever seizures, family history of epilepsy, aneurysm and eclampsia.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, this patient is in stage 1 sleep with vertex waves.  She transitions in and out of stage 1 sleep to wakefulness.  The patient rapidly transitions in and out of stage 1 and stage 2 sleep.  She is falling asleep during photic stimulation.
There is a single paroxysmal burst noted in that transition which is generalized, but is suspicious for a discharge on the left.  As she is falling asleep during photic stimulation, there are a handful of bursts with isolated paroxysmal 5 Hz activity, but not definitive spike and wave activity.  The individual appears to be excessively sleepy.  Limited wakefulness is achieved.
IMPRESSION:  Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
2 subtle bursts of 5 Hz activity not exactly during photic stimulation, but around the time of photic stimulation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG did not adequately identify epileptiform activity.  There are, of course, constraints in the evaluation of a pregnant patient.  The features
described above are suspicious for a inherited mechanism for epilepsy, but are not definitive.  A follow-up study may be helpful to search for epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  88 year old woman found down, not moving her right side, and aphasic.  CT showed left MCA stroke.  Past medical history is significant for DVTs, hydrocephalus, kidney disorder, and questionable Alzheimer's disorder.
