REASON FOR EEG:  Rule out seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures, including photic stimulation and hyperventilation, were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm at 9-10 Hz on the right hemisphere, but on the left hemisphere there is a disorganized slow frequency with a maximum of left temporal at T1 and 3, which is consistent throughout the recording.  There is a disruption of the fast activity on the left side with a sharp contoured wave and slowing at the left mid temporal. The patient appears to go to stage I sleep.  Activating procedures, including hyperventilation and photic stimulation, produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Disrupted and slow background on the left side with focal slowing, maximum at T1 and T3 consistent throughout the recording.
Disrupted fast activity on the left side.
Sharp waves on T3 with more than 100 mV amplitude.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left sided focal slowing in the mid temporal region, maximum at T1 and T3.
Disrupted fast activity on the left side.
Sharp waves on the left temporal, maximum at T3.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There were no seizures seen in this EEG, however, left sided focal slowing with a sharp wave on the mid temporal region and the sharp fast activity in the left hemisphere can be consistent with white and gray matter underlying structural brain lesions in regard to nonspecific etiology.  Left anterior stroke can also be contributing to the changes on the EEG.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is agitated and wearing a hard collar.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 7 Hz alpha rhythm reaching 50 mV.  There is an asymmetry noted with disruption of faster frequency activity on the left compared to the right.  Unfortunately, there are more electrode issues on the left compared to the right as well.  There seems to be a breech rhythm in the right central region. Features of sleep include hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing with brief vertex waves and then immediately and arousal.  Sweat artifact is also noted.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
An asymmetry between the 2 hemispheres with slower activity on the left.
A modest degree of background slowing and disorganization on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings may be correlated with this patient's imaging.  There is a bit more slowing on the left and what seems to be a breech on the right.   No sharp waves were seen.  When this patient is more cooperative, a follow up, outpatient EEG is recommended to more assess the possibility of epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  56 year old right handed man with previous right frontal clot.  The patient had an episode with loss of consciousness, evaluate for seizures.

A prominent breech rhythm is noted in the right frontal central region and the patient has a craniotomy scar in the right greater than left frontal region. There are rare bursts of focal delta in the right hemisphere.  These occur as the patient transitions towards sleep with concomitant frontal delta, but the focal delta is maximum in the mid temporal region. Hyperventilation produces an increase in theta. Photic stimulation elicits generous driving.  As the patient transitions in and out of sleep, the focal delta is a bit more prominent in the right frontal central region.
HR:    72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Intermittent, right frontal delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Breech rhythm is an anticipated finding following craniotomy.  Focal delta is in the region of this patient's previous surgery.  If seizures are an important consideration, a more prolonged tracing may be of value.

An asymmetry in the alpha rhythm with a somewhat slower pattern on the left.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 55 year old man with intermittent left upper and left lower extremity shaking since yesterday.  While getting hooked up today he had an episode of left arm shaking and head turning to the left.  He also has a history of alcohol use and possible withdrawal.  CT had hypodensity in the right large frontal parietal region.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Keppra,Thiamine
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while lethargic.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow disorganized background with no posterior dominant rhythm or frontal central beta.  The patient has no normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen with a white field, but maximal at T4 with a frequency of 1-3 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV almost continuously throughout the recording with no clear evolution and some intermittent periods of pause for 2 seconds.  These are consistent with periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLED'S).
Focal slow waves at P4 in the right hemisphere maximal at P4 with a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
Generalized slowing at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-40 mV.  Note:  The low amplitude seen diffusely and intermixed with this generalized slowing there is some bursts of 14-15 Hz discharges with a spindle appearance seen diffusely.
SEIZURES:  None seen.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right hemispheric maximal parietal PLED'S and slow waves.
Generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of right hemispheric maximal parietal focal structural dysfunction and irritability, which is consistent with a known lesion seen on the CT.  In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  However, the spindle like discharges suggest it may be, at least in part, due to medication effect.  No seizures were seen during this routine recording.  If there is further concern for intermittent seizures, I would recommend continuous monitoring to evaluate for this occurrence.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is 10 Hz beta.  A 13 Hz posterior dominant rhythm is noted.  Features of drowsiness include an accentuation of the beta followed by vertexes and then K complexes, spindles, and posts. The patient is falling asleep in photic stimulation and then falls asleep shortly thereafter.  Photic stimulation was performed while the patient is falling asleep but still elicits a driving response.
HR:    84 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG demonstrates a very sleepy patient.  The generous beta described above is a nonspecific finding which can be seen in a sleep deficit or in the context of a sleep disturbance.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  67 year old male with prostate cancer, renal failure, and a hepatic mass.  The patient experienced 2 episodes of generalized shaking with his eyes rolling back into his head during dialysis.  Following those he remained obtunded with myoclonic jerking.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is intubated.  He demonstrates many different motor movements during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Background EEG is markedly slow with a mixture of delta and theta.  The patient has various different twitching including eye movements, mouth movements, and jerking of the lower extremities.  None of these are associated with epileptiform activity on the EEG.  There is a small degree of variability in the record and some sections of it are richer in beta than others.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Significant, generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.  This process may be toxic or metabolic.  No epileptiform features were seen.  The patient's involuntary movements were not associated with epileptiform activity.  Evaluation for a metabolic or anoxic cause may be appropriate.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  45 year old right handed woman, with past history of cocaine abuse, diabetes, epilepsy, HIV infection, previously evaluated a year ago after 2 tonic clonic seizures.  The patient reports that she is now drug free, but last week had an argument, her hands became swollen and then she had loss of consciousness with generalized tonic clonic activity and a fall.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Meloxicam, Multiple HIV medications, Lisinopril.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The overall EEG is very low voltage, but there is a discernable 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and successfully produces an increase in the overall amplitude. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta, followed by vertex waves.  Spontaneous arousals include rhythmic alpha frequency activity.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is in stage II sleep and does not significantly activate the record.   This is a technically somewhat challenging EEG in that is a very low voltage study,
HR:    55 bpm
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the second EEG in our lab for this individual with epilepsy, which does not demonstrate epileptiform activity.  A follow up study using
different techniques may be helpful in characterizing any potential epileptiform activity.  A low voltage record is a normal finding.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  25 year old right handed female with episode of shaking, increased heart rate, rapid breathing followed by left arm shaking which progressed to the whole body.  The patient awake and aware of the episode.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal single lead EEG electrodes.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.

TECHNICAL DIFFICULTY:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation produced no abnormal discharges, however, see below for photic stimulation.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
EVENTS:  During photic stimulation, the patient started having slow movements of her head side to side then started twitching her upper extremities and moving her body towards the right side and appeared to be unresponsive to commands.  This episode lasted for a period of about 40 seconds and then she remained with her eyes closed and appeared to be slightly more responsive.  Minutes later, photic stimulation was performed again after she had opened her eyes and appeared to have followed commands.  At that point she started jerking her left shoulder slowly, then trembling her upper extremities and again falling towards the right side of the seat.  This second episode lasted for about approximately a minute and 20 seconds.  During both episodes, the EEG revealed a normal awake background with no epileptiform abnormalities and no EEG correlate to this behavior described above.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG with two episodes of shaking during photic stimulation with no EEG correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and asleep EEG with no seizures or epileptiform discharges.  The episodes captured above had no EEG correlate and are consistent with nonepileptic events.  No seizure.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  49 year old right handed male with post traumatic epilepsy, closed head trauma injury in 1980, atonic seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Phenobarbital, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This is the patient's fourth EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat slow and disorganized.  There is some bursts of posterior predominant slowing.  There are also bursts of frontally predominant high amplitude 3 Hz spike and slow wave activity.  This activity demonstrates some asymmetry, maybe a little bit more prominent in the right frontal region on the left.  It starts to transition to more of a 4-5 Hz spike and wave activity.
Although it is present in relaxed wakefulness, it also occurs during hyperventilation.  Most bursts are less than 2 seconds in duration.  No impairment of awareness is noted with the bursts.
As the patient becomes drowsy, following hyperventilation, the bursts are again seen, but are a little bit slower and transition to a more of an almost 3 second burst with a high amplitude frontal spike, followed by rhythmic delta, which may or may not have a spike.  All of the activity has bilateral representation, but some has a field more prominent on the right.
Photic stimulation may well have accentuated this activity and, again, in photic stimulation sometimes there did seem to be a more clearly defined right frontal spike and slow wave complex before the left, but not always.
At the end of the record when the patient is maximally awake, there is little in the way of background slowing.
Even when the EEG is well organized, the alpha rhythm remains low at 8 Hz.
HR:    64 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity, which was accentuated by hyperventilation and photic.
Occasional shifting asymmetries, particularly in the posterior region.
A slow alpha for an adult of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are features in this EEG which support a focal mechanism for epilepsy.  Other features support a generalized mechanism, particularly with 3-5 Hz frontally predominant spike and wave activity, which was accentuated by hyperventilation and photic stimulation.  This suggests more than one possible contributor to this patient's epilepsy.
Of note, some of these findings were seen in an EEG in March 2011, but not in October 2010 or September 2011.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  50 year old male with status epilepticus and bilateral MCA infarcts, right greater than left.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Midazolam, Vancomycin, Zosyn.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is described as poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a significant asymmetry.  The activity from the right is low voltage, relatively featureless.  From the left, there is more theta.  There is also wicket-like rhythm at T1.  There are sharp waves, but they lack after-going slow waves.  The patient is febrile, intubated and poorly responsive.  As the recording continues, the quality of the EEG recording declines as the pace melts off.  Stimulation of the patient produces artifact.  The patient is markedly diaphoretic, but with a temperature of only 99.6.
HR:    104 bpm and irregular.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Markedly slow and suppressed pattern on the right.
A slow pattern on the left with prominent wicket, but no definitive sharp waves or spikes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Previous EEGs were not available for comparison.  If seizures are an important consideration, a follow-up study when the patient is not so sweaty is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 35 year old man with hypertension, pericarditis, alcohol abuse, HIV, lupus who presents with seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Ativan, Protonix, Lovenox.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with an additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness only.  Activating procedures are not performed except minor photic stimulation was performed for a couple of seconds.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient is recorded mainly during wakefulness.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
EPISODES:  During the recording, the patient had 2 episodes where at the beginning he would start stretching his arm and becoming tense then his body started trembling slowly in his hands and his feet and developing whole body trembling lasting for about 1 minute 15 seconds, not being able to follow commands during the episode and not recalling the code word.  Afterward, he woke up and asked what happened and he was crying.  During this first episode, there was no clear EEG abnormality or changes and after the event there was a clear posterior dominant rhythm that could be changed.  During the event, there were just multiple artifacts.  A second event occurred minutes later while photic stimulation was started.  He started trembling slowly and the whole body started shaking irregularly and moving toward the left side.  This episode lasted about 2 minutes and again afterward the patient remained unresponsive for some time.  During the entire episode, the EEG did not reveal any epileptiform activity or any EEG correlate.  There was a lot of muscle artifact and after the event there was a clear normal posterior dominant rhythm seen during the recording.  Two episodes of diffuse body shaking with no unresponsiveness and no EEG correlate.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   The 2 episodes with diffuse body shaking had no EEG correlate which is consistent with the diagnosis of a nonepileptic event.  No seizures or epileptiform activity were seen during the recording.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  19 year old left handed male admitted on April 22, 2012 with new onset seizure characterized by loss of consciousness, face falling forward from a standing position, with 2 minute tonic clonic seizure, followed by 5-10 minutes of confusion.  Past history of seizure.
MEDICATIONS:  Lovenox, Percocet,
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 8.7 Hz alpha rhythm of 40 mV.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta. Hyperventilation is performed early in the record producing an increase in theta, following this the patient becomes drowsy with attenuation of the alpha rhythm and an increase in both beta and theta.  Vertex waves are noted in stage I sleep.  Vertex waves are slightly asymmetric.
In stage I and stage II sleep frontal beta is quite prominent. Hyperventilation produces a small amount of theta.  The patient is drifting into and out of stage II sleep during photic stimulation, which does not otherwise activate the record.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  Asymmetry in the vertex waves could be related to a head measuring error, therefore, this should not be considered pathological.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  48 year old male admitted on May 11 with alcohol withdrawal seizures versus epilepsy.  Evaluate for viral encephalitis.  CT scan showed diffuse cerebral edema.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Vancomycin, Acyclovir.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is intubated and unresponsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates a diffusely slow pattern.  It is a mixed frequency pattern with generous beta and theta.  There is intermittent attenuation of the background lasting about 1-2 seconds.  In addition, although there is some technical issues, the frontal regions sometimes demonstrate a bit more attenuation.  EEG is overall relatively symmetric. Stimulation of the patient produces an attenuation of the background.
HR:    96 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background with a mixed frequency markedly slow pattern.
Intermittent attenuation of the background.
Flattening of the activity.  Flattening of the EEG in response to stimulation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are nonspecific.  This EEG could be seen in a diffuse, serious disturbance of many different causes.  There were no specific hallmarks of a herpes encephalitis.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   39 year old right handed woman with 2 spells in September 2011.  The patient unable to describe the spells.

Rhythmic temporal theta drowsiness appears as the patient transitions into drowsiness and then very brief stage I sleep. Hyperventilation produces a small amount of theta.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is drifting off to sleep.  There is scant driving, but again the temporal theta.
HR:    90 bpm
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  54 year old woman with acute right-sided weakness, numbness and slurred speech for 45 minutes.  History of meningioma resection October 2011.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm which is symmetric and reactive.  There is mu activity identified, but testing was not performed to confirm this.  A prominent breach rhythm is noted with accentuation of amplitude in the left hemisphere including frontocentral and temporal regions.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is subtle, intermittent focal slowing noted from the left hemisphere.  Other features of drowsiness include an increase in beta. Photic stimulation elicits a vigorous driving response with harmonic and supraharmonic driving.  Hyperventilation produces minimal background slowing.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Subtle focal slowing from the left hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The breach rhythm is an anticipated finding following craniotomy and is quite prominent for this individual.  The subtle left central slowing is in the region of this patient's craniotomy defect.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  50 year old woman with history of epilepsy, learning disability, hypothyroidism, admitted for an ankle fracture.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  Post partum, 27 year old female, who delivered at 26 weeks gestation on April 4, 2012 with eclampsia, positive family history of nieces and nephews with epilepsy.  MRI demonstrates posterior abnormalities.

HR:    66 bpm

Slowing of the alpha rhythm.
Left temporal sharp waves.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  50 year old woman found down without pulse.  CPR was started 5-10 minutes and now with rhythmic jerking and left eye with gaze preference.  Past medical history is significant for diabetes, hypertension, and bipolar disease.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Lovenox, Protonix, Metoprolol, Lipitor.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Status post code.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using a standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while unresponsive.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontal central beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.  During the recording the patient is stimulated and there is no real change in the background.  I will describe the background and the abnormal discharges in the next paragraph.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  The EEG is fully comprised of a background predominated by bilateral frontal central predominant sharp waves, followed by slow waves in a periodic pattern at 2 Hz in a monomorphic rhythm that does not change, consistent with generalized periodic epileptiform discharges (GED's) occurring throughout the entirety of the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slow waves.
Continuous GED's.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction and irritability, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  However, the generalized
periodic discharges in the setting of hypoxia are suggestive of a very poor prognosis.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  62 year old male, status post cardiac arrest, now with myoclonus.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Fentanyl, Valproate Acid, Vecuronium.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Status post cardiac arrest, now with myoclonus.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during unresponsiveness and comatose.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely attenuated, or almost completely suppressed background, with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontal central beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
During the recording there is intermittent bursts of anterior predominant spike and wave, as well as polyspike and wave appearing at 5 Hz in bursts that may last up to 20-30 seconds.  They appear to be mainly symmetric, but with some frontal predominance at times.  During these bursts the patient is seen on video to be having regular diffuse marked jerking of the truncal muscles associated with each one of these bursts.  This is most consistent with myoclonus.
Generalized attenuation of background.
SEIZURES:  See myoclonus described above.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
myoclonus and diffuse suppression of the EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cortical dysfunction and irritability, which is consistent with the known hypoxic injury.  However, it is possible that the intermixed diffuse attenuation may be at least in part due to medication effect.  Lastly, the myoclonus seen after a hypoxic injury suggests a poor prognosis for significant neurological recovery.

Focal slowing characterized by intermittent disruption of faster frequency activity in the left frontotemporal region.

Underlying disorganization.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  48 year old female found down with a PEA code on the 28th of March, shocked a total of 3 times, then having a second PEA code for 22 minute and a third one for 50 minutes.  By the time she had arrived, she was cooled and now she is having myoclonic jerks.
MEDICATIONS:  Versed, Depakote, Midazolam, Heparin.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Myoclonic jerks.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while unresponsive and having jerks. No activating procedures were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely low attenuated background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or normal frontocentral beta.  Patient had no normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Throughout the recording, there are frequent frontally predominant and right more than left sharp waves which appeared to start and decrease in frequency for about 2-10 seconds with some minimal spread to the left hemisphere.  During these discharges, the patient appears to move and it is difficult to be clear of the precise locations of the discharges.  In between these discharges, there is diffuse attenuation and cortical suppression in the EEG.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Frequent bilateral frontally predominant discharges with some right-sided asymmetry.
Evidence of diffuse cortical attenuation in between the bursts.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cortical dysfunction and attenuation in addition to frequent myoclonic seizures which appears to have a bilateral frontal onset and lateral right-sided predominance.  It is possible that the known left cortical stroke is causing this asymmetric appearance.
The presence of these discharges after a posthypoxic event carries a poor prognosis.  The lower attenuation is likely due to diffuse cortical dysfunction, however, there may be some influence due to the sedation medications.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz 40 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm.  The patient's seizure is identified and is characterized in the EEG at 11:26. The left hemisphere demonstrates more significant arrhythmic delta activity and slowing of the alpha rhythm.  In addition, there is left frontal delta. As the patient drifts off to sleep, arrhythmic delta activity is much more prominent in the left hemisphere with some shifting slowing on the left.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
An interhemispheric asymmetry with a slow and disorganized pattern on the left.
Shifting slowing on the left, some of which is sharply contoured in the left parietal region.
Mildly slow background on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures were recorded.  The left hemispheric focal slowing is consistent with a history of stroke.  The mild background slowing on the right is more supportive of a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.

Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz with an amplitude of 20-70 microvolts seen throughout the recording mainly in wakefulness.
There is a single focal sharp transient seen at F3 throughout the recording which has a morphology very suspicious for a sharp wave, but not clearly definitive, only seen once throughout the recording. Mild excessive theta during wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards  to etiology.  The single sharp transient
seen in the left frontal region is suspicious, but clearly epileptic.  A repeat EEG with deeper stages of sleep may be helpful in confirming diagnosis.

Background slowing.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  29 year old right handed male with history of febrile convulsions at age 3.  The patient developed recurrent seizure while drinking water, had epigastric rising and then eyes rolling back in head with loss of consciousness and left arm and leg shaking for one minute. To more fully evaluate this patient's epileptiform potential, a repeat tracing with stage II sleep and hyperventilation can be scheduled as an outpatient.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 24-year-old woman with history of sexual abuse and mental disease with a motor vehicle accident in June, since then has been having seizures that month and just had a premature baby on 02/01/2013.
ARTIFACTS:  None.
MEDICATIONS:  Cannot remember medications.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  Patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures include hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontal central beta.  The patient was recorded in wakeful and stage I and stage II of sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation which produced no abnormal discharge, however, during photic stimulation there was event which I will describe in the next section.  Stage I and stage II sleep were seen.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow wave seen intermittently at T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
EPISODES:  During photic stimulation, specifically at 11 Hz, the patient all of the sudden starting shaking her head side to side followed by generalized shaking in an irregular fashion of her whole body while she had her eyes closed.  This continued to occur for about 3 minutes, at which point the patient stopped and appeared to be tired.  During the recording there was a lot of diffuse artifact, however, in between the shaking normal posterior dominant rhythm can be seen and no epileptiform correlate was seen during the episode.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal electroencephalogram due to left mid temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left mid temporal region, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  The episode described above had no EEG correlate and is consistent with the diagnosis of psychogenic nonepileptic event.  No seizures or actual epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  31 year old right handed gentleman with 1-year history of epilepsy.  The patient was a steel worker who fell 20-30 feet 2 years ago.  Suffered a loss of consciousness. INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized with a 10 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in theta.  The drowsy pattern is relatively symmetric and on rare occasions, the slow activity seems to be slightly slower on the right compared to the left.  This is more apparent with the use of frequency analysis.  Hyperventilation produces bilateral theta.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous, bilateral driving with harmonic and supraharmonic driving.  There is vigorous harmonic driving and supraharmonic driving identified from both hemispheres.  The driving response is higher amplitude on the left compared to the right, but the overall frequency differences are relatively symmetric.  On some occasions, the supraharmonic driving seems to be bit a more prominent on the right.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:   EEG is at the limit of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Simple visual analysis of the EEG would not otherwise identify the subtle asymmetries described above.  In this individual with head trauma, the subtle features on the right may be evaluated by imaging.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  62 year old woman status post code in the field, intubated on June 24, 2012 at 1848.  Initially moving all extremities, now with only eye movements, COPD, oxygen dependent.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Simvastatin, Zosyn, Vancomycin, Flagyl, Solu Medrol
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is intubated and comatose.  The technologist observes that the patient has intermittent eye movements.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates primarily a burst suppression pattern with a markedly suppressed pattern.  In the bursts of activity that occur, there are bursts of high amplitude, sharply contoured faster frequency activity.  Some of these bursts begin on the left.  The duration of the bursts varies from 3 seconds to 10-15 seconds.  Many of the bursts, particularly those with high amplitude activity, are associated with eye blink.  At the beginning of a burst there are typically three eye blinks.  In addition, in some of the discharges when the patient has another high voltage burst within that burst, eye blink will be seen again. Later sections of the record demonstrate a burst and attenuation pattern with lower voltage theta, but the initial sections are markedly suppressed.
HR:    120 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Burst suppression pattern.
What appears to be an ictal pattern with consistent pattern of eye blinking with high voltage discharges.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a very worrisome pattern, 18 hours following cardiac arrest.  Because of the correlation between the discharges on the EEG and the patient's clinical symptoms, this EEG should be considered ictal.

A post-anoxic pattern with discontinuity and bursts of fast activity.

EXTENDED EEG RECORDING SAME DAY
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Additional EEG recording is performed as the patient received IV Depakote.  Following the infusion of the IV Depakote, the patient continues to have a diffusely slowly and somewhat discontinuous pattern with brief bursts of fast activity.

IMPRESSION:  This EEG was remarkable for:
A post anoxic pattern which was somewhat discontinuous with bursts of fast activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform seizures were seen.  These findings are worrisome following anoxic insult.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  69 year old man with history of a right MCA stroke as well as AFib, CHF, and hyperlipidemia that presents with an episode of possible syncope with shaking of the head for a few minutes.

There is also frontocentral beta that can only be seen over the left hemisphere.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness, stage 1 and stage 2 sleep.  Some of the sleep architecture was best observed only over the left hemisphere.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen frequently at F8/T4.
Focal slow waves were seen continuously over the right hemisphere, maximal at F8/T4.  There was also loss of faster frequencies over this hemisphere.

HR:   80 bpm and irregular
SEIZURES:  None.

Right anterior temporal sharp waves and slowing with loss of faster frequencies.
Intermittent left anterior temporal slowing.

In addition, there is evidence of focal structural dysfunction in the right hemisphere, maximal in the right anterior temporal region, which is consistent with the known stroke.  Lastly, there is some evidence of left anterior temporal slowing, focal cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  Unknown age man who presents with gunshot wound x4.  He presents with asystole, transferred, now to have twitching of the shoulders, loaded with Depakote.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Keppra, Depakote
REASON FOR STUDY:  Facial twitching and Asystole.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during unresponsiveness.  No activating procedures were performed.  An EMG electrode was also added to the recording.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Continuous repetitive myogenic artifact seen over the right hemisphere.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffuse slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that, at best, reaches 6 to 7 Hz.  It does not appear to be reactive to eye opening.  There is no normal frontocentral beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture.  There are no activating procedures performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slow waves at 5 to 7 Hz seen continuously throughout the recording, at times with intermittent suppression and with a slight asymmetry in amplitude with higher frequencies over the left than the right.
There are focal sharp waves seen at CZ frequently
There are focal slow waves at CZ at 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts.
The patient has twitching noted over the right hemispheric electrodes that occurs irregularly but almost continuously throughout the recording with no clear EEG correlate on the left hemisphere.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slow waves.
Right hemispheric decreased amplitude.
Central sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction which is nonspecific with regard to etiology but may be due, at least in part, to medication effect.  There is some loss of faster frequencies over the right hemisphere which may imply some cortical damage or overlying fluid collection in that region.  Lastly, there are also signs of focal cerebral dysfunction and irritability over the central region, which has a high correlation with acute injury in that region.  The facial twitching has no EEG correlate and may represent myoclonic jerks arising from an unknown source in the left hemisphere which cannot be seen in EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  18 year old right handed female syncopal spell lasting 25 seconds.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This was an awake and a sleep record in very drowsy individual.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm, exceeding 70 mV with posterior slow waves of youth.  In drowsiness there is hypersynchronous rhythmic higher amplitude theta frequency activity hypnogogic, hypersynchrony.  There were 1 or 2 points of head rocking artifact and there were 1-2 bursts which are slightly asynchronous. Hyperventilation produces hypersynchronous rhythmic high amplitude, somewhat sharply contoured theta frequency activity, but no definitive spike and wave activity. The patient transitions in and out of stage II sleep with vertex waves and spindles.  Other features of drowsiness include the hypersynchronous rhythmic theta.
Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving with harmonic and supraharmonic driving.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  This EEG demonstrates multiple normal variants for a young adult.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There was no definitive spike and wave activity, although hyperventilation did produce some rhythmic high amplitude theta.  There were a handful of slightly asynchronous bursts as the patient transitions to drowsiness.  If absence seizures are an important consideration, a repeat fasting EEG, perhaps with a second hyperventilation session maybe helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  74 year old woman with left-sided weakness and slow speech and confusion with 2 episodes of twitching of the left hand and twisting of the lips.
MEDICATIONS:  Famotidine, Probenecid, Hydralazine, Aspirin.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Left-sided weakness with twitching of the right hand and lips.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a mildly diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 8 Hz and can only be seen over the left hemisphere.  Over the left hemisphere, there is normal amount of frontocentral beta, however, none can be seen over the right hemisphere.  Patient appears to be awake and go into stage change of sleep, but the classic sleep architecture is not seen. Activating procedures were not performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow sharp waves seen periodically in the right hemisphere usually maximal at F8/T4, however, at times more maximal at F8, at times even more maximal at T6 and some of them appear to be maximal at FP2.  These sharp waves were occurring periodically at a frequency of 0.5-1 Hz with an amplitude of 20-70 microvolts.  The periodicity is consistent with periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLEDs).
Focal slow waves in the right hemisphere maximal at T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
Generalized slow waves at a frequency of 5-7 Hz with an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts seen continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right hemisphere periodic lateralized epileptic discharges maximally in the midtemporal region, although with broad field.
Mild generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of right hemispheric maximal in the midtemporal region, but with a broad field, cortical dysfunction and irritability, which is consistent with an acute lesion in that region.  In addition, there is evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures were seen.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta and a 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm. The patient transitions to stage 2 sleep with vertex waves, spindles and POSTs during photic stimulation.  Despite this, as he transitions in and out of sleep during photic stimulation, there is a driving response.  Hyperventilation produces a small amount of slowing.
HR:    78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG is wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There were no epileptiform features identified.  If additional information is needed, a follow-up, more prolonged study or sleep-deprived study might be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 54-year-old woman with migraine headaches, depression and intermittent hand shaking lasting 5 minutes in duration.  This occurs 4 to 5 times per week, followed by generalized pain and confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Risperidone, Effexor, Ativan, Lidoderm, Reglan, Pentazocine, Maxalt, many others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  The patient seemed to be very uncomfortable during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the overall EEG includes a low voltage pattern with generous beta and scant, 11 Hz alpha rhythm.  Drowsiness is characterized by a generalized beta pattern followed by theta.  Even when the patient is becoming drowsy, there is a great deal of muscle artifact noted.
Photic stimulation elicits a vigorous driving response bilaterally.  Heart rate 60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Within normal limits this was technically somewhat a challenging EEG in what appeared to be an anxious individual.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  The generous beta may be due to this patient's medications.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   29 year old right handed female with a history of anxiety and vitamin D deficiency who complains of right-sided tingling and numbness for 50 minutes, two previous episodes several years ago on the left.
MEDICATIONS:  Protonix, ASA, Lovenox, Klonopin.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Paresthesias.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation and hyperventilation were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 to 10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient has a mild excessive amount of beta seen diffusely.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation and hyperventilation produce no abnormal discharges.  The patient reached stage I and stage II sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  Please note that diffuse beta may be seen as an effect of the use of benzodiazepines or barbiturates at times.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  29 year old right handed woman with fibromyalgia and epilepsy.  She has 2 types of seizures, including grand mal seizures which began as a funny smell and then clenching of hands and teeth.  These may occur in sleep.  In addition, she has seizures characterized by an aura, followed by blanking out for a few minutes.
MEDICATIONS:  Trileptal, Klonopin, Pristiq, Pamelor.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness the background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is a small amount of background theta. Hyperventilation produces an increase in theta. Wicket is noted.  Photic stimulation elicits a vigorous driving response at essentially all flash frequencies.
Muscle artifact is noted in relaxed wakefulness.
HR:    84 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Wicket is a normal finding.  If further characterization of this patient's epilepsy is needed, a more prolonged record capturing stage II sleep is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  32 year old man with a history of TBI in 1998, admitted after having an episode of tonic-clonic seizure, brought to the emergency department where he had another seizure and confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Pantoprazole, Depakote
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  The patient's impedances were inappropriate, specifically in the occipital electrodes which caused some multi-electrode artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that appears to reach 9 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient had some normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures did not produce any abnormal discharges.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep, stage I/stage II.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
One single sharp transient maximal at F3 seen in the recording while drowsy.
Occasional small amplitude sharp spikes seen at T3, only in stage I sleep, although not seen over T2.  The morphology is most consistent with benign epileptiform transients of sleep (BETS).
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal limited EEG with one suspicious left frontal sharp transient and BETS.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The significance of the left frontal sharp transient is unclear.  A repeated recording should be performed.  Particularly in this patient where the impedances and the quality of the recording was poor, it should be repeated free of charge.  The BETS are benign and do not indicate a high correlation with an epileptogenic focus in that region.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  42 year old right handed man who presents with a history of syncope at 9 p.m. associated with nausea, the neighbors walked in and he started shaking and had loss of consciousness for 5-10 minutes with awareness of his surroundings.
MEDICATIONS:  Percocet, Atropine, Alprazolam, Lovenox, Protonix.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Episode of loss of consciousness.

TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 10-11 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is an excessive amount of beta seen diffusely throughout the recording.  No activating procedures were performed.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and stage I sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  Excessive beta may represent effect from benzodiazepines or barbiturates.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 54-year-old woman with a history of hyperlipidemia, hypertension, seizures, schizophrenia, and CAD, presents with altered mental status, had acute change in mental status and was minimally responsive.
MEDICATIONS:  Lorazepam, Protonix, Lisinopril, Percocet, Plavix, Lovenox

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a mildly slow background at 8 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a normal amount of frontocentral beta.  No activating procedures were performed.  The patient was recorded only in wakefulness.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Mild excessive theta in wakefulness at 5 to 7 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction and slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  45 year old right handed male with history of hypertension, hyperlipidemia, back pain, and now with difficulty finding the right word.
MEDICATIONS:  Lovenox, Baclofen, Lisinopril, Atorvastatin, Elavil, Amitriptyline, Protonix, Pantoprazole, Dexamethasone
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient was extremely drowsy, transitioning in and out of sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm which is symmetric and reactive.  The patient transitions in and out of wakefulness to stage II sleep with vertex waves, K-complexes, spindles, and POSTS. Hyperventilation produces a small amount of slowing.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR:    78 bpm
IMPRESSION:   EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified in the record, but the patient appears to be quite sleepy.  This could be related to a sleep deficit or an underlying sleep disturbance.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  73 year old right handed man with a history of end-stage renal disease, diabetes, hypertension, CAD, CHF and prostate cancer, recently admitted for weakness, diaphoresis, near syncope, and possible seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Zosyn, Acetaminophen, ASA, Atorvastatin, Protonix, Ditropan, Heparin
REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while poorly responsive.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation. No normal sleep architecture was clearly seen.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded while poorly responsive.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  During the recording at times there is some intermittent transient bursts of faster frequencies in the theta range that seem to be related to stimulation.  We did perform photic stimulation which revealed no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:   Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts seen almost continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slowing with some good activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  The good reactivity suggested maybe due at least in part to medication effect.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.

Generalized slowing.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  50 year old prisoner with diabetes, schizophrenia, and blindness.  The patient has a history of right hemiparesis, status post tracheostomy with refractory prolonged seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Keppra, Depakote.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient's lower extremities only are shackled.  She is awake and answering questions, but is not 100% cooperative.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is low-to-medium voltage.  There is an overall theta frequency pattern with a glimpse of an alpha rhythm, but the patient does not particularly even cooperate with the concept of eye opening and eye closure.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in slowing.
HR:    120 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Excess theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  If refractory epilepsy is an important consideration, more prolonged EEG recording will be undertaken.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  53 year old man with change in mental status, found on the side of the road, unresponsive with septic shock, acute kidney injury, upper GI bleed, noted to have right arm shaking, right eye deviation, and was placed on pentobarbital for cerebral edema and seizure monitoring.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Pentobarbital, Phenylephrine, Dopamine.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures and pentobarbital coma.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during unresponsiveness.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG reveals no abnormal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  Overall, it reveals a very low amplitude diffuse slow record with an overriding EKG artifact and no clear cerebral activity.  There is no normal sleep architecture and no activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Almost completely suppressed EEG with no cerebral activity.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Complete suppression of any normal cerebral activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of marked diffuse cerebral dysfunction with no cerebral activity which may be due, at least in part, to medication effect.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.  The findings on this EEG were reported to the consult team right after it was done.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  Twenty-five-year-old woman anemia, leukopenia, and an episode of syncope lasting 5 minutes in July 2012.
MEDICATIONS:  Omeprazole.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10Hz alpha rhythm.  Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm with rhythmic central theta.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.  Hyperventilation does not significantly activate the record.  Heart rate 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage I sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified in the record.  Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are an important consideration, a follow-up study capturing deeper stages of sleep may be valuable.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  83 year old with left carotid stenosis, intracranial stenosis, recurrent hemiparesis.
MEDICATIONS:  Colace, Senokot.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates stage I sleep with occasional vertex waves and POSTS. Stimulation of the patient produces theta.
HR:    90 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG in a hypersomnolent patient due to:
Excess theta.
Slowing of the alpha rhythm.
Shifting slowing left more than right
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There were no epileptiform features identified.  This EEG supports a bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function.  The sleep recording is relatively symmetric, but in the limited wakefulness there may be more of a disruption of faster frequency activity on the left.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  81 year old female with a history of right a MCA stroke as well as 79% right carotid stenosis who presents preoperative for a right carotid endarterectomy.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Right carotid endarterectomy.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement with the additional of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Then record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a normal amount of  frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation and posed no abnormal discharges, but a nice photic driving response was seen.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen frequently at F7/T3 as well as F8/T4, slightly more on the left than the right at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Independent bilateral anterior temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the bilateral anterior temporal regions, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology, but may be due at least in part to the previous stroke.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 64-year-old man with a history of seizures and diabetes who presented after a fall and noted to have a change in mental status, a large bifrontal intracerebral hemorrhage and edema.
MEDICATIONS:  Lovenox, sertraline, Zocor, gabapentin, phenytoin, and glipizide.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while lethargic. Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
Technical difficulties:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 7 Hz and does not appear to be reacting to eye opening.  There is the lack of normal frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded while in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation which produced no abnormal discharges.
Abnormal discharges:
Focal slow waves seen in the right hemisphere, maximal in the F8/T4 electrodes at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts seen almost continuously throughout the recording.  In addition, there is generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz seen continuously throughout the recording.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to right hemispheric slowing, maximal in the anterior temporal region, in addition to generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right hemisphere, maximal in the temporal region with additional moderate diffuse
cerebral dysfunction, both of which are nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 60 year old right handed woman with a history of migraine headaches, tachycardia and a family history of epilepsy.  On May 7, she began to have 5 seizures characterized by tonoclonic activity with loss of consciousness and  incontinence.  The seizures occur out of sleep.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel  EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy EEG.  It was an extended study in an attempt to obtain sleep, completing 40 minutes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm at 40 microvolts with generous, frontocentral beta activity.  Wicket activity is noted as is rhythmic temporal theta of drowsiness.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in theta.  Photic stimulation produces bilateral driving.
HR:    90 bpm
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Given the normal variant identified above, a repeat study capturing deeper stages of sleep would be helpful to search for epileptiform features in this patient with newly diagnosed epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  36 year old female with history of seizures, presents with multiple seizures and postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Vimpat, Topamax, Neurontin, Percocet.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness, but mainly in sleep.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background, however, there are short episodes of wakefulness where for very short periods there appears to be a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz that appears somewhat reactive to eye opening.  Otherwise, the patient, even while awake there appears to be some diffuse slowing and quickly drowses off to stage 1/stage 2 sleep.  There is some normal frontocentral beta seen in the short wakeful state.  Photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-70 microvolts which is seen almost continuously throughout the recording and then quickly the patient goes into sleep.
There are some focal sharply contoured waveforms at F8/T4 seen on rare occasions.  Two of them had a clear morphology of BETS, however, one of them had a much higher amplitude and was suspicious for epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1.  Generalized slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures were seen.  Please note that the single sharp epileptiform transient was only seen once and it is not clear if it is pathologic.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  82 year old woman found unresponsive, not moving her right side with 2 tonic-clonic seizures in the emergency room.  Left MCA infarct, multiple medical problems.
MEDICATIONS:  Versed, Keppra
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is quite agitated.  There is an extraordinary amount of muscle artifact.  She receives Versed during the EEG with little benefit.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Underneath the muscle and movement artifact, there seems to be a theta frequency background.  Surprisingly, despite the artifacts, there is a periodic complex in the left hemisphere maximum at T1, but with involvement of F7 and T3.  It overall has a generous field of spread throughout the temporal region on the left and the frontal regions.  The periodic complex is seen in approximately every 2 seconds.  It does not evolve.  The patient is talking during the discharge.
HR:    90 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing.
A periodic complex noted on the left temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This was a high amplitude, but relatively simple periodic complex.  It did not evolve.  It is more likely to be a hallmark of an epileptiform process than an active ictal discharge.

TYPE OF STUDY:  Routine EEG.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 50-year-old ambidextrous gentleman with history of right subcortical CVA with hemorrhagic transformation and pre-existing epilepsy with left frontotemporal encephalomalacia who presents for a preop EEG for right carotid endarterectomy.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient's medications include Dilantin, nortriptyline, aspirin, lisinopril, Tricor, and fluoxetine.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the lab using a standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to one channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation are performed to see tracing captures wakefulness only.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was asymmetric and characterized by 9-10 Hz in frequency, 30-40 microvolts in amplitude seen in the left occipital region and 8-8.5 Hz on the right side which attenuated with eye opening.  There was right hemispheric slowing in theta frequency and attenuation with loss of faster frequencies noted throughout the study. There were intermittent focal slowing in the left frontal and anterior temporal regions consisting of 5-6 Hz theta frequency activity with 30-40 microvolt amplitude lasting for 1-2 seconds, occasionally with a field to the left anterior and mid temporal region.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple/frequencies and result in no driving response. No epileptiform activity with seizures were seen in the study.  Heart rate was 90-100 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing wakefulness only due to:
Right hemispheric attenuation and slowing with loss of faster frequencies.
Intermittent left frontotemporal slowing during wakefulness.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Diffuse attenuation and loss of faster frequencies in the right hemispheric could be seen in the structural lesions of the underlying cerebral cortex or fluid accumulation in the extra-axial space.  Right hemispheric slowing is suggestive of subcortical structure or functional abnormalities. Focal left frontal and temporal slowing could be suggestive of an underlying structural abnormality in the left hemisphere or left frontotemporal dysfunction.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No epileptiform abnormalities were seen in this record. This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.
Please note that the patient is tachycardic.
