REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 59-year-old male with a history of seizures for a month.  Last one 1 week ago consisting of generalized tonic/clonic shaking with tongue biting.  Sometimes he has blinking tremors and staring.  Also has hypertension and reflux.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Restoril, and Zantac.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a normal amount of frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded in wakeful state and sleep.  Activating procedures include hyperventilation.  It did reveal some normal discharges which will be described next.  Photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
Heart rate:  54.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Burst of generalized spike and wave at 3.5 to 4 Hz were seen frequently throughout the recording.  These bursts were anterior predominant and symmetric and lasting a maximum of 2 seconds.  There appeared to be no clinical changes during these episodes that the technician could note.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of idiopathic generalized epilepsy.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 44-year-old man with 2 seizures on 10/11/2012 and 10/17/2012, both events with loss of consciousness, fall, shaking, and confusion.  He feels they are stress related. A past medical history of diabetes, hypertension, and depression.
MEDICATIONS:  Zoloft, Buspar, Klonopin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and a single lead EKG electrode.  Patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep, stage I and stage II.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record open to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep, stage I and stage II.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Intermittent F7/T1 focal slowing seen at 2-4Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.  At  times this focal slowing appears to become monomorphic and rhythmic consistent with temporal intermittent rhythmic delta activity.  At times is also sharply contoured.
HEART RATE:  84 and regular.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to intermittent left anterior temporal slowing as well as intermittent left temporal intermittent rhythmic delta activity, (TIRDA).
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  In addition, the finding of TIRDA has a high correlation with seizures arising from that region.  No actual seizures were seen in this recording.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 56-year-old woman who was originally admitted with abdominal distention and mental status change, subsequently found to have small bowel obstruction, requiring surgery.  Status post surgery the patient aspirated and was intubated on 10/05/2012.  The patient is currently comatose with frequent eye twitching.  Past medical history is significant for hypertension, dementia, schizophrenia, and seizure disorder.
MEDICATIONS:  None listed.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The background consists of frequent isolated bursts of high amplitude generalized spike and wave discharges followed by 3 to 5 seconds of burst suppression.  The longest burst of activity lasts approximately 6.5 seconds.  During longer bursts, there is predominantly bifrontal EMG artifact and rhythmic 2 to 3 Hz diffuse sharply contoured activity.  Review of the video demonstrates that brief bursts of activity as well as longer bursts of activity accompanied by eye flutter as well as rapid low amplitude head shaking.  These bursts are not time locked with ventilator artifact.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.
FINDINGS:
Burst suppression with suppression lasting 3 to 5 seconds.
Generalized frontally predominant spike and wave discharges that are intermittently accompanied by 3 to 6 second bursts of frontally predominant EMG artifact and diffuse 2 Hz bursts of activity.  No clear electrographic seizures are captured.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 22-minute EEG due to frequent bursts of generalized spike and wave discharges, periods of 2 to 5 seconds of background suppression, and intermittent up to 6-second bursts of rhythmic activity that on the video correlates with eye fluttering and head rocking.  These findings indicate severe diffuse cerebral dysfunction, significant cortical irritability, and increased risk of seizures.  No clear electrographic seizures are captured.  These findings were discussed with the Neurology consult team at the time of the recording.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  Nearly 23 minutes.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation was performed.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 46-year-old woman with past medical history of seizures, right hemispheric stroke, hepatitis C, who presents with a possible seizure.  As per history, patient had an episode characterized by left upper extremity shaking that lasted a few minutes.  This is the second such episode since August of 2012.  Patient stopped taking Keppra about 2 days ago.
CURRENT MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, metformin, Coumadin, insulin, Zocor.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is right to left interhemispheric asymmetry with slow waveforms over the right hemisphere.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the left hemisphere consists of a well formed and modulated 9 to 10 Hertz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  Over the left hemisphere, there is preserved anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the right hemisphere is unstable and reaches about 9 Hertz alpha.  There is no clear anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The background over the right hemisphere consists of a mixture of polymorphic theta and delta activity with under-riding faster frequencies.  Slowing is more pronounced over the anterior temporal/frontal region.  The patient briefly falls asleep by the end of the recording.  Sleep spindles are captured only over the left hemisphere.  Brief 1 to 3-second bursts of frontally predominant rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA) are captured.  Occasional poorly formed, sharply contoured waveforms observed over the right midtemporal region with phase reversal over T4-T6 electrode.  Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation results in occipital driving only over the left hemisphere.
FINDINGS:
Continuous moderate slowing over the right hemisphere, most pronounced over the anterior temporal/frontal region.
Sharp waves over the right mid temporal region.
No electrographic seizures.
Asymmetry of sleep architecture with sleep better formed over the left hemisphere.
Asymmetrical occipital driving with driving only observed over the left hemisphere.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 23-minute awake and briefly asleep EEG, due to continuous focal slowing over the right hemisphere that is most pronounced over the frontotemporal region and occasional epileptiform discharges over the right mid midtemporal region. These findings indicate focal cerebral dysfunction that carries increased epileptogenic potential. FIRDA is observed in encephalopathies, increase intracranial pressure, deep white matter lesions. No electrographic seizures are captured.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 63-year-old female with a history of hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and right sensory neural hearing loss presents to us due to paresthesias on the left face and arm, found to have a right frontotemporal mass.
MEDICATIONS:  Ancef, labetalol, hydralazine, morphine, potassium, midazolam, gentamicin, dexamethasone.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some multiple electrode artifact seen throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness, stage I and stage II sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
Heart rate:  60 and regular.
Abnormal discharges:
Continuous focal slowing seen at C4/T4 at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 microvolts.  At times this is sharply contoured.
Intermittent focal slowing at times seen at F7/T3, frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to continuous right central temporal focal slowing as well as some intermittent left anterior temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural dysfunction in the right central temporal region, which is consistent with the known mass.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  85 year old right handed male with recurrent episodes of syncope versus possible seizures. Pacemaker, hypertension, hyperlipidemia and aspiration difficulties.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Norvasc, ASA, Metoprolol, Simvastatin
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This patient is extremely sleepy and spends much of the record in stage 1 or stage 2 sleep.  Brief, maximal wakefulness includes a well organized pattern with a low voltage, 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  In the transition in and out of sleep, there are mild shifting asymmetries, but well-defined vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTs are noted in stage 2 sleep. IMPRESSION:   EEG is within normal limits, although there is very little wakefulness.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  53 year old male who presented with right-sided weakness, left MCA infarct, COPD, HIV, hypertension, gout.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Corgard.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is intubated and poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a markedly abnormal pattern.  The initial sections of the record demonstrate an asymmetric pattern with marked suppression of activity on the left.  The right initially demonstrates low-to-medium voltage rhythmic delta.  As the record continues, there is some theta on the right.  There are also some portions with generalized attenuation of the background.  Frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity is noted, right greater than left, as is eye blink artifact.
HR:    78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Marked attenuation or suppression of activity on the left compatible with a left middle cerebral artery infarct.
Markedly slow pattern on the right with rhythmic delta.
Frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a severe, bihemispheric process, but the process on the left suggests marked disruption of cerebral activity.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 56-year-old man with a history since the age of 18.  Seizures are reported as cessation of speech, followed by humming, followed by generalized tonic-clonic convulsions.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, Abilify, ciprofloxacin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation is performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm reaches 9 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  Intermittent bifrontal monomorphic theta activity, right greater than left, is captured during wakefulness.  Voltages are overall low.  During sleep, symmetrical sleep spindles and K complexes are noted.  Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation does not produce additional abnormalities.  Intermittent polymorphic theta activity is observed over the right anterior temporal region.  Additionally, occasional sharp waves with after-going slow waves are noted over the bilateral anterior temporal regions, right greater than left, with a phase reversal over F7/T1 and F8/T2 electrodes.  A heart rate of 160 beats per minute is noted on the single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:
Mild slowing, right anterior temporal region.
Occasional right anterior temporal and less frequent left anterior temporal sharp waves with after-going slow waves.
Stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and asleep 22-minute EEG due to mild right anterior temporal slowing and occasional independent bilateral anterior temporal epileptiform discharges, right greater than left.  Focal slowing indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, possibly structural in etiology.  There is an epileptogenic focus over the bilateral anterior temporal regions, right greater than left.

There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  Lambda waves are occasionally captured.  During sleep, vertex waves, sleep spindles, K complexes, and POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep) are captured.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving.  A regular rate is noted on the single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:
No epileptiform discharges.
Stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep 22 minute EEG.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  26 year old right handed woman with epilepsy, seizure free since 2008, 2007 EEG demonstrates a 3.5 spike and wave activity.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, Zonisamide.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with symmetric reactive 10 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity.  In relaxed wakefulness, prior to hyperventilation, there are bursts of high amplitude, frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity, which are relatively symmetric.  The discharges are less than 2 seconds and start with a 5 Hz discharge transitioning more to a 3 Hz over time.  The bursts are so brief and they are not associated with impairment of awareness.  The technologist gives the patient tasks to do and she is able to count during these brief bursts which wax and wan.
Hyperventilation accentuates the bursts of frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is a more of a polyspike component to the bursts.
Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.  It does not accentuate the epileptiform activity.  The epileptiform activity does occur around the time of stimulation, but it also occurs even just prior to her following the stimulation.
HR:    96 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Bursts of high amplitude frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These bursts are quite prominent.  None were longer than 2 seconds in duration and none were associated with impairment of awareness.  The
technologist did extensive testing of the patient to try and see if there would be a pause during the bursts, but she was not able to demonstrate any impairment of awareness.

Focal sharp waves seen at T5 and at times moved more forward to T3 and very rarely at T6.

Lastly there is evidence of  generalized cerebral dysfunction, of which is nonspecific with regards to etiology and may be due at least in part to medication effect.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  Sixty-year-old female with history of hypertension, diabetes, right-sided facial pain, nausea, vomiting, sudden confusion, right gaze deviation, then recurrent shaking.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long-term EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during lethargy and later on wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  During the first 3-4 hours of the recording, there is a diffuse delta pattern and slowing throughout the recording with a more prominent right hemispheric focal slowing maximal in the occipital lobe and some intermittent right temporal sharp waves.  This is also superimposed to O2 PLEDs that were seen continuously at 1-2 Hz.  About 4 in the morning, this pattern appeared to improve and faster frequencies started to appear over the central and frontal regions of the recording.  The EEG continued to improve over the next hours with some normal sleep architecture and the faster frequencies over the right hemisphere.  By 2 p.m., the faster frequencies and the posterior dominant rhythm during wakefulness appears to be 9 Hz with a normal frontocentral beta.  At that point, there is intermittent right hemispheric slowing, but not as frequent as before and some intermittent FIRDA (frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity).  By the end of the recording, there is a lot of muscle artifact which makes it difficult for visualization, permits limits visualization of the EEG.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  As above, described as at onset, there were O2 PLEDs and focal slowing in the right hemisphere, maximal at O2 with some intermittent T4 sharp waves and generalized slowing.  This continued to improve until the end of the recording where the EEG almost normalizes.  However, there is some intermittent FIRDA.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right occipital periodic lateralized epileptic discharges and right midtemporal sharp waves in addition to right hemispheric slowing maximal at the occipital region which improved and with intermittent FIRDA.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural dysfunction and irritability of the right hemisphere, maximal in the occipital region in addition to some generalized dysfunction.  All of these findings appear to have improved markedly over the last 24 hours.  No seizures were seen.

INTRODUCTION:

During very brief wakefulness, there is a posterior dominant rhythm of 8.5 Hz with anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  Throughout the majority of the study, the patient is asleep with vertex waves, sleep spindles, and POSTS seen.  Also, REM sleep is observed by the end of the recording.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  No epileptiform discharges were observed.
FINDINGS:  Primarily asleep study to REM sleep at the end of the recording.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal primarily asleep and briefly awake EEG due to excessive drowsiness and REM sleep captured on a 22-minute study.  These findings indicate excessive drowsiness.  In a routine EEG, a finding of REM sleep is abnormal.  In a proper clinical setting, further investigation to causes of excessive sleepiness may be considered.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine EEG does not exclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 47-year-old male with HIV and 6 months of vertigo.  Vertigo occurs without head movement.
MEDICATIONS:  Risperdal and Celexa.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity.
Hyperventilation produces slowing of the background.
There are sections of the record when the patient is maximally awake, such as during photic stimulation where the alpha rhythm is somewhat slow, 7.8 to 8.3 Hz.
Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
Heart rate:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a mildly abnormal EEG due to:  Intermittent slowing of the alpha rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were noted.  The mild background slowing is a nonspecific finding and can be seen in a diffuse disturbance of cerebral dysfunction due to many different causes.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow up study may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  53 year old man with MS and recurrent seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and during lethargy.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some electrode artifact and muscle artifact seen throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no posterior dominant rhythm and no normal frontal central beta.  There was no normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.  The background is consistent of generalized slow waves at a delta frequency at 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen frequently at F3/C3 and sometimes at T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV seen continuously throughout the recording.
At two points during the study there was a rhythmic run of A1 sharp waves that lasted 5-10 seconds with no clear evolution.  There was no video correlate or clinical correlate to this discharge.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left frontal central and temporal sharp waves.
Two runs of sharp waves in the left temporal lobe
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from the left frontal central region and/or the mid temporal region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in this region which has a high correlation with a structural lesion in that region.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  78 year old woman found down with low blood glucose and now in change in mental status.
MEDICATIONS:  Heparin, Zosyn, Vancomycin
REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while unresponsive.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a disorganized slow background that consists of bursts of diffuse theta activity which in the posterior region reaches at best a frequency of 7-8 Hz.  In between these bursts of theta activity, there appears to be complete suppression activity that lasts as long as 10 seconds in between bursts.  The bursts consist mainly of theta, delta activity, at times having some vertex-like waves suggestive of stage 1 sleep, although no clear sleep-wake cycle is noted.  During the study, the patient is stimulated and there appears to be a reactivity with the EEG with some faster frequencies and some muscle activity coming through.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Again, generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz with intermixed burst suppression lasting up to 10 seconds.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slowing.
Burst suppression.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of marked cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology, but may be due in part to medications or a toxic metabolic encephalopathy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  39 year old right handed male with history of right ankle pain and narcotic abuse, now with episodes of loss of consciousness with diffuse body shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term EEG monitoring was performed at bedside for 4.5 hours using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were performed.  Continuous spike detection software, as well as seizure detection software, as well as patient alarm events, and nurses notes were used to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm with normal frontal central beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures produce no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
Events:  The patient had about 9 events which consisted of him pressing the alarm, suddenly his arms would become flexed, and he would become stiff and grimacing his face, lasting for about 20-30 seconds, during the episode and after which he would be unresponsive for another 2-3 minutes.  The behavior was very similar to the ones that he described before and every episode remained the same.  During these episodes the EEG would have a diffuse muscle artifact, but underlying it there would be a normal posterior dominant rhythm and no epileptiform discharges prior to the flexing, posturing, or after when he would remain unresponsive.  It looked like a normal EEG.  Sometimes with the flexor posturing he would hip thrust during the event.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG with events with no EEG correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The events that were captured and described as above had no EEG correlate and are consistent with psychogenic nonepileptic seizures.  No epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  49 year old right handed female with seizures since age 14, presents with refractory episodes, here for seizure classification.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness.  Hyperventilation was performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9 to 10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is an increased amount of beta activity seen diffusely throughout the EEG.  During the recording, the patient is recorded only during wakefulness.  The only activating procedure that is performed is hyperventilation, during which she has an episode which I will describe below.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
Events:  During this recording, while the patient was doing hyperventilation she suddenly stopped responding, started moving her throat and jerking her back and forth repeatedly.  At times she would move to the left and then to the right.  During this episode, the tech stimulated her feet and she would respond and at times appeared to follow commands, but would not verbalize.  The whole episode of unresponsiveness lasted some minutes, but with the clinical presentation lasted about 12 minutes.  During this recording, the EEG revealed prominent muscle artifact but a nice posterior dominant rhythm could be seen at times and normal EEG could be seen at times throughout the episode.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake EEG with an episode of unresponsiveness as described above with no EEG correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is diagnostic of a nonepileptic event, likely psychogenic in nature.  Otherwise this is a normal awake EEG and no seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded while poorly responsive.  Activating procedures were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  There was no normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz seen continuously throughout the recording at an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.
Triphasic waves seen at 0.5-1 Hz with anterior predominance seen almost continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:    None.
HR:     114 and irregular
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 26-year-old female with history of renal calculus status post cystoscopy and seizures.  Her seizure was 4 years ago, last seizure was 3 days ago.  Per patient, she has 2-3 seizures per month described as upper extremity shaking with unawareness.
MEDICATIONS:  Xanax, Percocet.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm was 10-11 Hz in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is diffuse low amplitude beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Stage I sleep is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and posts.  A stage II was characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles.  Hyperventilation results in symmetric slowing of the background.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response.  Heart rate was 70 beats per minutes and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through stage II sleep.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are a clinical concern, the repeat EEG or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.  The generalized beta activity could be due to medication effect including benzodiazepine, barbiturates, or could be due to anxiety or hyperthyroidism.  Clinical correlation is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  73 year old male with acute right posterior MCA infarct with hemorrhagia conversion.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly slow and low voltage.  It is somewhat lower voltage and slower on the right in comparison to the left.  There is a bit of head rocking artifact, but also some slower delta picked up in the right occipital and posterotemporal region.  Stimulation of the patient produces an alpha rhythm briefly which is not sustained.  The patient transitions into stage 2 sleep with scant, low voltage spindle.  An abnormal EKG with significant EKG artifact throughout the EEG.
HR:    90 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Significant background slowing.
An asymmetry with a lower voltage pattern on the right in comparison to the left.  In addition, although there is more EKG artifact on the right, there is a bit of more slowing in the right posterior quadrant.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function affecting gray and white matter.  No seizures were recorded and there were no epileptiform features.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   32 year old right handed woman with new onset of seizures who was unconsciousness, unable to speak, and left face twitching.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Lovenox
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term EEG monitoring was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Continuous spike detection software, as well as seizure detection software, patient events, and alarms, as well as nurses events were noted to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  In the middle of the night some electrodes became dislodged and there is some electrode artifact by the end of the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm at 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontal central beta.  Activating procedures and photic stimulation produce no abnormal discharges.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness and sleep and normal stages I to III with sleep are recorded.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
Episodes:  The patient had 3 episodes throughout the recording.  The first one occurred at 12:34 p.m. at the onset of the recording where she started having left facial twitching, followed by unresponsiveness while continuing to have left facial twitching.  This event lasted for about 2 minutes and then the patient became reactive again.
The second event occurred at 8:18 p.m.  The patient suddenly started having left facial twitching and grimacing, as well as tightening her arms, as well as becoming unresponsive.  This was followed by staring and mouth movements.  The episode lasted for over 4 minutes.
At about 3:32 a.m. the patient suddenly started having diffuse body shaking and rocking, as well as facial twitching.  This was much more severe than the other ones.  She continued rocking, jerking, and being unresponsive.  Then after stopping the jerking she laid in bed and remained unresponsive and started moving her mouth rhythmically in a chewing fashion.  The whole event lasted for about 4.5 minutes.
The EEG during the whole 3 events revealed a normal posterior dominant rhythm and no epileptiform correlate to any of the events.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG and 3 non-epileptic events.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.

FINDINGS:
Mild diffuse slowing.
Disorganization.
Symmetry.
No electrographic seizures.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal greater than 1-hour EEG due to moderate diffuse slowing and thus disorganization.  These findings indicate nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction, that in this patient could partially be related to the medication effect.  No electrographic seizures are captured.  These findings were conveyed to the primary team and to the neurology consult team at the time of the recording.

RECORDING LENGTH:  23 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is an 80-year-old woman with past medical history of dementia, TIA, left frontal infarct.  She is admitted now from a nursing home for change in mental status.  The patient had a staring episode lasting a few minutes.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm reaches 9 Hz activity. There is an anterior-to-posterior gradient but it is weak.  Additional diffuse polymorphic theta activity is present. Nearly continuous bifrontal polymorphic delta activity is captured as well.  Frontally predominant generalized delta activity (FIRDA) is observed occasionally.  Sleep is very fragmented with some sleep spindles captured.  No epileptiform discharges are captured.
FINDINGS:
Mild diffuse slowing.
Bifrontal slowing.
FIRDA.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal 23-minute awake and asleep EEG due to mild diffuse slowing, moderate bifrontal slowing, and occasional frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA).  Diffuse slowing is a nonspecific indicator of diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  Focal bifrontal slowing may be indicative of bifrontal structural abnormalities. FIRDA (frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity) is a nonspecific finding and could be seen in encephalopathy, increased intracranial pressure, and deep white
matter abnormalities.  No epileptiform discharges are captured.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

Left more than right anterior temporal slowing.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  48 year old right handed woman with catamenial epilepsy.  She had a seizure, not related to her period, which was a prolonged complex partial seizure followed by a second complex partial seizure and then tonic-clonic seizure on March 27.  Still somewhat confused.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  This is an awake and asleep EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness with stimulation, the background EEG includes a 9.5-Hz alpha rhythm, but early in relaxed wakefulness the background becomes somewhat slower with a bit of 6-Hz activity.  Relaxed wakefulness and hyperventilation both accentuate focal slowing in the right hemisphere with right temporal focal slowing and sharp waves noted at T2 and F8.  Following hyperventilation, the patient waxes in and out of a drowsy state.  There are some bursts of generalized mixed theta-delta.  This is a paroxysmal burst of slowing, somewhat irregular, a little bit more so on the right than the left. Photic stimulation elicits minimal driving bilaterally.  Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Intermittent slowing and disorganization in apparent wakefulness.
Right temporal focal slowing, accentuated by drowsiness and more significantly by hyperventilation.
Right temporal focal sharp waves, accentuated by hyperventilation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a focal mechanism for seizures.  It is similar to previous studies.  The overall background slowing appears to have improved compared to a previous report last week.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  62 year old woman found down, cardiac arrest for 20 minutes.

Absence of normal electrocerebral activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of electrocerebral silence which in the right scenario is consistent with an EEG with presentation of breath death.
However, there are multiple artifacts due to the EKG and ICU which make it difficult to make a definite conclusion about this electrocerebral silence.

Stage 2 sleep.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  51 year old right handed woman with depression, anxiety, schizophrenia and epilepsy.  Seizures are characterized by shaking with tongue biting and incontinence, last seizure was 1 week ago.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is excess theta in apparent wakefulness.  There is sometimes a background of more rhythmic theta.
Interictal findings for this individual include frontal fast activity, right more so than the left with a subtle frontal sharp wave underlying and a sharp wave can be seen at  Fp2-F4 with a small amount of bilateral representation.  Rare, higher amplitude left mid temporal sharp waves were identified.
Hyperventilation was performed early in the record producing rhythmic slowing particularly in the frontal regions.  The hyperventilation response included some arrhythmic slowing. Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Frontal fast activity with a right frontal underlying sharp wave.
Left anterior temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a focal mechanism for epilepsy and raises the possibility of more than one mechanism for seizures.  Left anterior temporal sharp waves, right temporal sharp waves and bifrontal sharp waves were noted in a previous EEG in 2008.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  23 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 63-year-old woman with past medical history of atrial fibrillation and metastatic ovarian cancer who underwent left frontal craniotomy on 08/21/2012.  She now presents with expressive aphasia and generalized weakness.
MEDICATIONS:  Dexamethasone, Lovenox and metoprolol.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and  T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The background consists of low to moderate amplitude  polymorphic mixture of theta and delta with occasional triphasic wave forms.  Additional intermittent theta and delta are captured over the left frontocentral region.   Sleep is not captured.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  No electrographic seizures are seen.  A single EKG lead demonstrates irregular heart rate with a heart rate up to 150 beats per minute.
FINDINGS:
Moderate diffuse slowing.
Focal left frontocentral slowing.
Cardiac arrhythmia.
No electrographic seizures.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 23-minute awake only EEG due to moderate diffuse slowing and focal left frontocentral slowing and triphasic wave forms.  Diffuse slowing indicates etiologically nonspecific cerebral dysfunction that in his case could partially be related to toxic metabolic etiology.  Triphasic waves are observed in different forms of encephalopathy.  Focal left frontocentral slowing could be secondary to an underlying cerebral dysfunction that is structural in etiology and is consistent with the patient's history of left frontal craniotomy.  Cardiac arrhythmia with heart rate up to 150 beats a minute is noted in the single EKG lead.  No clear electrographic seizures are captured.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 43-year-old male with schizophrenia and 20 year history of epilepsy, transferred from Episcopal after 4 tonic clonic seizures with subsequent seizures on route to the hospital.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Dilantin, Depakote, Haldol, clindamycin.

As the recording continues, tactile stimulation of the patient results in an alerting response with eye opening, lower voltage fast beta pattern and spontaneous movements of all extremities of the patient.  As the recording continues, the patient starts to drift back towards stage II sleep.
Heart rate:  78 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to: Replacement of normal background with low voltage and generalized slow pattern.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Brief alerting response identified is a positive finding for this individual with recent status epilepticus.  No epileptiform features were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 36-year-old woman with migraines and seizures.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  21 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 53-year-old man brought after having 2 witnessed episodes of generalized tonic/clonic convulsions.  The patient received Versed and Ativan.
MEDICATIONS:
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  During maximal wakefulness, the posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated 10 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient that is less well preserved over the left hemisphere.  Intermittent polymorphic theta and delta activity are captured over the left frontal/anterior temporal region.  Additional faster frequencies are captured over the left frontal leads.  During sleep, vertex waves, sleep spindles and K complexes are captured.  Sleep architecture is more pronounced over the left hemisphere.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.

FINDINGS:
Intermittent focal moderate slowing over the left frontal/anterior temporal region.
Breach artifact over the left anterior temporal/frontal central region.
Prominence of sleep architecture over the left hemisphere.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal 21-minute awake and asleep EEG due to intermittent moderate focal slowing over the left anterior temporal/frontal region.  This finding indicates underlying cerebral dysfunction that could be structural in etiology.  Breach artifact indicates a defect in the skull.  No clear epileptiform discharges were captured.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine EEG does not preclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Preop for aortic arch replacement.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 29-year-old man with a past medical history of aortic valve replacement in 2012 with complications and with IV drug use, diabetes, depression, anxiety, hepatitis C, with complaints of leg and back pain, found to have an aortic and bilateral iliac thrombus and he is preop for aortic arch replacement.

INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while awake and drowsy and stage 1 sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 5 Hz which appears somewhat reactive to eye opening.  There is some faster frequencies in frontocentral beta seen intermittently and some stage 1 sleep architecture appears to be seen.  Overall, there is a diffusely slow background in the delta range seen almost continuously throughout the recording.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:

Generalized slow wave at 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts is seen almost continuously throughout the recording.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right midtemporal region, with an additional diffuse cerebral dysfunction, both of which are nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  The primary team was informed of these abnormal findings in the EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 62-year-old male with liver disease, hypertension, and stroke and epilepsy admitted after found unresponsive with incontinence, possible witnessed shaking spell.  Now confused.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient was confused.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not possible.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  It is diffusely slow with high amplitude, sharp waves and spikes from the left hemisphere particularly in the frontotemporal region.  Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in muscle.  When the technologist stimulates the patient, the patient is inattentive but there is no increase in epileptiform activity.
This is a technically challenging EEG for an individual who his very active with tactile stimulation but as he drifts off to sleep, the epileptiform activity is well defined.
Heart rate 75 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Markedly slow background.
Left anterior temporal spikes and sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG suggests a highly epileptiform focus.  This is likely a postictal record but ongoing vigilance is essential.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 35-year-old woman with a history of new onset seizure activity in July of 2012, described as head shaking and generalized body shaking lasting 5 minutes with biting her tongue afterwards and being confused for about 30 minutes.  The patient had another event on 08/29/2012, she complained of a frontal headache.  She has a family history of seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Simvastatin, clonazepam, topiramate, Neurontin, omeprazole, Percocet, Tramadol.

TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm at 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is an excessive amount of theta throughout the recording.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness, stage I and stage II sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.  There was no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  A normal awake and sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  Please note that the excessive theta may be seen as part of medication effect usually due to benzodiazepines or barbiturate effect.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 30-year-old male with diabetes, confusion, fever, and shortness of breath; evaluate for encephalopathy.
MEDICATIONS:  Vancomycin, antibiotics, clonidine, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This is a bedside recording performed on a patient who is confused.  The overall background is slow.  At times, there is a glimpse of an 8 Hz alpha rhythm, but most of the background is a mixture of theta with a smaller amount of beta.  The 8 Hz alpha rhythm clearly attenuates with eye opening, and much of the record includes more of a low to medium amplitude theta pattern with occasional rhythmic delta.  The patient is drowsy, yawning with some hypersynchronous rhythmic theta.
Heart rate 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Rhythmic slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is most characteristic of an encephalopathy.  There were brief sections of the record with an alerting with an 8 Hz alpha rhythm.
There were no focal or epileptiform features identified. If seizure is an important indication, a followup study in the lab may be of use.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 65-year-old male with a past medical history remarkable for depression, hypercholesterolemia, diabetes and seizures.  He described seizures as feeling pressure in his head and shaking of the right hand.  He also described loss of consciousness with generalized shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient is taking medications for high cholesterol, depression, and diabetes.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the laboratory using the standard International 10/20 System of electrode placement in addition to one channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation was performed, photic stimulation was not performed. This tracing captures wakefulness through drowsiness.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, alpha rhythm is 9-10 Hertz in frequency, 30-50 microvolts in amplitude, seen in all critical region which attenuates with eye opening.  There is small amount of low amplitude, which was frontal central beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically, drowsiness is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm and slowing of the background and access of motion and eye-blink artifact.  Heart rate was 50-60 beats per minutes.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Normal EEG, does not exclude diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 27-year-old right-handed woman with history of staring spells, lasting 2-3 minutes with post event sleepiness, started when she was a kid, without any workup at that time.  The patient reports aura as dizziness and she states she has event on a daily basis.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the laboratory using the standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement, in addition to T1 and T2 electrodes and 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness through stage II sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 10.5 to 11.5 Hz in frequency, 30-40 microvolts in amplitude seen in the occipital region which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontal central beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Stage I sleep is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact, as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and POSTS.  Stage II sleep is characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles.  Hyperventilation results in symmetrical slowing of the background activity.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response.  Heart rate was 70 to 80 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through stage II sleep.  No epileptiform abnormalities were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are clinical concern, a repeat EEG or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 41-year-old male with recent onset of epilepsy, 3 nocturnal seizures with tongue biting.  Each seizure was associated with a low blood glucose.  The patient had violent swinging movements with one of the seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Insulin, Keppra, and enalapril.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity.  In relaxed wakefulness there is a small amount of shifting slowing with occasional, independent right or left temporal slowing.
Hyperventilation was performed early in the record producing an increase in theta, a little bit more so on the left than the right.  Some of this was rhythmic, but some was somewhat arrhythmic as well.
Sleep was characterized by a prominent increase in beta.  Spindles were noted.  Again, there was a small amount of shifting slowing noted in sleep.  Vertex waves and POSTS were also seen.  As the patient transitions in and out of sleep, there was some rhythmic, hypnagogic hypersynchrony.
Photic stimulation was performed at the end of the record when the patient was awake.  A normal background was noted at that time.  Despite the tech's attempt to maintain him in an awake state during photic stimulation, the patient started to drift off to sleep during photic.  A driving response was elicited.
Heart rate:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to: Occasional bursts of shifting slowing noted as the patient transitions in and out of drowsiness and in hyperventilation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No sharp waves or spikes were seen.  There were no specific hallmarks of an underlying seizure disorder.  The shifting slowing noted in the transition to sleep is characteristic of that seen in older adults with cerebrovascular disease.  It is, however, a nonspecific finding.  In this individual with new onset seizures, perhaps a more prolonged sleep recording may be helpful in the search for epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 44-year-old right-handed woman with epilepsy since 18 months of age. The patient reports grand mal, petite mal and complex partial seizures.  The seizures occur during sleep, the last seizure was 10 days ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Gabapentin, Provera, Excedrin, ibuprofen, Dulera, may others.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz 40 microvolt alpha rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Prominent mu activity is noted with 8 Hz activity in the central regions particularly on the left although testing was not performed to confirm this.  Mu rhythm was also noted in the right central region as the recording continued.  Features of drowsiness include anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.  The overall EEG is relatively high voltage with a very prominent mu activity.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.  Drowsiness produces an increase in beta.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving.  In some sections of the record there is a question of an alpha sub-harmonic.
Heart rate 72 b.p.m.
IMPRESSION:  This is an interesting but normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient has an interesting but normal EEG including the mu activity and the alpha rhythm with the alpha supra-harmonic.  No epileptiform features were identified.  If additional information is needed to characterize this individual's epilepsy, a more prolonged study can be considered.  Although benzodiazepines were not listed in this patient's medications, benzodiazepines or other similar medications might account for the prominent beta noted in the record.

TYPE OF STUDY:  Routine EEG at bedside, awake and sleep.
DIAGNOSIS:  Rule out seizure.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 33-year-old right-handed woman, with past medical history of diabetes and moyamoya disease status post surgical revascularization who presents with 3 days history of headache and transient slurred speech.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient's medications include aspirin.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using the standard international 10/20 system of electrode placement in addition to 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness through stage II sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  in the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 11-12 Hz in frequency, 40-50 microvolts in amplitude seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontal central beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically, stage I sleep is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifacts as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and posts.  Stage II sleep is characterized by the presence of K complexes, sleep spindles, and posts.  There are occasional bursts of left anterior and mid temporal slowing at 67/T3 in wakefulness and sleep consisting of 3-3.5 Hz delta frequency, mixed with 4-5 Hz theta activity lasting for 1-2 seconds.  There were no epileptiform discharges or seizures noted during this recording.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response.  Heart rate was 60 beats per minutes and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to the left temporal slowing seen during wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings are suggestive of a structural abnormality in the left hemisphere or left temporal dysfunction in this case secondary to history of left MCA stroke.  There were no epileptiform activities or seizures noted during this recording.  If seizure activity is a clinical concern, a bedside EEG monitoring may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 47-year-old male with episodes of blacking out and visual blurring.  The patient states that he was walking and has a sudden feeling out of the ordinary and then visual obscurations.
MEDICATIONS:  None.

Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
Heart rate 84 BPM.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified.  The generous beta described above is a nonspecific finding which can be seen in the context of anxiety, normal variant, or the use of a benzodiazepine medication.  The low voltage pattern described above is also a normal adult pattern.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 31 year old right handed woman with generalized anxiety disorder, constant seizures, depression, and heart murmur.

There is also some challenging electrode impedances noted with a fair amount of eye movement artifact. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in beta.  POSTS and rare vertex waves are noted in stage I sleep.  There are rare spindles. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is asleep.  Despite this, there is a driving response.
HR:    66 bpm

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are identified.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  The prominent beta may be due to medications for anxiety or other causes. This EEG was compared to a previous EEG in 2009, this is her second, normal, EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 25-year-old right-handed woman with epilepsy since age 13, currently seizure free since age 16.  The patient previously had nocturnal tonic/clonic seizures.

Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic central theta followed by vertex waves and spindles.  There is a slight asymmetry noted in the frontocentral regions, which could be attributed to electrode placement.  Prominent posts were noted in sleep.  Hyperventilation produced some increase in amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation elicited vigorous bilateral driving.
Heart rate:  68 BPM.
Occasional head rocking artifact was noted.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 73-year-old woman who presents with episodes of loss of consciousness and generalized stiffness lasting for 5 minutes with confusion.  She has working diagnosis of Hashimoto's encephalitis due to rapidly progressive dementia.  Currently on steroids.
MEDICATIONS:  Risperdal, levothyroxine, famotidine, Keppra, steroids.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using a standard 10-20 electrode placement with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while lethargic.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some frontal electrode artifact seen frequently throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The records opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontal central beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture.  Photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
Overall the background consisting of diffusely slow delta 2-4 Hz frequency discharge, which is intermixed with some theta frequency discharge.  In addition, there are frequent anterior predominant deflections with an anterior to posterior lag most consistent with triphasic waves seen frequently, at times rhythmically, in a pseudoperiodic fashion.  In addition, there are intermittent focal sharp waves seen over the left hemisphere at T3, sometimes at F7 and sometimes at T5, and independently over the right hemisphere at T4 and sometimes at F8/T4.
Seizures:  None.
Heart rate:  Regular at 84 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to multifocal left hemisphere and right hemisphere sharp waves, as well as triphasic discharges and generalized slow disorganized background.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of multifocal cortical irritability, as well as generalized diffuse cerebral dysfunction, all of which may be seen with a diffuse cortical process suggestive of an encephalitis or rapidly progressive neurologic degenerative disease.  Some of the findings may also be due to a metabolic disturbance.  No clear seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 24-year-old, left handed male, with epilepsy as a child, seizure free for 2 years, but recurrent seizures on October 15, 2012 characterized by right shaking for 1-2 minutes with tongue biting, loss of consciousness, and postictal confusion.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with  channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.

Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements and attenuation of the high amplitude theta, as well as the bursts of FIRDA.  Bursts of higher amplitude delta were noted during photic stimulation and after photic stimulation, but without spike and wave activity.  Photic stimulation elicited a driving response at intermediate and faster flash frequencies.
Heart rate:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Excess theta.
It seems to be frontally predominant rhythmic mixed theta delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No definitive epileptiform features were identified.  This EEG may hide an underlying frontal epileptiform focus.  A follow up EEG with cognitive testing is advised to more clearly determine when the patient is maximally awake.  In addition, more extended sleep may be helpful in capturing epileptiform activity.  The higher amplitude frontal slowing is not as apparent as the patient transitions into sleep.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 50-year-old male with epilepsy since age 12.  Subsequent cocaine dependence.  After a seizure, patient became violent.  Seizures characterized by an aura of strange feeling followed by postictal confusion.  Last seizure 1 day ago. The patient asked the technologist if photic stimulation would produce 1 of his typical seizures.  The technologist told him that, that was a possibility.  The patient subsequently had 1 of typical behaviors during photic stimulation, but after the photic stimulation had stopped.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz alpha rhythm and a scant amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Hyperventilation was performed early in the EEG and produces and increase an amplitude of the background.  Vertex waves and POSTS are observed in stage 1 sleep with brief stage 2 sleep.  The patient was falling asleep during photic stimulation and transitioning in and out of sleep during photic stimulation.
The patient had an event during photic stimulation.  The patient was drowsy prior to photic stimulations, the patient was waking up, although there were brief transitions in and out of sleep.
The patient was awake at the end of the 11 Hz stimuli, when the behavior occurred, he sat up abruptly.  His eyes were dilated, he was moving back and forth and his heart rate increased briefly to 150 BPM.
Although the audio was not working, the patient was able to communicate during the event.
There were no epileptiform features noted during the event.  No postictal features were identified.
Heart rate 78-150 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  The EEG is normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient had an unusual behavior.  The patient was clearly awake for several seconds prior to the event, but he had been drifting in and out of sleep.  The event had no epileptiform features, but a link either to a sleep-related disorder or a psychiatric illness may be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 21-year-old right-handed woman with a syncopal spell with twitching with loss of consciousness lasting 2 minutes.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz alpha rhythm of 60 to 70 microvolts.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in synchronicity of the alpha rhythm with some slow-rolling eye movements.  Hyperventilation produces a small amount of slowing.  Photic stimulation elicits minimal driving.  The patient was falling asleep during photic stimulation.
Heart rate 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. If seizures are an important consideration, a sleep-deprived 1-hour EEG may be considered.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 19-year-old woman status post MVA with multiple fractures and pneumothorax, traumatic brain injury.  Initial CT demonstrated cerebral edema.  Follow up CT demonstrated improvement.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilaudid, propofol drip, fentanyl drip, Benadryl, Ativan, ceftriaxone.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  This was a technically challenging EEG due to the patient's matted hair and encrusted blood.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates a markedly slow pattern with slow delta and some faster frequency activity.  The patient is somewhat interactive despite the background slowing and the technologist reports that with stimulation the patient will move the right hand to command.
There is a small amount of faster frequency activity noted in the frontal regions, as well as slow frontal delta.
Heart rate:  120 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a technically challenging, but markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Marked background slowing.
Shifting slowing with a bit more rhythmic delta noted with stimulation on the left compared to the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  On the whole this EEG supports a severe bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function with shifting asymmetries, but no specific lateralization.  Although the patient appeared to be responsive to the family, the responsive was difficult to identify.  No epileptiform features were identified.  Given the number of sedative hypnotic medications utilized, medications may play a significant role in the pattern described above.

STUDY DATE:  11/30/2012.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Syncope.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 72-year-old female admitted with syncope and a sudden change in mental status after a code with tachycardia and  hypertension.
MEDICATIONS:  Tramadol, Tylenol, lorazepam, aspirin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded while awake and drowsy.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that at times reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontocentral beta seen.  In general, the background has intermittent theta bursts even during wakefulness at 6-7 Hz seen diffusely.  The patient does appear to become drowsy at times.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Excessive theta in wakefulness at 5-7 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts seen intermittently throughout the recording.
Abnormal discharges:
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to excessive theta in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals mild to moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Unresponsiveness status post code.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 50-year-old woman with known thyroid cancer discovered 15 years ago with progressive dysphagia who had emergency surgery remove mass.  She became acutely bradycardic.  She had CPR started and coded for about 12 minutes.  She had a change in mental status after the code.
MEDICATIONS:  Zofran, albuterol, insulin, Ancef, sodium chloride, chlorhexidine, __________, magnesium oxide, amiodarone, Tylenol, Protonix, vitamin K, Zosyn, vancomycin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while unresponsive.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  There was a 60 Hz artifact seen in the F1 and F2 electrodes throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  There was no normal sleep architectural and no activating procedures were performed.  Overall, the background was consistent with a diffuse delta pattern at 2-4 Hz and an amplitude 20-40 microvolts.  __________ there is frontal by frontal slowing and sharp waves seen frequently throughout the recording.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Bifrontal and sometimes central sharp waves seen at CZ, F3 and F4, and at times at FP1 or FP2.
Focal slowing in the bifrontal region.
Generalized slowing as described before.
SEIZURES:  At 1:21 p.m. the EEG recording suddenly stopped and the recording restarts at 1:24 p.m.  At this point there is a clear prefrontal rhythmic discharge consistent of sharp waves maximal mainly at FP1, but at times at FP2 at a frequency of 3-4 Hz going on continuously with no clear clinical correlate.  This pattern is consistent with an electrographic seizure.  The electrographic seizure continues without stopping until about almost 19 minutes later after receiving Ativan at 1:39 p.m.  After that the EEG appears to go back to a diffusely slow background with some prefrontal slowing.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to an electrographic prefrontal maximal seizure with no clear onset seen as well as bifrontal slowing and generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals electrographic seizures which appears to be maximally in the frontal region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the frontal region as well as diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology, but is likely related to the hypoxic injury.  These findings were discussed with the team and the patient will be placed on long-term monitoring.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 68-year-old woman admitted to the hospital several days ago with aphasia and a 1 week history of language difficulties, resolving and right-sided weakness.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, lisinopril, others.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is diffusely slow and poorly organized.  Both hemispheres are somewhat slow and disorganized with a posterior dominant rhythm of 6-7 Hz.  There is disruption of faster frequency activity noted from the left hemisphere.  There are bursts of frontally prominent regular or irregular delta noted.  Rhythmic delta activity is also observed in the occipital regions, right or left with an occipital sharp wave which is almost at the midline.  In addition, there are rare left central sharp waves maximum at C3 in wakefulness, there is an increase in more rhythmic theta frequency activity and the alpha rhonchi is a bit better defined on the right.  Photic stimulation did not significantly activate the record.  Heart rate sometimes irregular, 72 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing and disorganization.
Superimposed focal features with disruption of faster frequency activity on the left compared to the right.
Sharp waves noted including left central as well as others that are occipital in nature.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a bihemispheric process involving gray and white matter.  In addition, focal features, congruent with the stroke history include disruption of faster frequency activity and the sharp waves described above.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 48-year-old woman admitted with an episode of transient dizziness.  Past history of hypertension, asthma and a psychiatric illness.
MEDICATIONS:  Lovenox, lisinopril, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was attempted in the laboratory using standard a 10-20 System of electrode placement, with 1 channel of EKG.  Significant technical difficulties included the hair weaves that the patient has.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Despite the problems with electrode placement and impedance, the background EEG is appropriately organized, with an 11 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation did not significantly activate the record.  The referential montage was not particularly successful.  Features of drowsiness included an increase in background slowing.  In addition, very brief stage I sleep was seen, with vertex waves and then a transition in and out of stage I sleep.  At the very close of the record, the patient was transitioning in and out of stage II sleep.  Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.  Heart rate 84 bpm, occasional PVCs.
IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging but normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  The transitions in and out of stage II sleep may reflect sleep deprivation or an underlying sleep disturbance, which could be correlated with this patient's clinical picture.  To obtain a better quality EEG, a repeat study, when the patient has had her hair weaves removed, is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 75-year-old gentleman with abrupt onset of word finding difficulty a year ago, problematic confusion.  The patient had an episode of loss of consciousness while getting out of the shower 1 week ago.
