There is an increase in beta following by vertex waves, POSTS and spindles.  This seems to be a very sleepy patient with the appearance of stage 2 sleep and then eye movement as if he is either very sleepy or having difficulty sustaining sleep.  Photic stimulation elicited a driving response, although the patient was transitioning in and out of stage 2 sleep with a suggestion of even early slow wave sleep.
Heart rate 54 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within normal limits in wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This individual appears to be quite sleepy which would be the case if this was a sleep-deprived EEG or this was a difficult area for the patient to really get comfortable and stay asleep with.  The bradycardia may be evaluated as indicated.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 33-year-old, right-handed female with new onset seizures since May 2012, during sleep with tongue biting and postictal confusion.  Her last seizure was in September 2012.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient's medications include Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the laboratory using the standard International 10-20 System of electrode placement in addition to T1 and T2 electrodes and 1 channel of EKG monitoring, hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness through drowsiness.
DESCRIPTION OF PROCEDURE:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 10-11 Hz in frequency, 70-75 microvolts in amplitudes seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Drowsiness is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact.  Hyperventilation results in symmetrical slowing of the background activity.  Photic stimulation was performed and multiple flash frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response.  Heart rate is 60 to 70 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through drowsiness.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are clinical concern, a repeat EEG capturing deeper stages of sleep or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Possible seizure.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 74-year-old woman with a right vasoganglia lesion biopsied on December 3, had on Sunday an episode of right upper extremity jerking.  She has a past medical history of diabetes, hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and atrial fibrillation.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Decadron, phenobarbital, oxybutynin, Klonopin, ceftriaxone, Cardizem, metoprolol.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded while minimally responsive.  Activating procedures were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 6 to 7 Hz, which appears to be somewhat reactive to eye opening.  There is no normal frontocentral beta.  Overall, the background is diffusely slow in a theta-delta frequency and appears to be asymmetrically faster over the left hemisphere. The right hemisphere reveals focal slowing.  In addition, there is again generalized slowing maximally bifrontally.
Heart rate 84 and irregular.
Abnormal discharges:
Focal sharp waves seen occasionally at F4 while unresponsive.
Focal slow waves seen over the right hemisphere, maximal at F8/T4 at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 40 microvolts.
Generalized slowing at 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts seen continuously throughout the recording, but at times maximally in the bifrontal region.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to right frontal focal sharp waves, in addition to right hemispheric focal slowing, maximally seen in the anterior temporal region with additional generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from the right frontal region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right hemisphere, maximal in the anterior temporal region, which is likely due to the known mass and lesion.  Lastly, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology.  No seizures were seen.

TYPE OF STUDY:  Routine EEG.
DIAGNOSES:  Memory problems, forgetfulness, and agitation.
HISTORY:  This is a 59-year-old right-handed woman with past medical history significant for dementia and asthma, who presents for worsening of forgetfulness and agitation.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the lab using the standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  These tracing captures wakefulness through short period of drowsiness.  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 9 to 9.5 hertz in frequency, 30-40 microvolts in amplitude, seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Drowsiness is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye-blink artifacts.  There are intermittent periods of bitemporal slowing at F7/T3 and F8/T4 during wakefulness and short period of drowsiness consisting of 3 hertz delta frequency, 50-60 microvolt in amplitude lasting 1-2 seconds.  Hyperventilation resulted in slowing seen in most cerebral hemispheres.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple fresh frequencies and resulting in a driving response.  Heart rate was 70-80 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to bitemporal slowing during wakefulness and short period of drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings are suggestive of bilateral structural abnormalities or bilateral cerebral dysfunction.  Other causes included toxic metabolic or infectious encephalopathy, or degenerative causes.  There were no epileptiform abnormalities or seizures noted during this study.  The abscess of epileptiform abnormalities does not exclude to possibility of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.  If seizure remains a clinical concern, a repeat EEG capturing either stages of sleep or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG monitoring may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 49-year-old female who presents with episodes of anxiety and right sided shaking, lasting 4-5 minutes along with loss of consciousness and postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Topiramate, alprazolam, and temazepam.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm was 9-9.5 Hz in frequency seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is diffuse low amplitude beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Drowsiness is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact.  Hyperventilation results in mild symmetrical slowing of the background.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in symmetric driving response.  Heart rate was 60 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through drowsiness.  No epileptiform abnormalities were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are a clinical concern, a repeat EEG capturing deeper stages of the sleep may be helpful.  The generalized beta activity could be due to medication effect including benzodiazepines, barbiturates, or could be due to anxiety or hypothyroidism.  Clinical correlation is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 19-year-old woman with asthma and 3 seizures in December 2012 characterized by blacking out while driving.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Five minutes hyperventilation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, this is a very useful appearing EEG with an 11 Hz alpha rhythm reaching 80 microvolts with prominent, posterior slow waves of youth.
Hyperventilation was performed early on the record producing bursts of rhythmic, synchronous theta and delta again with a slight posterior predominance.  Following hyperventilation, as the patient became drowsy, hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing was identified.  Other features of sleep include vertex waves and multiple transitions in and out of sleep.
Photic stimulation elicited a driving response with harmonic and supra harmonic driving.  In addition, on occasion during photic stimulation, the patient was becoming drowsy with bursts of paroxysmal slowing, but without definitive spike and slow wave activity.
Heart rate 78 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within normal limits for a young adult of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this EEG.  There are multiple, youthful findings noted in this EEG, but no pathological features were noted.
The previous EEG demonstrated some of these same youthful findings, but raised some concern as to possible underlying spike and wave activity.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Brain tumor and seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 69-year-old man with a history of brain tumor in the right frontal region status post radiation, epilepsy, hypertension and diabetes with increased seizures after surgery, now with increased seizures about twice per month, described as tonic-clonic with no loss of consciousness for 4 to 5 minutes afterwards or a bad in the mouth.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Keppra, metoprolol, metformin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Movement throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz.  The patient is recorded mainly in wakefulness.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation that was performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen continuously over the right hemisphere, maximal in the central parietal and temporal regions at a frequency of 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.  There is also increased beta over that region consistent with a breached rhythm.
SEIZURES:  During the recording there were about 4 seizures which appeared to begin over the right hemisphere at T4/C4 and increasing amplitude and frequency from delta to theta, and seconds later appeared to spread to the left hemisphere in the T5 electrode which appeared to continue to evolve and then suddenly stop.  During the event the patient is tested and at the time is slow to respond, but not clearly unresponsive.  The seizures last about 1 minute and 45 seconds, otherwise there is no other EEG correlate.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to right central temporal and parietal continuous focal slowing and breach in addition to multiple seizures likely arising from that region
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures arising around the right central parietal region.  Multiple of what appeared to be possible electrographic versus complex partial seizures.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right central parietal and temporal region which is consistent with the known tumor and radiation.  These findings were informed to the patient.  He was sent to the emergency room for admission and further treatment of his seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 50-year-old gentleman who suffered a cerebral abscess in the 90's, subsequent development of epilepsy with four seizures per month.  He reports seizures began with a feeling of numbness or burning in his feet followed by loss of awareness with tongue biting, incontinence following generalized shaking.  Last seizure two weeks ago.  Seizures have increased with life's stress.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was awake and conversant throughout.  He has a prominent, frontal craniotomy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This is an unusual and dynamic EEG.  Some sections of the record demonstrate a pretty well organized background with a lower voltage alpha rhythm of 11 Hz and some lower voltage frontocentral theta.  Other sections of the record demonstrated bursts of high amplitude, bifrontal sharp waves or spikes.  These occur with the patient relaxing comfortably but were accentuated by hyperventilation.  The epileptiform activity is usually bilateral but can be maximum in the right or left frontal region.  There can be a polyspike component at FP1, F3 or FP2.  The bursts of slow spike-and-wave activity are associated with background slowing, and bursts of epileptiform activity or bursts of slowing with epileptiform may be on the order of two seconds or longer.  Aside from these bursts, the patient is awake, alert, and conversant.  The bursts are brief enough that it is difficult to determine if they are clinically significant.
Heart rate:  72  BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Burst of slow, frontal spike-and-wave activity.
Associated focal slowing noted with these bursts.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In the context of this patient's significance neurosurgical history, the location of the epileptiform activity is anticipated.  Despite the bursts of slowing, the patient was relatively asymptomatic.  In this individual with frequent seizures, additional EEG recording may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 25-year-old male with a history of childhood brain tumor in the left hemisphere, status post radiation and chemotherapy.  First ever seizure today, followed by right-sided weakness.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.  The patient had already had Ativan.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was quite drowsy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG includes a breach rhythm with considerably higher amplitude activity on the left compared to the right.  As the EEG begins, the patient is asleep with generous beta of 13 Hz in the frontocentral region, but without some of the typical features of stage II sleep.  The activity on the right is lower voltage and slow.  With stimulation, there is some sharply contoured activity appearing at T5 and T1.  Higher amplitude focal delta is noted throughout the left hemisphere and varies from left frontocentral to mid to posterior temporal region.  As the patient becomes a bit sleepier, the activity on the right is lower voltage and slower.  In sleep, despite the breach rhythm, there is more of a left parietal focus.  Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
Heart rate 90 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing from the left hemisphere with variability, but in sleep much more prominent in the left parietal region.
Sharply contoured slowing in the context of a breach rhythm with suggestion of a left parietal sharp wave.
Some sharp wave contoured wave forms in the left frontocentral or frontotemporal region, as well.
In wakefulness, the background is also slow on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a structural or functional abnormality on the left, congruent with a previous tumor and surgical history.  The foci of sharply contoured slowing is more prominent in the left parietal region in sleep, but is a little bit more anteriorly when the patient is stimulated.  The bilateral background slowing may be due to a diffuse brain process or postictal state.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 57-year-old man with history of cirrhosis admitted for abdominal pain.  He has been unresponsive since 11/21/2012.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient's medications include propofol, rifaximin, vancomycin, lactulose.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in ICU using the standard international 10/20 system of electrode placement in addition to two T1-T2 electrodes and 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This tracing captures the patient in a comatose state, sedated state.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the comatose/sedated state, there was seen diffuse attenuation of the background with intermittent EKG artifacts.  There was unknown artifact in bilateral frontoparietal regions likely due to a ventilators.  There was seen very low voltage 1.5 Hz delta frequency activity and occasional 3 Hz delta frequency activity of 5-10 microvolt amplitude.  There was seen no spontaneous variability and reactivity on stimulating the patient.  No seizures or epileptiform activity was seen during this recording.  Heart rate was 80-90 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing the patient in a comatose/sedative state due to diffuse slowing and attenuation of the background.  No seizures or epileptiform activity was seen during this recording.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Diffuse slowing and attenuation of the background are suggestive of severe anoxic encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to severe metabolic or infectious encephalopathy or due to effect of medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunction.  In addition, diffuse attenuation could be seen in bilateral fluid collection in the extra-axial space or the overlying skull.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were captured.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or of intermittent seizures.  If clinically indicated, a continuous bedside EEG monitoring may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is an 18-year-old man with a history of seizures since 16 years of age.  Last seizure was approximately in 01/2012.

IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 24 minute awake only EEG due to frequent brief bursts of generalized frontally predominant spike and wave and polyspike and wave discharges.  In a proper clinical setting this EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of idiopathic generalized epilepsy.  No electrographic seizures are captured.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 28-year-old man who presents with an episode of loss of consciousness with associated fall, shaking and postictal confusion.  The patient states that it might have been his third episode of such nature.
CURRENT MEDICATIONS:  None.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The record was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated moderate amplitude 12 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  Frequent slow and fast alpha variants are present.  There is anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  Throughout the recording there are frequent polymorphic intrusions of diffuse theta and delta.  Drowsiness is present, but stage II sleep is not recorded.  Hyperventilation results in mild diffuse symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.
FINDINGS:
No stage II sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and briefly drowsy 23 minute EEG.  Diffuse intrusions of theta and delta activity likely represent a normal variant.  No epileptiform discharges were captured, however, stage II sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indication for seizures persist, a repeat study with sleep may be of benefit.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a36-year-old woman with a past medical history of epileptic and nonepileptic events.  She now presents with an increase in seizure frequency.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamotrigine, Dilantin, Synthroid.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the  standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated moderate amplitude 10 to 11 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient, with faster frequencies at lower amplitude anteriorly.  During sleep symmetrical vertex waves and sleep spindles are captured.  Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving a multiple flash frequencies.
FINDINGS:
No epileptiform discharges.
Stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep 23 minute EEG.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 48-year-old woman admitted on October 23, with fatigue and a fever found to have a right frontal subdural hematoma and a left MCA infarct.
MEDICATIONS:  None reported.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This is an awake and drowsy EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  Sections of the record include a rhythmic approximately 7 Hz theta frequency background with a 7-8 Hz alpha rhythm, but much of the record include significantly more slower rhythmic mixed theta and delta.  Superimposed upon this is some focal slowing with a bit more arrhythmic alpha on the left compared to the right and disruption of faster frequency activity.  In addition, occasional sharp waves are noted independently at T4, P4 and T1.  Sharp waves are relatively infrequent.  Stimulation of the patient produces an alerting response with an increase in the faster frequency activity.  Rare triphasic waves were observed.  Heart rate 97 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Intermittent, paroxysmal slowing.
Superimposed asymmetry with disruption of faster frequency activity on the left in comparison to the right.
Independent sharp waves seen from either hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function affecting gray and white matter.  In addition, a structural or functional process on the left should be considered.  There are infrequent sharp waves seen from either hemisphere.  These findings may even be correlated with imaging and clinical history.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  New onset seizures with right-sided focal shaking followed by right eye deviation.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient is intubated and comatose.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG is diffusely slow.  From the left hemisphere, there is a periodic sharp complex which is polyphasic in nature.
Although due to technical limitations only a limited review is seen, there is no definitive evolution.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing, which is bihemispheric in nature.
A complex periodic complex in the left hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG demonstrates a markedly abnormal pattern with significant epileptogenic potential.  Additional EEG recording is essential to evaluate for additional clinical or subclinical seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  44 year old male with palpitations and acute loss of consciousness, second syncopal event with confusion and abnormal EKG.
MEDICATIONS:  Lovenox, Percocet, Advair
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10-Hz alpha rhythm.  This patient transitions in and out of stage I and stage II sleep with vertex wave, K-complexes, spindles and posts, and frequent transitions between wakefulness and stage II sleep.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were observed.  The disrupted sleep may be due to underlying sleep deficit, effect of medications, or other causes.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 79-year-old man admitted for acute renal failure, change in mental status, with right-sided weakness and 2 tonic/clonic seizures with eyes rolling backwards and right facial twitching.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  T4 electrode artifact.
MEDICATIONS:  Amlodipine, loratadine, Dilantin, and vancomycin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while unresponsive.  Activating procedures were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely low slow background with normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture and no normal frontocentral beta seen.  No activating procedures were performed.  No sleep architecture was seen.
Heart rate:  114.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz seen continuously throughout the recording with amplitude of 20-30 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to marked diffuse or generalized slowing.  This EEG reveals evidence of marked diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology but may be at least due in part due to medication affect.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 54-year-old woman with epilepsy, admitted to the hospital on the 30th after a tonoclonic seizure with postictal confusion.  The patient remained mute after the seizure.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Ativan, Keppra, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab  using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was initially somnolent, then inattentive.  This was an awake through stage II sleep record.  After the patient drifted off to sleep, it was somewhat difficult to awaken the patient.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The tracing begins with stage II sleep with central spindle activity.  Focal slowing is noted from the left temporal region with left temporal sharp waves.  The sharp waves are mid to anterior temporal with a generous field spread.  They are discrete, at 70 microvolts at the maximum.  In the T1 and T2 montage they are maximum at T1.
The patient is still quite drowsy during photic stimulation.  During photic stimulation, there are trains of left anterior temporal sharp waves as the patient transitions in and out of stage II sleep.
The technologist attempts to awaken the patient for hyperventilation without success.  The patient remains in stage II sleep again with prominent sharp waves from the left temporal region.
Heart rate 96 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Left anterior temporal sharp waves.
Left temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are relatively characteristic of temporal lobe epilepsy.  This patient's postictal state may account for the hypersomnolence as it might be the use of benzodiazepines.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Hypoxic injury.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 48-year-old man found unresponsive with carbon monoxide poisoning on December 1st, with a history of hypertension and alcohol abuse, left foot ischemia, non-ST-elevation myocardial infarction, bacteremia and pneumonia.
MEDICATIONS:  Insulin, aspirin, Lovenox, vitamins, Coreg, thiamine, vancomycin, Lipitor.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  Overall, the patient's background is mainly in the theta frequently at 5-7 Hz and amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.  The patient does appear to be reactive to commands and there is variability in the EEG upon stimulation.  The patient did have photic stimulation which revealed no abnormal discharges.
Heart rate 84.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Diffuse slow waves seen at 5-7 Hz and amplitude of 20-40 microvolts continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to mild-to-moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of mild-to-moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology, but is likely related to the carbon monoxide/hypoxic injury.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 66-year-old female with abdominal pain, shortness of breath, and change in mental status, initially admitted to the medical ICU due to sepsis versus hypercapnia.  The CT abdomen found fluid collection and status post colectomy in 12/2009, had an episode of shaking, bilateral shoulders for 2 minutes, given Ativan and stopped.  She also has a past medical history of COPD, GERD, hypertension, SVT, and essential tremor.
MEDICATIONS:  Fentanyl, Keppra, Flagyl, hydrocortisone, Advair, Protonix, cefepime, vancomycin, Lovenox, insulin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while slightly responsive while sedated.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some movement artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Overall, there is a diffusely slow background in the delta frequency at 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-30 microvolts seen continuously.  At times, there is intermittent triphasic live waveforms which appear to be symmetric and maximally center frontally and at times periodic.
SEIZURES:  None.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-30 microvolts seen continuously.
Triphasic waves.
Heart rate 180, irregular.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to generalized slowing as well as triphasics.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  However, the triphasics suggest at least a possible metabolic component.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  Evaluate for paresthesias and shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Elavil, Ativan, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a well organized pattern with an 11 Hz, 60-70 microvolt alpha rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral theta.  Hyperventilation was performed early in the record producing an increasing amplitude of the background.  Drowsiness is characterized by brief attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Drowsiness is characterized by brief attenuation of the alpha rhythm.
Photic stimulation did not significantly activate the record.
Heart rate:  70 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The generous beta may be related to this patient's medications.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow-up study capturing deeper stages of sleep may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 74-year-old male, status post severe head trauma, patient discharged to a nursing home and then re-admitted on 11/11/2012.  Evaluate for impaired mental status.
MEDICATIONS:  Amantadine, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was drowsy.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates a pattern of low voltage data, intermittently interrupted by rhythmic 1 to 2 Hz delta activity.  In addition, there is some shifting arrhythmic delta activity, a little bit more prominent on the right.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in delta.
Heart rate 114 bmp.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Markedly slow background.
A patient suffering with traumatic brain injury who does demonstrate some alerting but with minimal alerting, a low alpha rhythm.
Bursts of delta.
Mild shifting and slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In this individual with both a neurodegenerative process with dementia, such as Parkinson's disease and severe traumatic brain injury.  This EEG demonstrates a slow background.  There was a section where the patient seemed to be awake with tremor and there was an emergence of an alpha rhythm but the patient did not seem to be very interactive at that time.  Clinical management may be the most important tool to follow his mental status.  No epileptiform features were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 61-year-old male with alcohol abuse, admitted with change in mental status, right arm tremor, and eye deviation to the left; evaluate for seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Metoprolol, aspirin, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was confused.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG includes a fair amount of muscle and movement artifact.  There is a mixed frequency pattern with generous faster frequency activity and some slow activity with a mixture of theta/delta.  There is a great deal of chew artifact noted.  Shifting asymmetries were observed.  Very brief epochs to suggest stage I sleep were noted, followed immediately by spontaneous agitation.
Heart rate 84 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing and disorganization.
Prominent shifting slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Sleep was not sustained.  There is shifting slowing in the sleep morphologies as well as in the overall background.  These findings may be correlated with imaging.  No epileptiform features were identified, but a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy should be considered.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 44-year-old man with history of hypertension and diabetes who presents with witnessed seizures described as generalized tonic-clonic seizures and postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient's medications include antihypertensive medication.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed in the lab using a standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to T1 and T2 electrode and 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This tracing captured wakefulness only.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 8.5-9 Hz in frequency 30-40 microvolts in amplitude seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontal central beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  No epileptiform activities or seizures are identified during this recording.  Heart rate is 70 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness only.  No epileptiform abnormalities were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG and does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are of clinical concern, a repeat EEG capturing deeper stages of sleep or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  Adult male found with intracerebral hemorrhage, previous encephalomalacia.  Intubated and sedated with EVD.
MEDICATIONS:  Propofol, Dilantin, Keppra
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a lower voltage pattern with generous beta.  There is a slight asymmetry with a slight disruption of beta activity in the right central region related to the left.  There is a single subtle right frontal sharp wave.
Heart rate 104.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to
Replacement of normal background with diffuse beta.
Very subtle right-sided slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The use of sedative or hypnotic medications, would produce the beta activity described above.  Given the magnitude of the patient's hemorrhage, the right central slowing is more subtle than one would expect.  In this patient with a history of frontal encephalomalacia, there was only a single right frontal sharp wave, which was of no clear clinical significance.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 55-year-old woman with cerebral aneurysm which was previously coiled. The patient was admitted November 8 for inability to move the right side and then December 3 for hypotension. Now with intermittent episodes of unresponsiveness.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Vimpat
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.   Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the EEG is somewhat slow.  In addition, there is an apparent breach rhythm present, but not prominent on the right with higher amplitude activity on that side.  Intermittent focal slowing is noted on the right with some sharp wave contours, delta in the right central temporal region.  Alerting seems to ameliorate this.  Photic stimulation elicits scant bilateral driving.  Heart rate 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Mild, generalized background slowing.
Somewhat subtle right central temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a structural functional abnormality on the right.  In comparison to a previous study on November 9, the focal slowing and the background slowing are markedly improved.  No definitive sharp waves or spikes were noted and no seizures were recorded.

REASON FOR STUDY:  A 51-year-old man with depression presents after possible seizure.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 51-year-old man with history of depression presents after an episode of seizure, found on the floor.
MEDICATIONS:  Hydralazine, lorazepam, and Lovenox.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using a standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while awake and sleep, stage I and stage II.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  There was a continuously seen overriding 60 Hz artifact which is eliminated partly with the notch filter, however, presents clear identification of all the wave forms in the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz when awake and has some frontal central beta.  No activating procedures were performed.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and stage I and stage II sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None clearly seen.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Limited normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This limited EEG in wakefulness and sleep is normal, however, note that the overriding artifact required a notch filter to be used for review of the EEG and all the wave forms cannot be clearly identified as factual. Repeated EEG addressing this issue may be helpful if the clinical diagnosis or epilepsy and seizures is a concern.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Episode of loss of consciousness.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  Patient is a 50-year-old male with history of hepatitis C, asthma, anxiety disorder and prior motor vehicle accident.  The patient had recent methamphetamine withdrawal and subsequently has an abrupt loss of consciousness with shaking of hands and legs for 5 minutes.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Vertex waves and spindles are noted in stage 2 sleep.  There is some head rocking in the transition from wakefulness to sleep.
Photic stimulation elicited a scant driving response.
Heart rate 60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits for age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 53-year-old woman with a history of seizures; followup for recurrent seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 to 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Photic stimulation produces no abnormal discharges.
Abnormal discharges:
Very frequent, at times rhythmic sharp waves seen over F7/T3 and at times at T3 during wakefulness and sleep, as well independent also frequent sharp waves over F8/T4, also seen during wakefulness and sleep; however, the majority of the sharp waves are seen mainly in sleep and appear to attenuate with eye opening and wakefulness.
Focal slow waves over the left hemisphere at F7/T3 at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts and independently at F8/T4, seen occasionally at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts.
Seizures:  None.
Heart rate 78, regular.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to very frequent left anterior temporal and independent right anterior temporal sharp waves in wakefulness and sleep, as well as focal slowing in those regions.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from either anterior temporal region.  In addition, there is evidence of independent focal cerebral dysfunction in the bilateral anterior temporal regions, both of which are nonspecific in regard to etiology.  No seizures were seen.  Please note that this EEG is not that dissimilar to the reported EEG done on August 1, 2011.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 72-year-old male with a history of head trauma, adult-onset epilepsy, and likely nonepileptic seizures as well.  The patient typically has seizures after encounters with the health care system and has many adverse reactions to antiepileptic drugs.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, oxycodone, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.  This was a very drowsy patient.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there was a 10.5-Hz alpha rhythm.  The patient quickly transitioned to a drowsy pattern with prominent slowing of the alpha rhythm. Vertex waves were noted in stage 1 sleep.  As the patient drifted off to sleep, there was an involuntary jerk of the right leg. This was not associated with epileptiform features.  Cognitive testing was performed at the end to make sure that the patient was maximally awake and there was an awake pattern and then the patient quickly started to become a little drowsy with slowing of the alpha rhythm.
Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.  Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within normal limits for an adult of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform activity was noted.  Sleep myoclonus was noted on one occasion which does not carry an EEG correlate.  This patient appears to be excessively drowsy which could be related to sleep deprivation or the use of opiate medications as described above.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 77-year-old male with systolic heart failure, tachycardia.  recent C3-C4 posterior cervical laminectomy.  Change in mental status with episodes of tongue movement and eye deviation.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  24 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 64-year-old woman with a chief complaint of slurred speech and stuttering for 1 day.
MEDICATIONS:  Hydrochlorothiazide, carvedilol, aspirin and Celexa.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single electrocardiogram lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.

There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During drowsiness the posterior dominant rhythm attenuates and vertex waves are observed.  Hyperventilation results in mild symmetrical background slowing. CLINICAL HISTORY:  An elderly man who had a seizure following dental work with lidocaine on the 5th, transferred to the hospital on a propofol drip.  After extubation, the patient was noted to have intermittent tremulousness.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Ativan
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient had 2 episodes of tremulousness, both of which seemed to occur when he was stimulated from sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Random wakefulness and sleep.  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized.  In sleep, there are normal features of stage I and stage II sleep.  No epileptiform features were observed.
Description of record:  The patient seems to be falling out of bed at 12:02.  He is awake, leans backward.  He has titubation of the head and body.  When he is trying to get up, there is some rhythmic 5 Hz artifact, but when he stops moving, there is a normal awake pattern.
He has some vocalizations but does not seem to be able to call the nurse.
The nurse enters and provides 2 mg of Ativan at 12:14.  The patient drifts off to sleep.  The pattern after the Ativan is relatively low voltage and slow.  Features of sleep are noted, but spontaneous arousals are also noted by 3:00 a.m.
The patient is resting comfortably.  With tactile stimulation, the patient alerts and has titubation of the head.  No epileptiform activity is accompanied by this behavior.
Heart rate 115 bpm with frequent PVCs.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal 24-hour video EEG with 2 events without epileptiform signature.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Titubation of the head or tremulousness was not associated with an epileptiform activity.  No epileptiform features were identified.  The behaviors described above had characteristics to suggest that they were not seizures including preserved interaction and purposeful movement.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 36-year-old woman with a history of complex partial seizures with last seizure reported in 2011.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.   Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well formed and modulated 10-11 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  Excessive diffuse beta is observed.
During sleep symmetrical vertex waves are captured.
Hyperventilation produces a mild diffuse background slowing.
Step photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving.
FINDINGS:
No epileptiform discharges.
No stage 2 sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy 22 minute EEG.  No epileptiform discharges were captured, however, the patient's sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indication for seizures persist, a repeat study with the patient asleep may be of benefit.  Excess beta could be secondary to medication effects, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 60-year-old woman who presents with a history of dizzy spells, the most recent about 10 days ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Meclizine p.r.n., Pravachol, and amlodipine.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well formed and modulated low to moderate amplitude 10 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During drowsiness, POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep) and vertex waves are captured.  Hyperventilation produces several bursts of diffuse polymorphic delta activity as well as mild symmetrical background slowing.  Photic stimulation results in occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.  A single EKG lead reveals a regular heart rate.
FINDINGS:
No epileptiform discharges.
No stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy 22-minute EEG.  No epileptiform discharges were captured; however, stage II sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indication for seizures persists, a repeat study with sleep may be of benefit.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  44 year old right handed female with significant cardiac disease, admitted with crushing substantial chest pain and facial twitching.  Radiculopathy.  Multiple skin tags.
MEDICATIONS:  Hydralazine, Protonix, Acetaminophen
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a pattern with generous beta and an 11 Hz alpha rhythm.  The patient becomes drowsy quite rapidly with an increase in central theta.  Spindles and posts are noted as the patient transitions in and out of sleep. HR:    84 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are observed.  The pattern with the rapid transitions between wakefulness and sleep is an anticipated finding in a patient with significant obstructive sleep apnea.

a follow-up study as the patient emerges from the use of propofol and other sedative hypnotic doses of medications for acute repetitive seizures is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 87 year old man with history of DVT, PE, hypertension, esophageal ulcer, angioplasty, that was found down confused by his son, now with a right frontal mass.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Haldol, Lorazepam, Hydralazine, Dexamethasone, Insulin.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Confusion and change in mental status.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness, but was lethargic.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some movement artifact during the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to diffusely slow recording with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 7 Hz and is reactive to eye opening.  There is lack of normal frontal central beta seen.  The patient is only recorded in wakefulness and no activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen at C4/F4 at times in rhythmic bursts of 2 Hz consistent with periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLED'S) almost continuously throughout the recording.
Focal slow waves seen at C4/F4 at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-100 mV also seen continuously throughout the recording.
Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 mV seen continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  During the recording at one point the rhythmic PLED'S appeared to increase in frequency and evolve to infrequency and decreasing amplitude for about 1 minute and 20 seconds.  In the video there does not appear to be a clinical correlate which is consistent with an electrographic seizure.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right frontal central PLED'S.
One electrographic seizure.
Generalized slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals one single electrographic seizure coming from the right fronto-central region. In addition, there is evidence of acute structural dysfunction and irritability in the right frontal central region which is consistent with the known frontal mass.  There was also evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology and may be due, at least in part, to medication effect.

TYPE OF STUDY:  Routine EEG during wakefulness.
DIAGNOSIS:  Rule out seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 19-year-old woman with a family history of epilepsy who presents with episodes described as foot shaking, stomach jumping, feeling of dizziness, and hot.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the lab  using the standard International 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to one channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness only.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 9 to 10 Hz in frequency, 30 to 40 microvolt in amplitude seen the occipital region which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity which is distributed symmetrically.  Hyperventilation results in symmetric slowing of the background.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple/frequencies and resulted in a symmetric driving response.  Heart rate is 60 to 70 beats per minute and regular.
CLINICAL EVENTS:  A 10:00:43 the patient reported that she has an attack described as her stomach is jumping with her arm on top of it.  She added that this is part of her attack.  At 10:06:01 she reported that she is feeling hot.  At 10:11:54 she stated that she is seeing blinking red stuff that hurts.  EEG showed a normal awake pattern with a posterior dominant rhythm of 9 to 10 Hz.  Eye blink artifact, lateral eye movement artifacts and muscle artifact with no epileptiform activity during this event.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness only.  No epileptiform abnormalities were identified in this record.  The episodes were characterized by clinical events of jumping stomach, feeling hot, and seeing blinking red stuff without any significant EEG correlation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This study does not support the diagnosis of epilepsy.  The episodes are diagnostic for psychogenic nonepileptiform events.  Although this study does not exclude the possibility of epilepsy and intermittent seizures, if seizures are a clinical concern a prolonged ambulatory EEG may be helpful to capture other types of events.

Otherwise, some normal sleep architecture sleep is stage II and I is seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 30-year-old with headaches and bilateral eye twitching lasting 1 minute.
MEDICATIONS:  None.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 65-year-old woman with diabetes and possible left MCA stroke, admitted in DKA, the patient began to arouse and was re-sedated.

Stimulation of the patient clearly produces an arousal.
The arousal includes an increase in theta.
There is a subtle asymmetry with a bit more slow delta in the right posterior quadrant.
Heart rate 120 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of a normal background with primarily a beta frequency pattern.
A low voltage slow pattern.
A subtle asymmetry with a bit more delta in the right posterior quadrant.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The findings described above are most compatible with a pharmacologic coma, the asymmetry described above should be correlated with repeat imaging.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  21 year old left handed male with blackout spells, memory loss, 2-year history of seizures.  Last seizure 3 weeks ago.  Father described staring spells and then blackout spells.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  59 year old right handed female employee who fell, hit her right ear, no loss of consciousness.  She slid from her chair.  She experienced a tonic clonic seizure with loss of consciousness during physical examination.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  62 year old female, status post cardiac arrest on January 7th.  The patient had a tonic-clonic seizure in the CT scan and received 12 mg of Ativan.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Fentanyl, Clindamycin, Demerol
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is intubated and poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly slow.  Relatively low voltage.  It includes slow featureless delta and some more scant rhythmic theta with a few bursts of more paroxysmal rhythmic low voltage theta.  In addition, there is a periodic transient noted in the right posterior quadrant.  Sometimes this appears as a pled, other times as slow delta.  It starts at P4 and ends at O2.  It is sometimes spikier at O2 than it is at P2, but occurs first at P4.  As the recording continues, this abnormality is less prominent and appears as an infrequent, periodic delta burst. Stimulation of the patient clearly produces a reactivity with an increase in faster frequency activity.
HR:    104 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Marked background slowing.
A slow, periodic complex in the right occipital or parietal region which improves over time.
Right posterior focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG demonstrates both positive and negative prognostic features for an individual 3 days post cardiac arrest.  In addition, it is not known when the patient had the seizure.  The overall pattern is one of some improvement in terms of the epileptiform activity over time suggesting that the seizure may have occurred today.  This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function as well as a focal disturbance in the right occipital region, but the presence of reactivity and variability are positive prognostic features after cardiac arrest.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 34 year old left handed male with 2 tonic clonic seizures. Past history of childhood epilepsy which he outgrew at age 15. Now with diverticulitis, awaiting colostomy.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a relatively fast alpha rhythm with alpha squeak noted with alpha rhythm transitioning to 13 Hz. In the transition in and out of sleep, there is rhythmic theta which is more prominent in the left temporal region. It has a 4 Hz component more than a 5 Hz component and then on some occasions, has a mixture of delta noted. Hyperventilation accentuates left temporal mixed beta delta with a T1 sharp wave noted infrequently during hyperventilation. This is also a finding that re-emerges in drowsiness. Photic stimulation is performed as the patient is drifting off to sleep. There is a photic driving response identified bilaterally.
HR:    84 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
TIRDA-intermittent rhythmic mixed theta delta.
Left mid to anterior temporal sharp waves elicited by hyperventilation.
Sharply contoured delta also noted in hyperventilation.
Some extension of bilateral temporal rhythmic mixed theta delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are relatively characteristic of a temporal lobe epilepsy. Correlation with imaging and clinical history is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  25 year old right handed male with a history of febrile convulsions.  The patient had a concussion and developed more seizures, and required a vagal nerve stimulator.  In April he had several tonoclonic seizures with loss of consciousness and aura.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel  EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness the background EEG includes a 9 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  The patient transitions in and out of sleep with prominent, hypnagogic hypersynchrony.  During photic stimulation, however, 6 Hz spike and wave activity is noted.  This is noted again during photic stimulation with a 5.5 Hz very brief spike and wave complex during various different photic stimulation parameters. Hyperventilation seems to accentuate the frontally predominant relatively symmetric spike and wave activity. On at least 1 occasion during the EEG, neuro artifact is noted, but no definitive vagal nerve stimulator artifact was observed.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Frontally predominant 5.5 Hz spike and wave activity accentuated by hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Hypnagogic hypersynchrony is a normal phenomenon, but may resemble a forme-fruste of the generalized spike and wave activity.  This patient clearly had generalized spike and wave activity.  This is more supportive of a generalized mechanism for epilepsy.  In this particular EEG, there were no asymmetries and there is otherwise a normal background.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 71-year-old woman with senile dementia and possible epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:  Lasix, Seroquel, Ativan, Percocet.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was unable to participate in hyperventilation. Photic stimulation was completed.  This was an awake and drowsy record in a somewhat anxious patient.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Some sections of the record are reasonably well organized with a 6.5 Hz alpha rhythm.  This is excess beta and excess theta.  There is a small degree of disorganization noted in the background.  Photic stimulation does elicit driving with harmonic, supraharmonic and subharmonic driving.
Heart rate 120 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Prominent slowing of the background.
Excess beta.
Excess theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This slow EEG pattern is supportive of an underlying encephalopathy such as dementia.  It is not specific in terms of any particular type of dementia, but Alzheimer's type dementia and B12 deficiency can both produce this pattern, as can multi infarct dementia.  This patient's medications may play a role in the background slowing.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 40 year old right handed man, with a history of seizures with Xanax withdrawal, anxiety, and hypertension, presents for episodes of strange things in mouth with quick recall of events.  He is here for classification of epileptic versus non-epileptic seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term EEG was performed for 24 hours using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  No activating procedures were performed.  Continues spike wave detection and seizure detection software was used to review the event, along with the patient's alarms, nurses notes, and clinical notes were used to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is an excessive amount of frontal central beta.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness, stage 1, stage 2, and deep stages of sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
EVENT:  During the recording the patient had 5 events where he would suddenly start shaking his head from side to side.  Sometimes towards the left and sometimes toward the right irregularly while becoming unresponsive and remaining so for minutes at time, sometimes for more than 5-10 minutes, and intermittently starting and stopping the behavior.  These  episodes, the first one which occurred at 3:28 p.m., the second one occurred at 9:23 p.m., the third one occurred around 2:40 a.m., and another one at 7:51 a.m., and the last one at 8:48 am had no EEG correlate other than a muscle artifact and afterwards there was normal posterior dominant rhythm seen, all consistent with nonepileptic events.
SEIZURES:  None
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  The episodes captured above with head shaking had no EEG correlate.  As such, they are consistent with psychogenic nonepileptic events. Please note that this patient had previous records which showed left temporal sharp waves.  This was not seen during this admission.

Hyperventilation is performed early in the record producing bursts of frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity, some of which are isolated, some of which are associated with frontal delta.  These are present bilaterally, but with a somewhat more generous field of spread posteriorly on the left.  Hyperventilation produces the bursts of spike and wave activity, but which seemed to be associated with a little jerking of the leg, but which were all less than 1 second in duration and were not associated with impairment of awareness.  As he drifts off to sleep, there is an increase in beta and some faster spike and wave complexes occurring as couplets.  Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.  Photic driving is noted at low frequency stimuli and immediately after photic is completed, spike and wave activity is observed.  There is some head rocking or single-channel electrode at P3 at the end of the EEG.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Frontally predominant 3-5.5 Hz spike and wave activity noted in relaxed wakefulness and accentuated by hyperventilation, but no photic stimulation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is most compatible with inherited or familial mechanism for seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 53-year-old woman with a 17 year history of epilepsy, 3-4 tonic clonic seizures per year, last in January 2013, and hypertension.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Tegretol, and phenobarbital.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is slow and disorganized with an alpha rhythm of about 6-7 Hz in a pattern more of diffuse theta.  This background is intermittently disrupted by bursts of higher amplitude slowing, which are bilateral, but are more prominent on the left compared to the right.  In a disorganized pattern there is an underlying sharp wave which may be in the left mid to anterior temporal region.  In addition, as the patient transitions into stage 1 sleep with vertex waves, some of these waves forms are also noted.  In stage 1 sleep there appears to be a left posterior temporal sharp wave noted.
In the transition between wakefulness and sleep, there is intermittent disruption of the alpha rhythm on either side.
Hyperventilation produced an increase in amplitude of the background with hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing.  In addition, it does seem to elicit some asynchronous slowing and there is a question of a frontal spike and slow wave complex, left greater than right, noted in hyperventilation.
Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
Heart rate:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Disorganization.
Bursts of paroxysmal higher amplitude slowing, which seemed to be maximum on the left and appear to have a poorly defined underlying left mid anterior temporal sharp wave.
Rare right posterior temporal sharp waves noted in sleep.
Rare left and frontal spike and slow wave complexes in hyperventilation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a bihemispheric process, but one which may involve the left hemisphere more significantly than the right.  The epileptiform activity has a preponderance in the left hemisphere.  No seizures were recorded.  If additional information is needed, an inpatient EEG monitoring session may be necessary.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 48-year-old male with hypertension, renal failure, diabetes.  Past history of MVA while intoxicated, admitted in early March with right subdural hematoma requiring right craniectomy.  The patient experienced 1 seizure since discharge from the hospital.  This is a repeat EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, isosorbide, Norvasc, gabapentin, lisinopril, many others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed, but hyperventilation was deferred.  A right craniotomy defect was noted.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In relaxed wakefulness, the background EEG is low-to-medium amplitude with a 6 Hz alpha rhythm which is a bit more prominent on the right than the left.  Bursts of shifting slowing were noted with sharply contoured delta with a broad field of spread in the right temporal region, but also right central parietal region.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing.  As the patient drifts off to sleep, snore artifact was noted and snoring functioned as an arousal for this individual.  Following snoring, the patient was waking up with an actually a faster alpha rhythm of 7.5 Hz.
Photic stimulation did not significantly active the record.
Heart rate 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing with slowing of the alpha rhythm.
Shifting slowing.
Focal slowing in the right hemisphere which may be maximum at T4, the right parietal region or right temporal region.
Breach rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The background slowing is a nonspecific findings which can be seen in diffuse disturbance of cerebral function which may include significant head trauma, renal failure or other metabolic issues. This patient appears to be excessively sleepy and in fact, snoring produced an alerting response for this individual. Evaluation of this patient's neuro anatomy as well as other causes for hypersomnolence with important, given the prominent snore arousals. In comparison to the March 20, 2013, EEG, the focal slowing from the right has improved.

Abnormal discharges:  Focal slow waves seen continuously over the right hemisphere, maximal at F7/T3.  There is associated loss of faster frequencies over this region.  There is also some attenuation.  This is seen continuously at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.
Seizures:  None.
Heart rate:  78.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left hemispheric slowing, maximal in the anterior temporal region with associated loss of faster frequencies.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural cerebral dysfunction in the left hemisphere, maximal in the anterior temporal region, which may be consistent with a structural lesion in that region.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 25-year-old male with a history of epilepsy since childhood.  The most recent seizure was 1 month ago characterized by eyes rolling backwards, breathing heavily, shaking and loss of consciousness lasting for about 1 to 2 minutes.

The amplitude on the left was slightly higher than the right.  The background was occasionally disrupted because of chewing and muscle artifact.
Sleep was not achieved during the recording.
Photic stimulation elicited driving at intermediate/frequencies.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There were no focal or generalized epileptiform features noted.  The asymmetry in alpha rhythm is not clinically significant.  We do not have previous EEGs for comparison.  A repeat EEG capturing sleep may be performed to increase the probability of finding epileptogenic activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 21 -year-old woman with seizures at age 12, not treated.  Recurrent seizures in sleep with an event with foaming at the mouth and unresponsiveness. A total of 3 nocturnal seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
This is an awake and asleep record in a very drowsy patient.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the patient is in stage 2 sleep with vertex waves and spindles.  With stimulation as the patient awakens from sleep, brief, frontal polyspike complexes were observed.  This was followed by a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm and then new activity of 10 Hz although testing was not performed to confirm the presence of new.
Hyperventilation was performed after this which did not produce an alerting response.  Following hyperventilation, the patient drifted back into stage 2 sleep with vertex wave, K-complexes, spindles and posts.
Photic stimulation was remarkable for photoelectric artifact.
Heart rate:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a subtly abnormal EEG due to rare, frontally predominant polyspike activity which was elicited when the patient was awakened from stage 2 sleep.  This activity is approximately 6.5 Hz.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Although the epileptiform activity described above is subtle and is seen in a record with frontal muscle artifact, there is a clear frontal 6.5 Hz spike and wave or polyspike and wave discharge noted in the arousal from sleep.  This seems to be frontally predominant and bilaterally symmetric and more compatible with a generalized mechanism for epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 64-year-old man who presented with right-sided seizures; Past medical history include: Hypertension, cirrhosis and CVA.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Keppra, and the patient received 8 mg of Ativan a few hours before the recording.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement and one channel EKG.  The long-term record was reviewed for abnormalities and clinical events.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Interictal EEG:  The recording from 04/15/2013 to 04/16/2013 was characterized by diffuse slowing.  There was also continuous polymorphic slowing at T3 in the 4-5 Hz range intermixed with 2-3 Hz frequency, which was frequently sharply contoured.  Occasional sharp waves were noted at T3.
From 10 p.m. onwards, the amount of sharp waves had significantly decreased. Towards the end of the recording, no sharp waves were seen.
Ictal Events:  There was one push button at 8:51 p.m., during which time clinically the patient was moving around.
Ictal EEG:  There was no EEG correlate to the push button event at 8:51 p.m.
Some sleep element characterized by sleep spindles were noted, but there was no definite sleep architecture recorded.
IMPRESSION:  This long-term EEG recording is abnormal due to:
Diffuse bilateral slowing.
Focal left T3 continuous polymorphic slowing in the theta and delta range sharply contoured.
Sharp waves at T3 without evolution.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:
The generalized slowing is suggestive of a diffuse process, such as toxic metabolic process versus medication induced versus a postictal state.
Left focal slowing, which is continuous and most pronounced in the left frontocentral and mid temporal regions is suggestive of an underlying structural abnormality, which is consistent with a known stroke in that region.
The left temporal sharps are consistent with epileptogenicity at T3 that places this patient at high risk of localization-related epilepsy.  Clinical correlation is recommended.
