CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 74-year-old right-handed woman status post cardiac arrest on 03/17/2013.  No CPR at home but intubated by EMS.  Critically ill patient.  Additional history not available but plan is for hypothermic protocol.
MEDICATIONS:  Fentanyl, Demerol, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU, using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient had not been paralyzed.  She had not achieved the hypothermic goal or hyperthermia had not been started at the time of the record at 16:05.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Background EEG demonstrates a burst suppression pattern with approximately 2 bursts every 20 seconds.  The bursts are 1 to 3 seconds in duration, and are associated with a little bit of jerking and oral facial movements.  In addition, in the period of time when the EEG is suppressed, following the bursts there is a very slow oral movement and then eye flicker, a bit of jerking, and oral bursts, and then the mouth opening and closing one more time while the EEG is suppressed.  Tactile stimulation does not activate the record.
The bursts of activity are high amplitude, almost with a 4Hz spike and wave-like burst and then a suppressed background.
Heart rate difficult to discern at times due to the background artifact, but 96 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background with a burst suppression pattern.
Postanoxic myoclonus with the bursts with oral facial movements.
Absence of reactivity or significant variability.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These are worrisome findings, more than 6 hours status post anoxic insult.  Due to this patient's cardiac condition, hypothermia protocol was initiated and additional EEG will follow.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 25-year-old man with a history of mental retardation, cerebral palsy, spastic quadriplegia, ventilator-dependent respiratory failure, seizure disorder, hypertension, dilated cardiomyopathy, hydrocephalus, and a history of encephalitis, now with recurrent seizures, rule out status.
MEDICATIONS:  Narcotics, zonisamide, primidone, benzodiazepines.  Will add the rest later.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with an anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while lethargic.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no posterior dominant rhythm or frontal central beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.  Overall the background is of low amplitude consistent with delta slowing at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of less than 20 microvolts seen continuously.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen frequently at C44/F4 seen almost continuously throughout the recording.
Focal slow waves seen continuously at C44/F4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-70 microvolts with additional asymmetric increased amplitude and faster frequencies consistent with a breach.
SEIZURES:  Throughout the recording, there were about 6 seizures which appeared to have an electrographic onset, sometimes at O2 and at times at C4 beginning with high-frequency beta discharge that could again start on the occipital region or the central region and increase in frequency and then in amplitude, later to slow down in frequency but increase in amplitude and would spread either from the occipital region towards the central region at C4 or from the central region to the occipital region and continue to evolve.  They would last for about 1 minute to 2 minutes.  Clinically, the patient appears to open his eyes and roll his eyes towards the right and may have some twitching of his arm and mouth movements.  The tech did question him once and he remained unresponsive.
HEART RATE:  120s between seizures and 134 while having a seizure.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to recurrent seizures as well as right central focal slowing and sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of status epilepticus with multiple seizures arising either from the right occipital or central region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral, structural cerebral dysfunction and irritability over the right central and frontal region.  These findings were discussed with the primary team as soon as the EEG was read.  Long-term EEG will be performed.

There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Drowsiness is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact. CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 39-year-old right-handed gentleman who presents with history of generalized tonic-clonic seizures.  Past medical history is significant for posttraumatic epilepsy and HIV infection.
MEDICATIONS:  Versed at and Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the bedside using standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulations are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, there is a slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm consisting of 7-7.5 Hz frequency activity.  There is excess 5-6 Hz theta activity during short periods of wakefulness.  There is low amplitude, generalized beta activity throughout the recording.  There are almost continuous bifrontal sharply contoured delta activity with a frequency of 2-3.5 Hz.  At times associated with occasional sharp and slow wave activity with no evolution.  There is also almost continuous delta activity noted in right temporal region.  Stage 1 sleep was seen as evidenced by vertex waves and posts.  Stage 2 sleep was seen as evidenced by sleep spindles and K complexes.  The heart rate was 80 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to:
Diffuse slowing of the background and posterior dominant rhythm.
Bifrontal slowing almost continuously with sharply contoured configurations.
Occasional bifrontal sharp and slow waves activities with no evolution.
Right temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Diffuse slowing and slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm are suggestive of metabolic toxic, anoxic, or infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to the effect of medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunction.  Continuous slowing of bifrontal region is consistent with structural lesions in these regions.  The presence of sharp and slow waves is suggestive of underlying epileptogenicity.  Continuous slowing of temporal region is also consistent with a structural lesions in this area.  Generalized beta activity could be due to the effect of sedating medications including benzodiazepine or barbiturate or it can be seen in anxiety or hyperthyroidism.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No seizures were captured during this recording.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 56-year-old right-handed female with a complaint of a syncopal event on March 25, 2013.  Apparently she fainted and was on the floor for 15 seconds and then was observed to shake.  Of note, during the recording here in the laboratory, there was a brief episode of right hemibody tingling.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The recording start time was 11:29 a.m.  The recording end time was 12 noon.  The recording length was 25 minutes.
As the record opens there is a well formed and symmetric 9-10 Hz  posterior dominant rhythm that is reactive to eye opening.  There is a small amount of frontal central beta activity that is symmetrically distributed.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm.  At approximately 11:45 a.m., approximately 15 minutes into the recording epic, the patient complained of right hemibody tingling and numbness.  She was examined by the physician in the laboratory at the time, and there were no obvious clinical sequela.  During this time, there was no change in the background cerebral activity of the EEG.
Hyperventilation was performed for 3 minutes with good effort and failed to activate the tracing.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and induced a very reactive and responsive photic driving response at intermediate flash frequency ranges.  The patient's heart rate ranged from 70-90 beats during the record epic.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG capturing wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does no rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  The brief clinical event of right hemibody numbness and tingling were not associated with changes in the background cerebral activity.  Thus, this event is likely a nonepileptic event.

ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen frequently at F7/T3 and independently at T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.  At times, they became monomorphic and rhythmic for about 3 seconds consistent with temporal intermittent rhythmic delta activity (TIRDA).
Focal slow waves seen rarely at F8/T4 independently at T4 at a frequency of 2-4 and an amplitude of 20-50 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  None.
Heart rate 84.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left anterior temporal and midtemporal focal slowing with temporal intermittent rhythmic delta activity (TIRDA) in addition to right anterior temporal and midtemporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior and midtemporal region, which in addition to the TIRDA may have a high correlation with seizures arising from that region.  There is also evidence of focal cerebral in the right midtemporal region, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 75-year-old woman admitted with acute and chronic subdural hematoma status post surgery 04/04/13 with left frontal skull defect.  History of dementia, psychosis, autism, depression, hypothyroidism.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, Klonopin, Gabapentin, Seroquel, and many others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed at bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient is in a hard collar and isolation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates an asymmetry.  The activity from the right hemisphere includes a mixture of data with smaller amounts of delta in this awake patient.  There is abundant 6 Hz activity and a glimpse of an 8 Hz alpha rhythm. The activity is relatively attenuated on the left.  As the patient becomes drowsy, the right hemisphere transitions a bit more towards the delta pattern.  There is some sharp wave contoured theta noted in the right hemisphere, particularly at T2 and there was also some arrhythmic delta activity in the right posterior quadrant as the patient becomes drowsy.
Heart rate 96 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal electroencephalogram due to:
Intra-hemispheric asymmetry with relative attenuation of the activity on the left compared to the right.
Background slowing noted bilaterally, right greater than left.
There are some subtle sharp waves noted on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a structural or functional abnormality on the left and the attenuated pattern is relatively characteristic of a subdural hematoma.  The sharp waves noted are relatively subtle.  These findings should be correlated with imaging.  Overall, this electroencephalogram supports a bihemispheric process, impacting the left hemisphere more so than the right but a subdural hematoma can attenuate the EEG.

TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that, at best, reaches 7 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is some minimal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.
Abnormal discharges:
Focal slow waves seen over the right hemisphere, maximal at F8/T4 at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts.
There is also intermittent left frontal at F3 focal slowing and at times seen in rhythmic discharges over the frontal hemisphere where it becomes sharply contoured.
Generalized slow waves at 5 to 7 Hz seen throughout the recording in wakefulness.
Heart rate:  72.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to continuous right hemispheric focal slowing maximal in the anterior temporal region, in addition to independent left frontal focal slowing and generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction over the right hemisphere, maximal in the right anterior temporal region, which is consistent with the known brain lesion, in addition to some left frontal cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology.  There is also evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This was predominantly drowsiness and stage 1 sleep record with brief periods of wakefulness.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
MEDICATIONS:  Zonisamide, albuterol, Zyrtec.
TECHNICAL PROBLEMS:  The C3 CZ leads appear to have been closely placed because of which there is flattening of EEG in that channel.
HISTORY:  A 27-year-old lady who is mentally challenged, born out of complicated pregnancy, i.e. cesarean section and was born blue.  She was diagnosed with seizure disorder 1 year ago.  Per mother the patient has seizures every day with just eye twitching.  Also has left-sided twitching.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Periods of wakefulness were very brief as this was predominantly a sleep record.  In the brief period that the was awake there is diffuse slowing with a posterior dominant rhythm in the theta range with maximum frequency of 7 Hertz which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.
Sleep was characterized by diffuse slowing and some waves resembling vertex waves, but no definite vertex morphology was seen.  There were abnormal discharges seen during sleep which will be further described below under the section abnormal discharges.
Hypoventilation did not change the record significantly.
Photic stimulation did not elicit any abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized symmetric frontally predominant spike and wave activity of 2.5 Hertz frequency and 130 to 150 microvolt amplitude were noted mainly during drowsiness and sleep.
There was generalized diffuse slowing in the theta range.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Frontally predominant generalized symmetric 2.5 Hertz spike and wave discharges in sleep.
Symmetric diffuse slowing in the theta range.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with that of a diagnosis of symptomatic generalized epilepsy with a pattern consistent with Lennox-Gastaut syndrome.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Recurring jerks.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
MEDICATIONS:  Neurontin, clonazepam, Flagyl, Lexapro, doxepin, omeprazole,  aspirin, hydrochlorothiazide, metformin, tramadol, albuterol, Singulair, Zofran, triamcinolone, Cardizem, atenolol.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
HISTORY:  A 62-year-old woman with past medical history of anxiety that has been having constant jerking episodes when falling asleep of her extremities, abdomen and face that lately have worsened in frequency and have become intolerable and do not permit her to go to sleep.  She is here for classification of these episodes, rule out seizures/myoclonus versus nonepileptic spells.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.
The patient is recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Overall, the background appears to be normal.  However, as the patient becomes drowsy, intermittent muscle artifact jerks can be seen throughout the recording, at times the EMG artifact could be noted more over the left temporalis muscle than the right.  There appears to be no preceding cortical discharge prior to this muscle artifact.  The video does not reveal clear facial jerks although the technician reports that she noticed some facial jerking irregularly. At one point, the patient does have some abdominal flexion which occurs congruously or at the same time as the muscle artifact occurred. Again, none of these artifacts have a preceding cortical discharge that could be clearly seen.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  66.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and drowsy EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy EEG.  No seizures were seen.  Please note that the jerking episodes described above had no clear cortical or electrographic discharge and may be muscular discharges or possible myoclonus of subcortical origin.  No clear seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient has new onset seizures characterized by loss of consciousness, tongue biting.

As she transitions into drowsiness, there is bilateral anterior temporal slowing more in the left hemisphere than the right and is slightly more than expected for age.
Sleep was captured which was characterized by vertex waves and K complexes.
No spikes or sharp waves were noted.
Heart rate 66 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is mildly abnormal for age due to bilateral anterior temporal slowing which is slightly more than expected for age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings of bilateral anterior temporal slowing are nonspecific, may suggest underlying cardiovascular disease.  Clinical correlation is recommended.

Drowsiness was captured, which was characterized by slow rolling eye movements and some slowing of the record.
Photic stimulation and hyperventilation were performed.  Hyperventilation did not elicit any abnormal activity.  It was characterized by diffuse slowing.
Photic stimulation was performed, which showed good driving at all frequencies.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 44-year-old woman with epilepsy since age 9, last seizure was 1 week ago.  The patient reports seizures during sleep with tongue biting, increasingly frequent, 6 to 8 within the last 6 months.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The patient seems to be drowsy throughout much of the EEG, but in wakefulness there is excess beta and excess theta in a somewhat poorly organized record.  In the sharply contoured background, there is prominent frontal beta and as the patient becomes drowsy there is some paroxysmal high amplitude bursts, but no definitive frontal sharp waves or spikes.
Hyperventilation seems to accentuate the background slowing and there is a very subtle focality with perhaps a bit more left-sided focal slowing in hyperventilation compared to the right.
Photic stimulation is remarkable for generous beta, but a driving response.  Heart rate is 60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG in wakefulness and sleep due to:
Somewhat disorganized pattern for age.
Excess beta.
Excess theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The excess beta could be due to medication effect or anxiety.  The excess theta suggests a bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function.  It is important to have a complete list of this patient's medications.  No definitive sharp waves or spikes were seen.  A more prolonged study capturing sleep may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 34-year-old woman with impaired cognitive thinking processes and progressive left-sided numbness.
MEDICATIONS:  Dyazide.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  The technologist noted that this patient seemed to have stable cognition throughout the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a low voltage 10 Hz alpha rhythm in the background with generous low voltage beta.  The patient seemed to be a bit drowsy, transitioning into stage I sleep with an increase in beta and in vertex waves followed by arousal.  Hyperventilation did not significantly active the record.  In fact, the patient seemed to be falling asleep at the end of hyperventilation with beta spindles characteristic of stage II sleep.  Other features of sleep included vertex waves and more subtle POSTS.  Sustained stage II sleep was more abundant in those vertex waves, K complexes, and POSTS were noted.
The patient remained drowsy throughout photic stimulation which nonetheless, elicited a driving response.  By the end of photic stimulation, she was drifting back into stage II sleep.
Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  This patient appears to be extremely sleepy.  Clinical correlation for hypersomnolence may be appropriate, but a sleep-deprived EEG could also produce these findings.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 58-year-old female with episodes of seizure-like activity.  When she tried to get up, had shaking of left arms followed by shaking of her right upper and lower extremities for a minute.  This was followed by post event confusion for 5 minutes.
PAST MEDICAL HISTORY:  Significant for diabetes, hypertension, and cervical stenosis.
MEDICATIONS:  Includes Keppra, Motrin, and insulin.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with addition of T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 9-10 Hz in frequency seen in the occipital region, which attenuated with eye opening.  There was presence of low-amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which was distributed symmetrically.  There were occasional bursts of focal slowing in the left anterior and mid temporal region consisting of 2.5-3 Hz delta frequency lasting for 1-2 seconds.  Drowsiness was characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact.  No epileptiform activity or seizures captured in this study.  Heart rate was 60 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through drowsiness due to occasional bursts of focal slowing in the left anterior and mid temporal regions during wakefulness and drowsiness.  No epileptiform abnormalities were identified in this recording.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Focal slowing in the left hemisphere suggestive of a structural abnormality in the left hemisphere or left temporal dysfunction.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were seen in this recording.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or of intermittent seizures.  If seizures are a clinical concern, a repeat sleep-deprived EEG or a 24-hour video EEG monitoring may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 20-year-old female with 2 episodes of seizure-like activity.  It is described as a screaming episode followed by tonic posturing of the left extremities.  The patient has brakes and electrodes may not be in accurate place.

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with the additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state for the short period of time during this recording, the posterior dominant rhythm was 8.5-9 Hz in frequency  in the occipital region which attenuates with eye opening.  There is presence of generalized beta activity with symmetrical distribution.  Drowsiness, stage 1 and stage 2 sleep are predominant features of this recording and are characterized by disappearance of the posterior dominant rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves, posts, K complexes, and sleep spindles.  This is a low amplitude EEG.  Hyperventilation results in no significant change in the background activity.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in no driving response.  Heart rate was at 80 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness for a short period of time through stage 2 sleep for most part of this recording.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were identified in this recording.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Generalized beta activity could be due to medication effect including benzodiazepine, barbiturates, or could be due to anxiety or hyperthyroidism.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were seen in this recording.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are of clinical concern, a repeat EEG when patient is more awake is recommended.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status, probable seizure.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This 52-year-old lady presents with change in mental status.  She had a seizure in the ED with left upper extremity shaking, right eye twitching, unresponsiveness.
PAST MEDICAL HISTORY:  Diabetes, hypertension, asthma, dementia, dyslipidemia, depression, right thalamic stroke, ambulatory dysfunction, hirsutism.

Photic stimulation was performed which did not bring about a change in the record.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Bifrontal slowing in the delta range was noted almost continuously.  The slowing was more prominent in the F3 and F4 regions.
There were rare F4 sharp waves seen.

Bifrontal F3 and F4 continuous focal slowing.
Rare F4 sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures arising from the right frontal region.  The bifrontal slowing indicates a possible underlying structural abnormality in these areas.  Clinical correlation recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 52-year-old male with hepatitis C, tuberculosis and alcohol withdrawal seizures.  Multiple recurrent hospitalizations for seizures, recently on the inpatient service in February 2013, for recurrent seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 67-year-old male with post traumatic epilepsy, admitted with repetitive seizures and prolonged postictal delirium.  The family states that the patient usually has a postictal right hemiparesis.  Past history of significant traumatic brain injury.  The patient states that he does not take his seizure medication.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Just prior to the EEG, the patient was quite somnolent, but he became more awake as the EEG began.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Background EEG is diffusely slow with primarily a theta pattern.  There is an asymmetry noted, initially with a bit slower theta-delta on the left and a bit faster frequency activity of theta on the right.  The patient drifts in and out of a drowsy state.  He is not able to cooperate with hyperventilation.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is some sharply contoured slowing noted in the right anterior temporal region.
Photic stimulation did not significantly activate the record.  Heart rate 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Excess theta.
An asymmetry with a slower background on the left.
Rare sharply contoured slowing in the right frontotemporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient with a history of traumatic brain injury and  asymmetry described above may be related to both the parenchymal pathology and the injury to the cranium.  No seizures were recorded.  Of note, the patient was a bit more awake at the end of the EEG, compatible with a resolving postictal state.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 61-year-old right-handed lady presenting with left arm and face numbness and weakness of 1 day duration.  She was found to have a subcortical CVA on CT scan of the head.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, acetaminophen, heparin, labetalol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement and one channel of EKG.  Wakefulness and sleep were captured.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a posterior dominant rhythm of 9-10 Hz frequency which is symmetric on both sides and reactive to eye opening.  There is a good anterior and posterior gradient.  There is some shifting slowing as the patient drifts into sleep.  Stage 2 sleep was achieved which was characterized by vertex waves, K complexes and spindles.  There was a wicket rhythm noted in stage 2 sleep.  As the recording progresses there are F7 sharp waves and rare T1 sharp waves which were identified as not being a part of the wicket rhythm.
Photic stimulation was performed which elicited a spiky driving response.
There was excessive theta in early drowsiness and right focal slowing as she became drowsy.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Excessive theta in early drowsiness.
Right focal slowing during drowsiness.
F7, T1 sharp waves in stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The left anterior temporal sharp waves are suggestive of a possible underlying epileptogenic process in the left anterior temporal region.  Clinical correlation is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 54-year-old female with history of hypertension, CHF, and status post cardiac pacemaker who presents for seizure-like activity occurred about a month ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Spiriva, simvastatin, aspirin, levothyroxine, lisinopril, lorazepam, Zanaflex, and isosorbide.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 8.5-9 Hz in frequency seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is 6.5-7 Hz diffuse theta activity seen during wakefulness, which is distributed symmetrically.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Drowsiness is characterized by disappearance of the posterior dominant rhythm slowing of the background and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in a driving response.  Heart rate was 80 beats per minute with pacemaker rhythm.
IMPRESSION:  This is this is an abnormal EEG recording due to diffuse slowing of the background with theta activity seen during wakefulness.  There is no epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were captured.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings could be due to metabolic, toxic, hypoxic, or infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to the effect of sedating medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunction or degenerative brain disease.  No epileptiform abnormalities are identified in this record.  No seizures were captured.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.  If clinically indicated, a repeat EEG capturing deeper stages of sleep or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 70-year-old found unresponsive in her kitchen, suffered a generalized tonic-clonic seizure of 30 seconds' duration en route to hospital.  Eyes deviated to the right.  Past left MCA infarct.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Versed, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was relatively somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a pattern with diffuse beta and bursts of spindles.  In addition, there is arrhythmic delta activity and the beta drops out for a burst of arrhythmic delta activity.  The arrhythmic delta activity is somewhat more remarkable on the right, and there is subtle underlying sharply contoured slowing in the right posterior occipital region as well as a bit more attenuation of faster frequency activity on the right relative to the left.  Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in rhythmic theta.  As the recording continues, the background EEG is richer in both beta and theta.  The initial asymmetry is a bit less prominent.
Heart rate 72 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a dynamic but abnormal EEG due to:
Initial markedly slow pattern with intermittent paroxysmal beta.
At the end of the record, the EEG remains quite slow, but there is an increase in beta and a decrease in the arrhythmic delta activity.
An asymmetry with a bit more arrhythmic delta activity in the right posterior quadrant.
Some sharply contoured slowing in the right posterior quadrant.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The postictal state and the use of sedative hypnotic medications may play a role in the marked background slowing and the beta in this record.  No seizures were recorded.  The arrhythmic delta activity may be correlated with imaging.  If seizures are an important consideration, a repeat tracing is suggested, given the sharply contoured slowing described above.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 24-year-old male admitted with 3 tonic-clonic seizures which began with shaking of the left arm and mouth and then went on to convulsive activity, followed by obtundation.
MEDICATIONS:  Vimpat, Keppra, benzodiazepines, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing began, the patient is in ICU and is very confused and moving about.  The background EEG is markedly abnormal with primarily a theta pattern, poorly organized with generous background beta.  In addition, there are sharp waves noted in the record with more than one localization including C3 and the right temporal region.  There is prominent theta noted in the background.
A burst of right temporal sharp waves and delta was noted at 2:35 but without a clear clinical correlate.  This burst continues as might be anticipated in an electrographic seizure but looking at the video the patient does not appear to be doing anything other than motion arrest.  There is no significant change in the patient's behavior after this 30-second discharge.  Additional bursts of right temporal sharp waves and spikes maximum in the anterior temporal region were noted at 2:47.  At the close of the EEG, the right temporal sharp waves are building up.  They have not yet evolved into the pattern of a seizure.  Of note, the patient has turned his head to the left but testing is not performed and it is difficult to determine if there is really a change in the patient's mental status.  The patient is confused but interactive throughout the EEG.
Heart rate 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Marked background slowing and disorganization.
Prominent right anterior temporal sharp waves and spikes.
At least 1 electrographic seizure from the right temporal region.
Sharp waves noted on occasion from the left hemisphere as well.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In this individual who has had recent, repetitive seizures, this is an ongoing ictal record although it does not meet the formal criteria for a status epilepticus record and the seizure that was recorded appeared to be with little clinical signs or symptoms and was brief.
Additional EEG recording was initiated on the evening of the 16th.

Slowing of the alpha rhythm.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using a standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 9-10 Hz in frequency, 60-70 microvolt in amplitude seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  The stage I sleep is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact, as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and posts.  The stage II sleep is characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles.  Hyperventilation results in symmetric slowing of the background.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response.  Heart rate is 55 beats per minutes and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through stage II sleep.  No epileptiform abnormalities were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are clinical concern, a repeat EEG capturing deeper stages of sleep or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.  Note that the heart rate was 55 and patient was bradycardic.

Features of drowsiness include anterior spread of the alpha rhythm. Deeper stages of sleep were not sustained.  Posterior slow waves of youth were noted in wakefulness.  Although deeper stages of sleep were not achieved, just as the patient was becoming drowsy there seems to be some subtle underlying 4-5 Hz theta in the left occipital region.
Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.
Photic stimulation elicited a bilateral driving response.
Heart:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  A very subtle abnormality was noted in this EEG just as the patient was becoming drowsy and included some focal theta in the left occipital parietal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  For this individual with a history of early developmental pathology and possible meningitis, these findings may relate to that premorbid process.  The findings were seen in a very
restricted section of the EEG.  If there is any questions, additional EEG recording may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 38-year-old gentleman with left craniectomy due to gunshot.  He returned from operating room this morning with seizure activity, treated with Ativan.  There is no T1 and T2 electrodes due to skull defect.
MEDICATIONS:  Fentanyl, midazolam, morphine, Ativan, Keppra, and Zofran.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  There is no T1 and T2 electrodes due to his skull defect.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  In the sedated state, there is diffuse slowing of the background consisting of delta activity, 2-3 Hz frequency, most pronounced on the left side.  There is intermittent alpha activity with a frequency of 8-9 Hz, lasting for 1-2 seconds, most pronounced in frontotemporal region.  There is hemispheric asymmetry characterized by higher amplitude in left hemispheric regions, most pronounced in the frontotemporal areas.  There is slowing of the background activity in delta range with a frequency of 2-3 Hz almost continuously.  There is spontaneous variability seen with increase in background frequency.  There is also reactivity to stimulation.  There is no epileptiform activity or clinical seizures noted during this recording.  Heart rate was 100 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Diffuse slowing of the background activity in delta and theta range intermixed with intermittent alpha activity.
Focal slowing and breach in left cerebral hemisphere, most pronounced in frontotemporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings are suggestive of metabolic, toxic, hypoxic, or infectious encephalopathy or due to the effect of sedating medications.  Left focal slowing is indicative of focal structural dysfunction in the left cerebral hemisphere, most pronounced in frontotemporal region.  Breach rhythm is consistent with a history of left craniectomy.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or of intermittent seizures.

Diffuse slowing of the background with theta activity seen in wakefulness and slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 79-year-old female with recent left MCA stroke, on warfarin with change in mental status with abrupt onset.

MEDICATIONS:  Levetiracetam, Norvasc, terazosin, labetalol, aspirin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 8.5 to 9 Hz performed in the right occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is hemispheric asymmetry, which is characterized by left hemispheric attenuation and slowing with loss of faster frequencies.  There is also almost continuous left temporal delta activity maximal at T3/T1 during this recording.  There are occasional sharp wave discharges noted at T3/C3/T5 with no evolution or electrographic seizures.  There is excess theta activity during wakefulness.  Stage I and stage II sleep were characterized by disappearance of the posterior dominant rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact, as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and posts and also K complexes and sleep spindles.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in an asymmetric driving response, most pronounced on the right side.  Heart rate was 60 and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to;
Left hemispheric asymmetry characterized by slowing, attenuation, and loss of faster frequencies.
Almost continuous left temporal delta activity, maximal at T3 and T1.
Occasional sharp wave discharges noted at C3/T3/T5.
Excess theta activity during wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Left hemispheric asymmetry characterized by loss of faster frequencies and attenuation could be due to a history of left MCA ischemic stroke.  Continuous left temporal delta activity in left temporal region could be due to structural abnormalities in the left temporal area or left temporal dysfunction.  The sharp wave discharges in left parietal, central, and temporal region are indicative of irritability of cerebral cortex in this area and place this patient at higher risk for partial seizures.  Diffuse excess theta activity is suggestive of toxic, metabolic, degenerative, infectious, or ischemic encephalopathy.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  There were no electrographic seizures or clinical seizures noted during this recording.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  58-year-old man with bifrontal bur holes and evacuation of subdural hematomas with change in mental status, with the wife noting that he is lip smacking and staring but never returned to baseline.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Keppra, Vimpat.
INTRODUCTION:  A long-term EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  Patient was recorded while lethargic.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Continuous spike wave detection as well as seizure detection software as well as patient notes and nurse's notes and patient alarms were used to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  Overall, the recording appears to be mainly in the delta frequencies with some intermittent faster frequencies showing up periodically.  There are some stage changes noted.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen continuously at T5/P3 with a periodicity that ranges from 0.5 Hz to 2 Hz, at times becoming slightly less organized.  These are consistent with periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLEDs).
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-40 mV.
SEIZURES:  Although there were about 2-3 rhythmic runs of the PLEDs, there were 2 electrographic seizures.  One occurred at 4:15 p.m. lasting for a minute and a half.  The 2nd one occurred at 9:43 p.m.  Both of them did not appear to have any clear clinical correlate.  They were comprised of rhythmic P3-4/T5 sharp waves, evolving in frequency and amplitude and then suddenly stopping.
HEART RATE:  84.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left posterior temporal and parietal periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLEDs) and electrographic seizures in addition to generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals left posterior temporal and parietal seizures as well as a focus of irritability and cerebral dysfunction in that region.  This is likely related to the known lesion in that region.  In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral  dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology and may be due at least in part to medication effect.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 65-year-old male with history of recent onset dementia and forgetfulness.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are completed.

There is a small amount of low amplitude frontal central beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  The background activity is characterized by delta activity with a frequency of 1.8-2.5 Hz frontally predominant delta activity intermixed with 5-6 Hz theta activity. RECORD START TIME:  11:59 a.m.
RECORD FINISH TIME:  12:21 p.m.
RECORDING LENGTH:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 58-year-old female with a history of epilepsy since age 11.  Her seizures occur more frequently now and are largely nocturnal.
MEDICATIONS:  Diazepam, divalproex and zonisamide.
INTRODUCTION:  __________
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the record opens, there is a well-formed and symmetric 9 to 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm that is reactive to eye opening.  There is a small amount of frontocentral beta activity identified which is symmetrically distributed.  Stage 1 sleep is characterized by attenuation and fragmentation of the existing posterior dominant rhythm and the appearance of central theta activity.  Stage 2 sleep is not appreciated.
On at least 4 occasions during the record, there is the appearance of spike and wave discharges.  On at least 2 of these occasions, the discharges appear generalized with a bifrontal maximum.  These appear during periods of light drowsiness.  For approximately 3 to 4 seconds, there is a disruption of the background and the appearance of bihemispheric slowing superimposed upon which there is a sharply contoured activity.  There is, however, a definitive bifrontal generalized spike.  Later in the recording, there is a similar brief background slowing, and there is again bifrontal generalized spike and wave discharges.  These discharges are singleton events and thus it is difficult to determine what their frequency is.  On the third appearance, the spike wave discharges appears predominantly over the left frontal region and is maximal at FT7.  This discharge has the appearance more consistent with a localized focal spike in the left frontal region.
Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed in multiple flash frequencies and did not induce a significant photic driving response.  Of note, a photoparoxysmal response was not identified.  During the course of the recording, the heart rate varied between 70 and 90 beats.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG capturing wakefulness and drowsiness due to the presence of generalized bifrontal spike and wave discharges and a focal left frontal spike and wave discharge.
CLINICAL IMPRESSION:  The presence of bifrontal generalized spike-wave discharges may suggest an idiopathic generalized epilepsy in this patient.  The appearance of a focal spike in the left frontal region may suggest fragmentation of the generalized pattern during drowsiness but may also suggest the concomitant appearance of a generalized process plus a localized process, such as may be seen in __________ epilepsy or possibly in generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus (GEFS+).  Clinical correlation is advised.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In a lethargic state, the background activity is characterized by a generalized slowing in the delta and theta-frequency range. There is hemispheric asymmetry characterized by attenuation and slowing in right cerebral hemisphere. There is a excess theta activity well formed in left cerebral hemisphere.  There are intermittent delta activity, beta seen with a frequency of 1 to 1.2 Hz lasting for 2-3 seconds.  There are intermittent sharp waves arising from the left parietal-occipital regions most pronounced in P3 with field spread to C3 and O1, occasionally intermixed with the burst of left parieto-temporal slowing. IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Diffuse slowing of the background activity.
Presence of theta burst.
Attenuation of the background activity in the right cerebral hemisphere.
Left parieto-occipital sharp wave discharges with no evolution, intermixed with temporoparietal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Diffuse slowing of the background activity could be due to toxic, metabolic, hypoxic, infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to sedating medications or cerebral dysfunction or degenerative brain disease.  The theta burst could also be due to increased intracranial pressure, metabolic encephalopathy, or deep midline lesions in the brain.  Right hemispheric attenuation of the background could be due to right subdural hematoma.  The presence of intermittent sharp wave discharges in the left parieto-occipital region is suggestive of underlying epileptogenicity of that region and place this patient at higher risk for partial seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  39-year-old woman with episode of bilateral arm stiffness and gaze deviated to the right.  Has 4-5 seizures in the past month, screaming, with a history of Lennox-Gastaut, mental retardation.  Follow-up EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Ativan, famotidine, Lovenox, topiramate, Flagyl, Depakote.
INTRODUCTION:  A long-term EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement with the addition of anterior temporal single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while unresponsive.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Continuous spike wave detection as well as seizure detection software in addition to nurse's notes were used to review the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm and frontocentral beta.  Overall, there are theta delta mixed frequencies intermingled with multiple multifocal spikes which I will describe in Abnormal Discharges.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Multifocal spikes seen at O1, O2, T6, Fp1, Fp2, T3, and P4.  However, the spikes are mainly seen at O1 and O2 and Fp1/Fp2.
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts seen almost continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  During the record, there are multiple seizures which in the EEG appear to begin suddenly and display rhythmic, sharply contoured theta intermixed with beta that at times appears to be maximal frontally and then centrally with an overlying rhythmic occipital sharp focus.  The maximal focus or origin of the seizure is unclear.  It is also atypical as it does not appear to evolve as it suddenly starts, remains in the EEG at almost this irregular but continuous frequency, and then appears to slowly dissipate.  During these discharges, the patient appears to move her head side to side and sometimes moves her arms in a wild fashion.  On 1 occasion, her mouth appeared to twitch in the video.  The duration of these episodes can be anywhere from 1 or 2 minutes to prolonged 38-minute seizure.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to multiple seizures with unclear origin and multifocal spikes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of multiple generalized seizures with unclear origin as well as multiple areas of irritability and structural dysfunction as well as diffuse dysfunction consistent with diagnosis of symptomatic generalized epilepsy.
These findings were communicated to the primary team as soon as the EEG was read.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is an 81-year-old male with fever and change of mental status.  No other clinical information available.
MEDICATIONS:  Cardizem, Reglan, vancomycin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was relatively somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a slow, mixed frequency pattern with theta and delta.  There are frontally predominant triphasic waves.  There are also some slow periodic complexes that appear in the right posterior quadrant more so than the left.  Stimulation of the patient produces a clear alerting response with a bit more fast theta frequency activity and a suggestion of a 6 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  When the patient drifts off to sleep, the EEG becomes more significantly slow with more rhythmic slow mixed theta delta.
Heart rate irregular 72 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
Marked background slowing.
Frontally predominant triphasic waves.
Occasional posteriorly predominant periodic complexes seen primarily on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Overall, this EEG is most suggestive of a toxic or metabolic pattern.  The triphasic waves improve with tactile stimulation and the patient shows a clear alerting with stimulation.  If seizures are an important consideration, additional EEG recording may be of value if this patient is thought to have seizures, particularly as  there is a right posterior periodic complex noted intermittently.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 67-year-old woman with stroke and aphasia.  The patient has limited motor deficits, but significant aphasia.  The clinical team noted that the patient speaks occasionally but never on rounds.
MEDICATIONS:  Insulin, aspirin, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was not possible due to the patient's mental status, but photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates continuous focal slowing from the left hemisphere, some of which is sharply contoured with a phase reversal at T1.  There are T1 sharp waves noted intermittently.  The field of focal slowing is relatively diffuse throughout the left hemisphere, and there is disruption of the alpha rhythm.  In wakefulness, the right hemisphere demonstrates a well-formed alpha rhythm.
Features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing.  Early stage I sleep was identified with limited vertex waves.  Of note, as the patient transitions to sleep, there is less in the way of rhythmic sharply contoured slowing.  Photic stimulation produces a driving response on the right but not the left.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to prominent, rhythmic slowing with sharp waves, really seen primarily in wakefulness on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There were no clear clinical correlates for the features described above.  There are brief transitions into stage II sleep for this individual, although sleep was not sustained, but the majority of the sharply contoured slowing and rhythmic slowing is seen in wakefulness.  Ongoing monitoring is essential.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 27-year-old woman with a history of seizures for 10 years.  She describes the seizures of 4 kinds. INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Both hypoventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of polymorphic moderate amplitude 10.5-11 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening. There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  Both slow and fast alpha variant are captured.  Diffuse excess beta is observed.
During sleep symmetrical vertex waves, sleep spindles, K-complexes and POSTS (positive occipital sharp transient of sleep) are captured.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and produces mild diffuse background slowing.
Step photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.  No focal slowing or epileptiform discharges are captured.  A regular heart rate is noted on a single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:
Stage II sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
Excess beta.
Fast and slow alpha variant.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and sleep 25-minute EEG.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Excess beta could be secondary to medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 55-year-old male with chronic kidney disease, lupus, admitted in respiratory failure with atrial fibrillation now with intermittent jerking activity.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Ativan, fentanyl.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This was a technical difficult bedside record in a critically ill patient who was receiving treatments during the EEG and awaiting dialysis.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly slow but continuous and lacks the typical hallmarks of either an awake or asleep individual in this obtunded patient.  There is primarily rhythmic theta with some arrhythmic delta.  Although this is a technically challenging record with perhaps some attenuation in the electrodes in the right temporal region, there is an occasional right occipital temporal sharp wave noted in the background.  No clinical jerking of the extremities is seen with the jerking.  Finally, predominant triphasic waves were noted as was shifting slowing in this overall slow record.  Intermittent attenuations were noted.
Towards the close of the record, intermittent jerking was noted.  On some occasions this was associated with movement artifact, on other occasions attenuation and on other occasions the jerkiness is associated with an overall attenuation of the background.
Heart rate:  120 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background with primarily a theta frequency background.
Shifting slowing.
Triphasic waves.
A right occipital sharp wave.
Intermittent attenuation of the background which was sometimes associated with jerking of the body or limbs.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptic seizures were identified.  Overall, the pattern described above is one more commonly seen in the context of metabolic encephalopathy as described above.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  26 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 59-year-old gentleman with a history of schizophrenia who presents with altered mental status and at least 2 episodes of tonic posturing with decreased responsiveness in the setting of ingesting Vicks VapoRub.
MEDICATIONS:  Lovenox, Ativan 1 mg at 6:00 a.m. and several mgs on 01/13/2013.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode with a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  There is right-to-left interhemispheric asymmetry with slower wave forms observed over the left hemisphere.  The background consists of a mixture of diffuse beta, theta, and delta activity.  Additional polymorphic often sharply contoured delta is observed over the left hemisphere, primarily over the left temporal region.  Several electrographic seizures are captured in this recording.  Seizures have abrupt onset without clear localization or lateralization.  Electrographically diffuse EMG artifact is observed.  Once the EMG artifact resolves generalized sharply contoured approximately 3 Hz rhythmic delta activity is observed diffusely, but it is higher in amplitude over the left hemisphere.  This activity increases in amplitude and decreases in frequency to approximately 2 Hz and often evolves into another episode of generalized EMG artifact that obscures the recording.  Once that EMG artifact resolves, rhythmic sharply contoured 3-4 Hz delta activity is often observed over the left temple region.
Clinically it appears that the patient moans and slobbers at the onset of seizure and has decreased responsiveness during the seizure.
FINDINGS:
Focal status epilepticus.
Excess beta.
Left hemispheric slowing most pronounced over the left temporal region.
Mild to moderate diffuse slowing.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 26-minute electroencephalogram due to diffuse slowing, focal left hemispheric slowing that is most pronounced over the left temporal region and multiple focal left temporal electrographic seizures without returning back to baseline.  Diffuse background slowing indicates etiologically nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  Focal left hemispheric slowing that is most pronounced over the temporal region indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, and in this case, could partially be to related post-ictal phenomenon.  Multiple electrographic and clinical seizures captured during the recording are consistent with focal status epilepticus.  These findings were conveyed to the Neurology consult team at the time of the recording.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  27 minutes.

Stimulation of the patient produced a brief arousal with an increase in alpha frequency activity but wakefulness was not sustained.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  Approximately 2 hours.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 51-year-old woman with a history of metastatic breast cancer who now presents with subacute change in mental status in the setting of fevers.  EEG is performed to rule out clinical seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Keppra, and antibiotics.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrode.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  A single EKG lead was used, as well.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  There is right to left interhemispheric asymmetry with slower waveforms at lower amplitudes over the left hemisphere.  The background consists of polymorphic low to moderate amplitude, mixture of theta and delta activity and abundant triphasic wave forms while the patient is awake.  By the end of the recording, the patient appears asleep; however, no normal sleep architecture is captured.  There are no clear epileptiform discharges or electrographic seizures.
FINDINGS:
Moderate diffuse slowing.
Focal left hemispheric slowing and voltage attenuation.
Abundant triphasic wave forms.
No electrographic seizures.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 2-hour continuous video EEG due to moderate diffuse slowing, focal left hemispheric slowing at lower voltages, and abundant triphasic wave forms.  These findings indicate nonspecific cerebral dysfunction that is moderate in degree and at least partially related to toxic metabolic disturbances.  Focal slowing an attenuation over the left hemisphere indicates left hemispheric dysfunction that could be structural in etiology.  Triphasic wave forms are seen in nonspecific encephalopathy.  There were no clear electrographic seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 46-year-old woman with a history of intracranial bleed in 09/2011 status post craniotomy.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Maximal wakefulness is achieved by the end of the recording.  During maximal wakefulness, the posterior dominant rhythm consists of 7 to 8 Hz theta activity.  The anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient is weak.  The majority of the recording is captured during sleep.  Abundant sleep spindles are captured.  There is intermittent asymmetry of sleep spindles.  This asymmetry is independent and bilateral and is most prominent posteriorly.  No clear epileptiform discharges are captured.  Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation does not result in additional abnormalities.
FINDINGS:
Mild diffuse slowing.
Independent bilateral asymmetry of sleep spindles, most prominent posteriorly.  No clear epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and asleep 22-minute EEG, due to mild diffuse slowing and asymmetry of sleep architecture, most pronounced posteriorly.  Mild diffuse slowing indicates etiologically nonspecific mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  Asymmetry of sleep architecture could be secondary to underlying focal pathology, and in this case could be consistent with the patient's history of prior intracerebral hemorrhage and surgery.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

EEG LENGTH:  23 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 57-year-old woman with a history of recent left MCA distribution ischemic stroke, who is scheduled to undergo left CEA tomorrow on 01/03/2013.
MEDICATIONS:  Nystatin, Lovenox, and Protonix.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to a standard 10-20 system with a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed. Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is a significant right-to-left interhemispheric asymmetry with slower wave forms at higher amplitudes over the left hemisphere.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the right hemisphere reaches 9 to 9.5 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  Additionally, there is an anterior-to-posterior frequency MCA gradient observed over the right hemisphere.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the left hemisphere is very unstable and reaches maximum about 8 Hz and it does not appear to attenuate with eyes opening.  There is no AP gradient over the left hemisphere.  Additionally, there is continuous polymorphic theta and delta observed over the left hemisphere.  Occasionally brief bursts of diffuse frontally predominant rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA) is captured.  This activity is higher in amplitude over the left hemisphere.  During drowsiness bursts of theta and delta activity seen over the right hemisphere and frequency of FIRDA increases.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation does not result in additional abnormalities.
FINDINGS:
Continuous moderate left hemispheric slowing.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and drowsy 23-minute EEG due to continuous moderate left hemispheric slowing.  This finding indicates a focal left hemispheric dysfunction, likely structural in etiology, and in this patient is consistent with a history of recent left MCA territory infarct.

Intermittent attenuations of suppressions.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  Epilepsy since age 7 admitted with 3 seizures on 01/18/2013 with generalized shaking and/or right sided shaking lasting 1-2 minutes.

The technologist attempts to obtain the patient's cooperation with little success.  Arousals produce eye opening.  The patient then drifts off to sleep.  On one or 2 occasions there is a suggestion of an 8 Hz alpha rhythm before he drifts off to sleep.  POSTS were noted in sleep.

IMPRESSION:  This is a technically challenging bedside EEG, but it is within normal limits, primarily in sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  Subtle focal features could be overlooked given the patient's positioning.  The hypersomnolence is an anticipated finding after seizures and a repeat study when the patient is able to come to the lab may be helpful in characterizing epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 35-year-old right-handed man with a history of migraines, presents with sharp pain in the back of his head, and eyes lasting all day.  He denies any seizure activity for the past 2 months.
MEDICATIONS:  Phenytoin, Topamax, and Bactrim.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm, 9.5-10 Hz of which in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is low amplitude diffuse beta-activity, which is distributed symmetrically, stage 1 sleep is characterized by disappearance of alpha rhythm, slowing of the background and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact, as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and posts and stage 2 sleep is characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles.  Hyperventilation results in symmetrical slowing of the background, and photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response.  Heart rate is 80 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.  No epileptiform abnormalities were identified in this recording.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy if seizures are a clinical concern, a repeat EEG or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.  The presence of diffuse beta-activity is indicated of anxiety or hyperthyroidism or it could be due to barbiturate or benzodiazepines.  Clinical correlation is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 58-year-old left-handed gentleman with history of seizure-like activity.  He had 4 episodes since 2004, last episode was on 01/13/2013, described as a weakness episode as bloody shaking, foaming at the mouth, and tongue biting.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel EKG.  Photic stimulation and hyperventilation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 9-10 Hz in frequency seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude, frontocentral beta activity which is distributed symmetrically.  Drowsiness is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm and slowing of the background and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact.  Hyperventilation results in symmetric slowing of the background activity.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response.  Heart rate was 55-60 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording, capturing wakefulness through drowsiness.  No epileptiform abnormalities are identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are a clinical concern, a repeat EEG capturing deeper stages of sleep or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 33-year-old woman with possible seizures, post traumatic stress disease, asthma, anxiety, hypothyroid, depression, chronic pain syndrome.  Now complains of worsening, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, and frequent falling with lightheadedness.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  This was an awake and sleep record in a patient who is quite sleepy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, throughout much of the record the background EEG is a bit slow with a 7 Hz alpha rhythm, but on rare occasions the alpha rhythm reaches 9 Hz.  The patient frequently transitions in and out of sleep with slowing of the background rhythm, hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing, and an increase in beta.  POSTS are identified in stage 1 sleep with vertex waves and spindles noted in stage 2 sleep.
Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.
Heart rate:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This adult appears to be excessively sedated or sleep deprived, but when maximally awake the alpha does achieve 9 Hz.  No epileptiform features were identified.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 34-year-old with recurrent spells in which he becomes unaware of his environment and is disoriented.  The patient is amnestic for the spells.  Has 2 syncopal spells as well which he did recall.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were both completed.

Hyperventilation did not activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.
Heart rate 96-104 BPM.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 72-year-old woman found confused on the floor with bladder and bowel incontinence, with hypertension, diabetes, chronic renal disease on hemodialysis, history of DVT and PE.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, morphine, lorazepam.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during lethargy.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Spike wave detection, seizure detection software, patient events and nurses notes were all used to review the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.  Overall, the background consists of mainly delta frequency at 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts seen diffusely with intermittent bursts of theta.  Sometimes the patient arouses and there is some diffuse muscle artifact seen.  In addition, there is frequent triphasic waves which appear to be bifrontal predominant symmetric at times seen more rhythmically at 1 Hz.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slow waves described above and triphasics.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to moderate to severe generalized slowing in addition to triphasic waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction which may be due at least in part to metabolic effect or a metabolic disturbance.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 68-year-old with generalized weakness, COPD, and tonic clonic seizure.
MEDICATIONS:  Tylenol, metoprolol, Klonopin, and oxycodone.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation are performed.  Hyperventilation was deferred in this patient with cardiopulmonary disease.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm reaching 50 microvolts with 10 Hz low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Frequent muscle artifact was noted.  Very brief drowsiness was characterized by a decrease in muscle artifact, attenuation of the alpha rhythm, and an increase in theta.  Rare lambda was noted in wakefulness with rare POSTS noted in sleep.  Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
Heart rate:  96 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  The general theta described above may be related to this patient's benzodiazepine use.  If additional information is needed, a follow-up study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested.
